window.CONTENT["4911"] = {"meta":{"id":"4911","code":"COMP 4911","name":"Developing Enterprise Service","exam":"2026-04-20T10:30:00-07:00","room":"SW05 2875","format":"Final Exam — MCQ + T/F + Short Answer + Essay + Code Annotation","instructor":"Bruce Link","notes_html":"\u003cp\u003eSource: study guide cover &quot;Mon Apr 20 · 10:30 · SW05 2875&quot;.\u003c/p\u003e"},"modules":[{"id":"ejb","name":"EJB — session beans","topics":[{"id":"4911-ejb-intro","name":"EJB Intro","tags":["ejb","tech"],"prose":"Cards covering EJB Intro.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What are the three types of EJB components?","answer":"1. **Session Beans** (business logic — stateless, stateful, singleton)\n2. **Message-Driven Beans** (async JMS consumers)\n3. **Entity Beans / JPA Entities** (persistent objects)","explanation":"EJB 3.x groups server-side components into three families by *what they do*. **Session beans** hold\nyour service-layer methods (think \"place an order\"). **MDBs** are async JMS consumers triggered by\na message on a queue/topic. **Entity/JPA** classes describe rows in the database. The container\ninjects, pools, secures and transaction-wraps all three — you only write the annotated class.","example":"```java\n@Stateless public class OrderService { public void placeOrder(Order o) { ... } }  // session\n@MessageDriven public class OrderMDB implements MessageListener { ... }            // MDB\n@Entity public class Order { @Id Long id; ... }                                    // JPA entity\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What services does the EJB container provide?","answer":"1. Transaction management\n2. Security\n3. Instance pooling\n4. Concurrency\n5. Persistence context management\n6. Resource injection (JNDI/ENC)\n7. Lifecycle callbacks\n8. Interceptors\n9. Remote invocation","explanation":"The restaurant-in-a-mall analogy: the container is the mall — it supplies the boring plumbing\n(threads, TXs, security, DB pools, JNDI, crash recovery) so your bean class only has to hold the\n*business* logic. Every cross-cutting concern listed here is declaratively triggered by an\nannotation (`@TransactionAttribute`, `@RolesAllowed`, `@PersistenceContext`, `@EJB`, etc.), not\nby you writing the plumbing by hand.","example":"```java\n@Stateless\n@RolesAllowed(\"CLERK\")                    // security\npublic class OrderService {\n    @PersistenceContext EntityManager em; // persistence + injection\n    @TransactionAttribute(REQUIRED)       // TX management\n    public void place(Order o) { em.persist(o); }\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What annotation indicates the no-interface view for an EJB?","answer":"`@LocalBean` — allows clients to invoke the bean class directly without defining a business interface.","explanation":"Pre-EJB-3.1 you always needed a business interface (`@Local` or `@Remote`). **`@LocalBean`** means\n\"the bean class itself IS the view\" — clients just inject the bean type. It is implicit when the\nbean implements *no* interface; you only write `@LocalBean` explicitly to keep the no-interface\nview when you *also* add a `@Local` or `@Remote` interface.","example":"```java\n@Stateless\n@LocalBean                              // no-interface view\npublic class GreetingService {\n    public String hello() { return \"hi\"; }\n}\n\n// client:\n@EJB GreetingService svc;               // injected directly, no interface needed\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is the difference between @Local and @Remote?","answer":"`@Local` = same JVM (pass by reference, faster). `@Remote` = different JVMs (pass by value/serialized, network-accessible).","explanation":"`@Local` calls cross *no* process boundary, so arguments pass by reference — cheap, but any change\nthe callee makes is visible to the caller. `@Remote` calls go over RMI-IIOP, so every argument is\nserialized (pass-by-value), which is slower and demands `Serializable` types. Default to `@Local`\nunless a client actually lives in a different JVM.","example":"```java\n@Local  public interface OrderServiceLocal  { void place(Order o); }\n@Remote public interface OrderServiceRemote { void place(Order o); }\n\n@Stateless\npublic class OrderServiceBean implements OrderServiceLocal, OrderServiceRemote { ... }\n```"}]},{"id":"4911-session-beans","name":"Session Beans","tags":["session-beans","tech"],"prose":"Three distinct session bean flavors, each with different statefulness + concurrency semantics.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"A `@Stateless` session bean keeps \\_\\_\\_ client state between invocations.","answer":"**no** — the pool can hand any instance to any client; nothing is retained between calls.","explanation":"Think *fast-food counter*: any cashier takes any order, nobody remembers you. Because instances\nare interchangeable, the container pre-creates a pool and round-robins them — that's why SLSBs\nscale horizontally. Any instance field you set is effectively garbage once the method returns;\nif you *need* to remember something across calls, reach for `@Stateful` or a `@Singleton`.","example":"```java\n@Stateless\npublic class TaxCalc {\n    private BigDecimal lastTotal;            // DO NOT rely on this\n    public BigDecimal compute(Order o) { ... }\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"A `@Stateful` session bean holds \\_\\_\\_ state for the duration of one client's conversation.","answer":"**conversational** (per-client). Container pins one instance to one client; may passivate when idle.","explanation":"SFSB = *personal banker*: one dedicated instance per client for the whole conversation. Because\nit holds state, the container serializes the bean to disk (`@PrePassivate`) when idle and restores\nit (`@PostActivate`) on return — so all instance fields (and referenced objects) must be\n`Serializable`. The conversation ends when a method marked `@Remove` returns, the session times\nout, or the client explicitly discards the reference.","example":"```java\n@Stateful\npublic class ShoppingCart {\n    private List\u003cItem\u003e items = new ArrayList\u003c\u003e();\n    public void add(Item i) { items.add(i); }\n    @Remove public Order checkout() { ... }   // ends the conversation\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"A `@Singleton` session bean has \\_\\_\\_ instance(s) shared across the whole application.","answer":"**one**. All clients share it; concurrency is controlled by `@Lock(READ/WRITE)` or BEAN-managed.","explanation":"*Shared bulletin board in the office lobby* — one instance, every client reads from it. Because\nit is shared mutable state, the container serializes access via `@Lock` by default. Combine with\n`@Startup` (eager init at deploy) and `@DependsOn(\"OtherBean\")` (init order) for app-wide caches,\nconfiguration, counters, or `@Schedule`-based timers.","example":"```java\n@Singleton\n@Startup\n@DependsOn(\"ConfigBean\")\npublic class AppCache {\n    private final Map\u003cString,Object\u003e cache = new ConcurrentHashMap\u003c\u003e();\n    @Lock(READ)  public Object get(String k)         { return cache.get(k); }\n    @Lock(WRITE) public void put(String k, Object v) { cache.put(k, v); }\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is the SLSB lifecycle?","answer":"**Does Not Exist** → (newInstance + @PostConstruct) → **Method-Ready Pool** → (method invoked) → back to pool → (@PreDestroy) → **Does Not Exist**. *No passivation.*","explanation":"Only two real states: in the pool, or destroyed. Because no client state is retained, there's\nnothing to serialize — `@PrePassivate` and `@PostActivate` are *not* used on an SLSB. Use\n`@PostConstruct` for expensive one-time setup (cache a prepared statement, acquire a handle) and\n`@PreDestroy` for cleanup. Do not assume pool instances are destroyed between calls — they're\nreused.","example":"```java\n@Stateless\npublic class PricingService {\n    @PostConstruct void init()    { /* warm up once per instance */ }\n    @PreDestroy   void cleanup()  { /* release resources */ }\n    public BigDecimal price(Sku s){ ... }\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is the SFSB lifecycle?","answer":"Does Not Exist → (@PostConstruct) → **Method-Ready** → (timeout / inactivity: @PrePassivate) → **Passive** (serialized to disk) → (client call: @PostActivate) → Method-Ready → (@Remove / @PreDestroy / timeout) → Does Not Exist.","explanation":"SFSB is the only bean type that **passivates**, because it is the only one with per-client state\nworth preserving. Passivation = serialize to disk to free memory; activation = deserialize on next\nclient call. Because the JVM may serialize the bean, every non-transient field (and anything it\nreferences) must be `Serializable` — a common midterm trap is a non-serializable field causing\nsilent activation failures.","example":"```java\n@Stateful\npublic class BookingWizard implements Serializable {\n    private Date checkIn;                        // serializable\n    @PrePassivate void beforeIdle() { /* close connections */ }\n    @PostActivate void afterWake()  { /* reopen       */ }\n    @Remove public void finish() { }\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What annotation marks a method that ends the SFSB conversation?","answer":"`@Remove` on the method. After the method returns, the container removes the SFSB instance.","explanation":"`@Remove` is the conversational \"checkout\" — after the method returns normally, the container\ndiscards the instance, releasing the memory (and any pinned resources). If the method throws an\n*application* exception, you can set `@Remove(retainIfException=true)` to keep the bean alive so\nthe client can retry. `@Remove` is meaningless on SLSB or Singleton.","example":"```java\n@Stateful\npublic class Cart {\n    private List\u003cItem\u003e items = new ArrayList\u003c\u003e();\n    public void add(Item i) { items.add(i); }\n    @Remove public Order checkout() { return new Order(items); }   // bean goes away after return\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What annotation starts a singleton at deployment?","answer":"`@Startup` — tells container to instantiate singleton eagerly when the app deploys (not lazy on first call).","explanation":"Without `@Startup` a singleton is lazy — its `@PostConstruct` runs on the first business-method\ncall, which means the first user pays the init cost and any early init errors surface late. With\n`@Startup` it fires at deploy time, so config loading, cache warm-up, and timer registration\nhappen before any client can touch the app.","example":"```java\n@Singleton\n@Startup\npublic class AppConfig {\n    private Properties props;\n    @PostConstruct void load() { props = readFromDisk(); }   // runs at deploy\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is @DependsOn used for?","answer":"Specifies which other singletons must be initialized BEFORE this one. `@DependsOn(\"ConfigBean\")` ensures ConfigBean's @PostConstruct runs first.","explanation":"Useful with `@Startup` singletons when one singleton reads data that another singleton loads.\nWithout `@DependsOn` the container picks an arbitrary init order, so a `@PostConstruct` that\ntouches a not-yet-initialized peer will NPE. You may list multiple dependencies:\n`@DependsOn({\"ConfigBean\",\"MetricsBean\"})`.","example":"```java\n@Singleton @Startup\npublic class ConfigBean { /* loads config */ }\n\n@Singleton @Startup\n@DependsOn(\"ConfigBean\")\npublic class CacheBean {\n    @EJB ConfigBean cfg;\n    @PostConstruct void warm() { /* uses cfg — guaranteed ready */ }\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is @Lock(READ) vs @Lock(WRITE) on a singleton?","answer":"**@Lock(READ)** — many threads concurrently. **@Lock(WRITE)** — exclusive (only one thread, blocks all others). Only applies when `@ConcurrencyManagement(CONTAINER)`, the default.","explanation":"Mirrors a classic *readers-writer lock*: many readers OR one writer. Default if neither is\nspecified is `@Lock(WRITE)` — safe but a throughput killer if you forget to mark read-only getters\nas `@Lock(READ)`. A writer-locked method blocks *every* reader as well as other writers.","example":"```java\n@Singleton\npublic class Counter {\n    private long count;\n    @Lock(READ)  public long get()          { return count; }   // parallel\n    @Lock(WRITE) public void inc()          { count++;      }   // exclusive\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does @AccessTimeout control on a singleton?","answer":"Max time (ms) a thread waits to acquire a @Lock before throwing ConcurrentAccessTimeoutException. Prevents deadlock.","explanation":"Without a timeout, two slow writers + a queue of readers can stall the whole app. `@AccessTimeout`\ncaps how long a thread will wait; once exceeded, the container throws\n`ConcurrentAccessTimeoutException` instead of hanging. Value `0` = fail immediately if lock busy;\n`-1` = wait forever.","example":"```java\n@Singleton\npublic class SlowCache {\n    @Lock(WRITE)\n    @AccessTimeout(value = 5, unit = TimeUnit.SECONDS)\n    public void refresh() { /* long I/O */ }      // caller waits max 5s\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Difference between @ConcurrencyManagement(CONTAINER) and (BEAN)?","answer":"**CONTAINER** (default) — container serializes access via @Lock. **BEAN** — developer responsible, must use synchronized / Lock manually. Bean-managed gives full control at the cost of complexity.","explanation":"CMC (the default) is the \"safe\" path: annotate methods and the container does the locking. BMC is\nthe escape hatch when coarse read/write locking is too blunt — e.g. you need a `ConcurrentHashMap`,\n`ReentrantReadWriteLock`, or lock-free data structures for hot paths. In BMC mode `@Lock` is\nignored completely; you own thread safety end-to-end.","example":"```java\n@Singleton\n@ConcurrencyManagement(ConcurrencyManagementType.BEAN)\npublic class HotCounter {\n    private final AtomicLong n = new AtomicLong();\n    public long inc() { return n.incrementAndGet(); }   // no @Lock\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Why does SLSB not need @PrePassivate / @PostActivate?","answer":"SLSBs have no client state. They're interchangeable from the pool. Container never needs to serialize them. Only SFSBs passivate.","explanation":"Passivation only exists to save memory when an idle SFSB is holding conversational state. A\nstateless pool instance has *nothing worth saving* — the container just shrinks the pool if memory\nis tight, destroying extra instances outright (calling `@PreDestroy`, not `@PrePassivate`). A\ncommon exam trap: \"Which callback fires when an SLSB is idle?\" — answer is none; pool shrinkage\nfires `@PreDestroy`.","example":"```java\n@Stateless\npublic class MailService {\n    @PostConstruct void init()   { }   // on add to pool\n    @PreDestroy  void shutdown() { }   // on pool shrink — never @PrePassivate\n}\n```"}]},{"id":"4911-mdb","name":"MDB","tags":["mdb","tech"],"prose":"Cards covering MDB.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What annotation marks an MDB?","answer":"`@MessageDriven`. Bean implements javax.jms.MessageListener, overrides `onMessage(Message m)`.","explanation":"An MDB has no client — it wakes up because a *message* arrived. The container pulls the message\noff the destination, picks a pooled MDB instance, and hands it to `onMessage`. There is no return\nvalue and no interface for direct client invocation; MDBs are fire-and-forget consumers.","example":"```java\n@MessageDriven(activationConfig = {\n    @ActivationConfigProperty(propertyName=\"destinationType\",\n                              propertyValue=\"javax.jms.Queue\")\n})\npublic class OrderMDB implements MessageListener {\n    public void onMessage(Message m) { /* process */ }\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Two JMS messaging models?","answer":"1. **Point-to-Point (Queue)** — 1:1, exactly one consumer\n2. **Publish-Subscribe (Topic)** — 1:many, all subscribers receive each message","explanation":"Queue = *work list*: each message is delivered to exactly one consumer — great for load-balanced\ntask processing. Topic = *broadcast*: every subscriber gets a copy — great for event fan-out.\nBruce flagged Queue-vs-Topic as HIGH priority on the final, so know the difference cold.","example":"```java\n// Queue (Point-to-Point): one of N workers consumes each job\n@ActivationConfigProperty(propertyName=\"destinationType\", propertyValue=\"javax.jms.Queue\")\n\n// Topic (Pub-Sub): every subscriber receives each event\n@ActivationConfigProperty(propertyName=\"destinationType\", propertyValue=\"javax.jms.Topic\")\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"How do you set destination type on an MDB?","answer":"`@ActivationConfigProperty(propertyName=\"destinationType\", propertyValue=\"javax.jms.Topic\")` inside @MessageDriven activationConfig array.","explanation":"`activationConfig` is an array of name/value pairs the container passes to the JMS provider at\nMDB deployment. Beyond `destinationType`, common entries are `destinationLookup` (JNDI name of the\nqueue/topic), `acknowledgeMode` (Auto/Dups-OK) and `messageSelector` (SQL-92-style filter on\nmessage headers).","example":"```java\n@MessageDriven(activationConfig = {\n  @ActivationConfigProperty(propertyName=\"destinationType\",   propertyValue=\"javax.jms.Queue\"),\n  @ActivationConfigProperty(propertyName=\"destinationLookup\", propertyValue=\"jms/OrderQueue\"),\n  @ActivationConfigProperty(propertyName=\"messageSelector\",   propertyValue=\"priority \u003e 5\")\n})\npublic class OrderMDB implements MessageListener { ... }\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Why is MDB like SLSB?","answer":"Stateless, pooled, same lifecycle (DoesNotExist → Method-Ready Pool). No passivation. Multiple instances handle concurrent messages.","explanation":"Both are stateless, both use a container-managed pool, both fire `@PostConstruct`/`@PreDestroy`\nonly. The key difference is the *trigger*: SLSB is invoked synchronously via `@EJB` injection;\nMDB is invoked asynchronously when a JMS message arrives. Because the pool size caps\nconcurrency, MDBs naturally process many messages in parallel.","example":"```java\n// Shared lifecycle: no passivation, no conversational state\n@PostConstruct void init()    { /* open resources once */ }\n@PreDestroy  void shutdown()  { /* close on pool shrink */ }\n```"}]}]},{"id":"jpa","name":"JPA — entities & persistence","topics":[{"id":"4911-entitymanager","name":"EntityManager","tags":["jpa","tech"],"prose":"EntityManager is the gateway between Java entities and the database. It maintains a Persistence Context (PC) — the set of managed entities within a transaction.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What does EntityManager.persist(e) do?","answer":"Makes the new entity managed, schedules INSERT for next flush/commit. Does NOT immediately write to DB. Throws EntityExistsException if entity already has id and exists.","explanation":"`persist()` is the **New → Managed** transition only. The INSERT is queued on the persistence\ncontext and flushed at the next `flush()` or at transaction commit. Calling `persist()` on a\n*detached* entity is an error — use `merge()` instead. Cascade type `PERSIST` propagates the call\nto related entities.","example":"```java\nCustomer c = new Customer();        // New/Transient\nc.setName(\"Alice\");\nem.persist(c);                      // now Managed, INSERT queued\n// INSERT runs on flush() or commit, not here\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"When do you use merge() instead of persist()?","answer":"For DETACHED entities. persist() throws on detached. merge() copies state into a managed copy and returns it. Use for entities returned from client / serialized across tiers.","explanation":"Key trap: `merge()` does **not** make the argument managed — it copies state into a new managed\ninstance and *returns* that. The parameter stays detached. Always assign the return value and keep\nworking with it. Use merge for entities that came back from a web tier, an RMI call, or were\ndetached when a previous TX ended.","example":"```java\nCustomer detached = /* came back from client */;\ndetached.setEmail(\"new@x.com\");\nCustomer managed = em.merge(detached);   // NEW managed copy returned\nmanaged.setPhone(\"555\");                 // changes go to managed\n// detached is still detached — modifications to it are lost\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What are the four entity states?","answer":"1. **New/Transient** (never persisted, no id)\n2. **Managed** (in persistence context, tracked)\n3. **Detached** (was managed, now outside PC)\n4. **Removed** (scheduled for DELETE)","explanation":"The four states are a tiny state machine: `new → persist → Managed → remove → Removed`, and\nManaged → Detached the moment the PC closes (TX commit / `em.clear()` / `em.detach(e)`). Only\nManaged and Removed are *tracked*; dirty checks and cascades only fire on tracked objects. Lazy\nloading fails on Detached because the PC is no longer watching.","example":"```java\nCustomer c = new Customer();          // New\nem.persist(c);                        // Managed\ntx.commit();                          // Detached (PC closed)\nc = em.merge(c);                      // Managed again (via copy)\nem.remove(c);                         // Removed\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does flush() do?","answer":"Synchronizes PC state to database — writes pending INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE. Transaction remains open. Does NOT commit.","explanation":"`flush()` forces the provider to emit queued SQL right now, so constraints, triggers, or generated\nIDs materialize early. It does NOT commit — the transaction stays open and a rollback still undoes\nthe flushed changes. Use it when you need a DB-generated id before commit, or when a subsequent\nnative query must see pending modifications.","example":"```java\nem.persist(order);            // INSERT queued\nem.flush();                   // INSERT runs now; order.id populated\nem.createNativeQuery(\"UPDATE ...\").executeUpdate();  // sees the order row\n// TX still open; rollback would still undo everything\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What's the difference between find() and getReference()?","answer":"**find()** — queries DB immediately, returns null if missing. **getReference()** — returns proxy, no DB hit, throws EntityNotFoundException only when proxy accessed. Use for FK-only updates.","explanation":"`getReference()` is the \"lazy\" cousin of `find()`. The returned object is a proxy that defers the\nSELECT until you actually touch a field other than the id. This is perfect when you only need the\nid to set a FK on another entity — you skip a round trip. But if the row doesn't exist, the error\nonly surfaces when the proxy is first accessed, which makes bugs harder to trace.","example":"```java\n// Only need dept as an FK on employee — no SELECT needed\nDepartment proxy = em.getReference(Department.class, deptId);\nemployee.setDepartment(proxy);          // FK set, zero DB reads\nem.persist(employee);\n\nDepartment real = em.find(Department.class, deptId);  // SELECT runs now\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What annotation injects a container-managed EntityManager?","answer":"`@PersistenceContext`. By default: transaction-scoped. Add `type=PersistenceContextType.EXTENDED` for SFSBs that span transactions.","explanation":"`@PersistenceContext` is *not* the same as `@Inject` or `@Resource` — it hooks the bean up to the\nJPA persistence unit declared in `persistence.xml`. `unitName=\"…\"` selects one when multiple PUs\nexist. The injected `EntityManager` is safe to share across threads because the container\nproxies it and looks up the current TX's PC on each call.","example":"```java\n@Stateless\npublic class OrderService {\n    @PersistenceContext(unitName = \"myPU\")\n    private EntityManager em;\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Transaction-scoped vs Extended persistence context?","answer":"**Transaction-scoped** (default): lives for ONE transaction; entities detach when TX ends. **Extended**: lives across multiple TXs in an SFSB; entities remain managed. Extended only valid in SFSBs.","explanation":"Transaction-scoped PCs are created at TX start and torn down at TX end — perfect for stateless\nservices. Extended PCs are tied to the SFSB's conversation: the same PC survives across multiple\nmethod calls and TXs, which is how wizards and carts can repeatedly load, edit, and save the same\nmanaged entity without re-merging. Using `EXTENDED` on an SLSB or Singleton is a deployment error.","example":"```java\n@Stateful\npublic class BookingWizard {\n    @PersistenceContext(type = PersistenceContextType.EXTENDED)\n    EntityManager em;   // survives every method call until @Remove\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Why does em.remove(detachedEntity) throw an exception?","answer":"remove() requires a managed entity. On detached, throws IllegalArgumentException. First merge() to reattach, THEN remove.","explanation":"`remove()` expects an entity that is currently in the persistence context — the PC is what\nschedules the DELETE. A detached object is outside the PC, so the provider literally doesn't know\nit exists. Pattern: `em.remove(em.merge(detached))`. Alternatively use `em.find()` to fetch the\nmanaged version first.","example":"```java\nCustomer detached = /* came from client */;\n// em.remove(detached);                    // BOOM: IllegalArgumentException\nem.remove(em.merge(detached));             // OK: merge first, then remove\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Does calling find(Employee.class, 1) twice in the same PC return the same object?","answer":"Yes — same object reference. PC caches by identity. Two finds with the same PK return the same Java instance (identity semantics).","explanation":"The PC is a *first-level cache* keyed by `(entity class, primary key)`. Guaranteed identity inside\nthe same PC is why you can safely compare with `==` and why dirty-checking works — there is only\none Java object representing each row. Across different PCs (or after detach) the guarantee is\ngone, so always compare with `.equals()` there.","example":"```java\nEmployee a = em.find(Employee.class, 1L);\nEmployee b = em.find(Employee.class, 1L);\nassert a == b;           // true — same PC, same instance\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does em.refresh(entity) do?","answer":"Reloads managed entity from database, overwriting in-memory changes. Used to discard unsaved edits or grab fresh data.","explanation":"`refresh()` re-reads the row and copies the DB state back into the managed instance, *throwing\naway* any unflushed changes in memory. Use it to recover from an optimistic-lock failure, to pick\nup values set by DB triggers, or to back out of a partially-edited entity.","example":"```java\nEmployee e = em.find(Employee.class, 1L);\ne.setSalary(BigDecimal.ZERO);   // bad edit, not yet committed\nem.refresh(e);                  // discards the edit; e.salary = DB value\n```"}]},{"id":"4911-mapping","name":"Mapping","tags":["jpa","tech"],"prose":"JPA entity mapping — `@Entity`, `@Table`, `@Id`, `@Column`, plus composite keys via `@IdClass` (multiple `@Id` fields) or `@EmbeddedId` (one `@Embeddable` PK class). Recognize the two composite-key styles by name.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What annotation marks a class as a JPA entity?","answer":"`@Entity`. Required. Class must also have: no-arg constructor, exactly one @Id, be top-level (not inner).","explanation":"`@Entity` is what flips the class from \"plain Java\" to \"row in a table.\" The structural rules\n(no-arg ctor, non-final class, top-level, `@Id`) exist because the provider needs to reflectively\ninstantiate and proxy the class. Missing any one is a deploy-time failure — common midterm trap:\na class declared `final` or lacking the default constructor.","example":"```java\n@Entity\npublic class Customer {\n    @Id private Long id;\n    private String name;\n    public Customer() {}                  // REQUIRED no-arg ctor\n    public Customer(String name) { this.name = name; }\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Is @Table required on an entity?","answer":"**No — it's optional.** Default table name = entity class name. Use @Table(name=\"...\") to override. (Midterm trap: watch for \"@Table is required\" T/F → FALSE.)","explanation":"\"@Table is required\" is a classic T/F bait — the answer is **FALSE**. Without `@Table`, JPA uses\nthe entity class name as the table name (often uppercased depending on provider/dialect).\n`@Table` also lets you override schema, catalog, or add unique constraints, so you still reach\nfor it whenever the legacy DB name disagrees with your Java class name.","example":"```java\n@Entity                          // no @Table → table \"Customer\"\npublic class Customer { ... }\n\n@Entity\n@Table(name = \"CUST_TBL\", schema = \"SALES\",\n       uniqueConstraints = @UniqueConstraint(columnNames = \"email\"))\npublic class Client { ... }      // table SALES.CUST_TBL\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which annotation marks a field to be excluded from persistence?","answer":"`@Transient`. Field never written to DB. Use for calculated / temp fields. (Fake distractors: @Virtual, @Calculated — don't exist.)","explanation":"Do NOT confuse `@Transient` (JPA, skip this field) with Java's `transient` keyword (skip on\nserialization). JPA will otherwise auto-map every non-static field. Classic use case: a derived\nvalue like `fullName` computed from `firstName` + `lastName`, or a cached display value you don't\nwant round-tripped to the DB.","example":"```java\n@Entity\npublic class Employee {\n    @Id Long id;\n    String firstName;\n    String lastName;\n    @Transient String fullName;      // never written to DB\n    @PostLoad void build() { fullName = firstName + \" \" + lastName; }\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which annotation maps a java.util.Date?","answer":"`@Temporal(TemporalType.DATE | TIME | TIMESTAMP)`. Required for java.util.Date / Calendar. NOT needed for java.time.LocalDate (JPA 2.2+).","explanation":"`java.util.Date` carries date+time+timezone ambiguity, so JPA makes you disambiguate with\n`@Temporal`: `DATE` (just date), `TIME` (just clock time), or `TIMESTAMP` (both). Omitting it on a\n`java.util.Date` field is a deploy error. Modern code should prefer `java.time.LocalDate` /\n`LocalDateTime` / `Instant`, which map natively without `@Temporal`.","example":"```java\n@Temporal(TemporalType.DATE)      private java.util.Date birthDate;      // DATE only\n@Temporal(TemporalType.TIMESTAMP) private java.util.Date createdAt;      // full ts\nprivate java.time.LocalDate hireDate;                                    // no @Temporal needed\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which annotation identifies the primary key?","answer":"`@Id`. Every entity must have exactly one @Id (simple) or use @IdClass / @EmbeddedId for composite. (Fake distractors: @Identity, @PrimaryKey, @PK.)","explanation":"MCQ trap: `@Identity`, `@PrimaryKey`, and `@PK` don't exist in JPA — only `@Id`. Pair it with\n`@GeneratedValue` to have the DB / provider allocate the value; otherwise you set it yourself\nbefore `persist()`. Place `@Id` either on the field or the getter, but be consistent for all\nentities in the class hierarchy (field vs property access is determined by where `@Id` lives).","example":"```java\n@Entity\npublic class Product {\n    @Id\n    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)\n    private Long id;\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Four strategies for @GeneratedValue?","answer":"1. `AUTO` (default, dialect chooses)\n2. `IDENTITY` (auto-increment column)\n3. `SEQUENCE` (database sequence, Oracle/Postgres)\n4. `TABLE` (portable fallback, separate PK table)","explanation":"`AUTO` lets the provider pick whatever fits the database (often IDENTITY on MySQL, SEQUENCE on\nOracle/Postgres). `IDENTITY` means the DB allocates the id on INSERT — cheap but blocks JDBC\nbatching. `SEQUENCE` is generally fastest because the provider can pre-fetch a block of IDs.\n`TABLE` fakes a sequence with a separate helper table — the most portable but also the slowest.","example":"```java\n@Id\n@GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.SEQUENCE, generator = \"emp_seq\")\n@SequenceGenerator(name = \"emp_seq\", sequenceName = \"EMP_SEQ\", allocationSize = 50)\nprivate Long id;\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Two ways to define a composite primary key?","answer":"1. **@IdClass** — external PK class (not annotated), @Id on multiple fields in entity that mirror PK class\n2. **@EmbeddedId** — PK class annotated @Embeddable, single @EmbeddedId field in entity\n\nBoth need equals() + hashCode() and Serializable.","explanation":"Bruce flagged composite keys as HIGH priority. Both flavors produce the same table layout but\ndiffer in Java shape: `@IdClass` keeps the PK fields inline on the entity (PK class mirrors them);\n`@EmbeddedId` groups them into one embeddable value object and the entity has a single PK field.\nThe common failure mode is forgetting `Serializable` or a correct `equals/hashCode` on the PK\nclass — the PC uses identity equality, so broken `equals()` silently duplicates rows.","example":"```java\n// @IdClass style\npublic class EmpPK implements Serializable { Long dept; String empNo; /* equals+hashCode */ }\n@Entity @IdClass(EmpPK.class)\npublic class Emp { @Id Long dept; @Id String empNo; }\n\n// @EmbeddedId style\n@Embeddable public class EmpPK2 implements Serializable { Long dept; String empNo; }\n@Entity public class Emp2 { @EmbeddedId EmpPK2 id; }\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Difference: @Enumerated(ORDINAL) vs (STRING)?","answer":"**ORDINAL** — stored as 0, 1, 2… (default; fragile if enum order changes). **STRING** — stored as name (safe, uses more space). Prefer STRING.","explanation":"The default is `ORDINAL`, which stores the enum's position. Insert a new enum value in the middle\nlater — all existing rows silently shift meaning. `STRING` stores the enum name, so refactors are\nsafe (though renaming a constant is now breaking instead). Always prefer `STRING` in new code;\nit's the classic exam \"why is this data corrupted\" scenario.","example":"```java\npublic enum Status { NEW, PAID, SHIPPED }\n\n@Enumerated(EnumType.STRING)        // stores \"NEW\" / \"PAID\" / \"SHIPPED\"\nprivate Status status;\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does @Version do?","answer":"Optimistic locking. Numeric field auto-incremented on each UPDATE. If two clients read + update, second's version mismatch triggers OptimisticLockException.","explanation":"`@Version` turns every UPDATE into a `WHERE id=? AND version=?` — if zero rows are affected\nbecause someone else already incremented version, the provider throws `OptimisticLockException`.\nThis is \"last write wins is wrong — detect it\" semantics: no locks are held in the DB, contention\nis detected at commit. Typically backed by a `long`, `int`, or `@Temporal` timestamp.","example":"```java\n@Entity\npublic class Account {\n    @Id Long id;\n    @Version private long version;    // auto-managed by JPA\n    private BigDecimal balance;\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"@Embedded vs @Entity — what's embedded?","answer":"**@Embeddable** = not an entity, no table, columns flattened into parent table. Parent uses **@Embedded** on the field. Use for value objects (Address, Money).","explanation":"An `@Embeddable` has no `@Id` and no table of its own — its columns live in the owner's table. It\nmodels *value objects* (two Addresses with identical fields are \"equal\" with no separate identity).\nGreat for grouping related columns (Address, Money, DateRange) without the overhead of a second\ntable or FK. Use `@AttributeOverride` to rename columns when the same Embeddable appears twice.","example":"```java\n@Embeddable\npublic class Address { String street; String city; String zip; }\n\n@Entity\npublic class Customer {\n    @Id Long id;\n    @Embedded Address shipping;         // columns flattened into CUSTOMER table\n}\n```"}]},{"id":"4911-relationships","name":"Relationships","tags":["relationships","tech"],"prose":"\"Technically difficult. He CAN ask hard questions here.\" — Bruce","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"A 1:1 unidirectional relationship uses `@OneToOne` plus \\_\\_\\_ on the owning side.","answer":"`@JoinColumn`. Owning side holds the FK; inverse side is absent in unidirectional.","explanation":"The owning side of any relationship is the side that physically holds the FK column — `@JoinColumn`\nis what declares that FK. In a *unidirectional* 1:1 only one class has the field, so that class is\nautomatically the owner. Without `@JoinColumn`, JPA still assumes a FK column exists and uses a\ndefault name (`profile_id`).","example":"```java\n@Entity\npublic class User {\n    @Id Long id;\n    @OneToOne\n    @JoinColumn(name = \"PROFILE_ID\")   // FK column in USER table\n    private Profile profile;\n}\n@Entity public class Profile { @Id Long id; }   // no reference back\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"A 1:1 bidirectional relationship marks the inverse side with \\_\\_\\_.","answer":"`@OneToOne(mappedBy=\"...\")`. The name points to the field on the owning side.","explanation":"`mappedBy` literally means \"I am the *inverse* — the FK lives over there, on the field named X.\"\nWithout it, JPA assumes two independent relationships and creates a second FK column. The string\nis the Java *field name* on the owning class, not the column name and not the class name.","example":"```java\n@Entity\npublic class User {\n    @OneToOne @JoinColumn(name = \"PROFILE_ID\")\n    private Profile profile;                            // OWNS\n}\n@Entity\npublic class Profile {\n    @OneToOne(mappedBy = \"profile\")                     // inverse — points at User.profile\n    private User user;\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"In a unidirectional 1:N, the FK usually sits on the \\_\\_\\_ side when `@JoinColumn` is specified.","answer":"**many** side. Without @JoinColumn, JPA defaults to a separate join table.","explanation":"A unidirectional 1:N is the awkward case: the *one* side declares the relationship but the FK\nnaturally belongs on the *many* side (one cell can't store a list of ids). With `@JoinColumn`,\nJPA puts the FK on the many-side table; without it, the default fallback is a join table with two\nFK columns — often a surprise, which is why `@JoinColumn` is nearly always added explicitly.","example":"```java\n@Entity\npublic class Department {\n    @Id Long id;\n    @OneToMany\n    @JoinColumn(name = \"DEPT_ID\")       // FK column lives in EMPLOYEE table\n    private List\u003cEmployee\u003e employees;\n}\n@Entity public class Employee { @Id Long id; }   // no back-reference\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"The annotation that declares an N:1 unidirectional relationship is \\_\\_\\_.","answer":"`@ManyToOne` (typically paired with `@JoinColumn`).","explanation":"N:1 is the \"natural\" direction — the many side has a single FK pointing at the one side, which is\nexactly what a DB row looks like. `@ManyToOne` defaults to EAGER fetch, which is usually fine for\na single parent but can be surprising in large graphs; override with `fetch=LAZY` if needed.","example":"```java\n@Entity\npublic class Employee {\n    @Id Long id;\n    @ManyToOne\n    @JoinColumn(name = \"DEPT_ID\")\n    private Department department;        // FK column DEPT_ID on EMPLOYEE\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"In a bidirectional 1:N/N:1, the \\_\\_\\_ side is the owning side.","answer":"**many (N)** side owns. The one-side uses `mappedBy`. Reason: the FK lives in the many-side table.","explanation":"This is Bruce's canonical high-priority card. The *many* side owns because that's where the FK\nphysically lives — 1:N doesn't fit in one cell. JPA only reads the owning side when deciding what\nSQL to emit, so forgetting `mappedBy` on the one side yields a second FK or even a join table.\nAlways add a helper method that sets both sides in Java to keep the object graph consistent.","example":"```java\n@Entity\npublic class Department {\n    @OneToMany(mappedBy = \"department\")          // inverse\n    private List\u003cEmployee\u003e employees = new ArrayList\u003c\u003e();\n}\n@Entity\npublic class Employee {\n    @ManyToOne @JoinColumn(name = \"DEPT_ID\")     // OWNING — holds FK\n    private Department department;\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"An M:N unidirectional relationship is declared with `@ManyToMany` plus \\_\\_\\_ to name the link table.","answer":"`@JoinTable`. Specifies the join table + both join columns.","explanation":"M:N always needs a link table in relational storage (no other way to express many-to-many). In\na unidirectional M:N, only one side has the field and that side declares `@JoinTable` naming the\nlink table, the FK to itself (`joinColumns`), and the FK to the other entity\n(`inverseJoinColumns`). Without `@JoinTable`, JPA auto-names the link table as the concatenation\nof both entity names.","example":"```java\n@Entity\npublic class Student {\n    @ManyToMany\n    @JoinTable(\n        name = \"STUDENT_COURSE\",\n        joinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = \"STUDENT_ID\"),\n        inverseJoinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = \"COURSE_ID\"))\n    private List\u003cCourse\u003e courses;\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"An M:N bidirectional relationship puts `mappedBy` on the \\_\\_\\_ side.","answer":"**inverse** side. Owning side carries the `@JoinTable`; inverse just refers back.","explanation":"In bidirectional M:N, *either* class can own the relationship (no FK-location constraint since it\nlives in the link table). Whichever side you put `@JoinTable` on becomes the owner; the other side\nsimply says `mappedBy=\"fieldName\"`. Changes to the collection on the *inverse* side are ignored\nat flush — only the owning side drives SQL.","example":"```java\n@Entity\npublic class Student {\n    @ManyToMany                                    // OWNS\n    @JoinTable(name = \"STUDENT_COURSE\", ...)\n    private List\u003cCourse\u003e courses;\n}\n@Entity\npublic class Course {\n    @ManyToMany(mappedBy = \"courses\")              // inverse\n    private List\u003cStudent\u003e students;\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which side of a bidirectional relationship is the owning side?","answer":"The side **with @JoinColumn (or @JoinTable)** — the side that holds the foreign key. The other side uses `mappedBy=\"...\"` pointing to the owner's field.","explanation":"Remember the definition: *owner = holds the FK*. JPA reads only the owner's collection/reference\nat flush to decide INSERT/UPDATE of the FK column. A bidirectional relationship that forgets\n`mappedBy` is treated as two separate unidirectional ones — you'll see double rows in the join\ntable or an unexpected second FK column.","example":"```java\n@ManyToOne @JoinColumn(name=\"DEPT_ID\")         // owner — holds FK\nprivate Department department;\n\n@OneToMany(mappedBy = \"department\")             // inverse — no FK here\nprivate List\u003cEmployee\u003e employees;\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"In a 1:N bidirectional relationship, which side owns?","answer":"The **MANY side** (with @ManyToOne + @JoinColumn) owns. The ONE side uses @OneToMany(mappedBy=\"...\"). The many side holds the FK.","explanation":"This is a direct consequence of \"FK goes where it fits\" — you can't store a list of ids in the\none-side row. Always add a helper on the one side that keeps both sides in sync, otherwise your\nin-memory graph and the DB will disagree until the next reload.","example":"```java\npublic class Department {\n    @OneToMany(mappedBy = \"department\")\n    private List\u003cEmployee\u003e employees = new ArrayList\u003c\u003e();\n    public void addEmployee(Employee e) {       // keep both sides consistent\n        employees.add(e);\n        e.setDepartment(this);\n    }\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does mappedBy point to?","answer":"The field name on the owning side that holds the relationship. E.g. @OneToMany(mappedBy=\"employee\") → owning Employee class has a field named \"employee\".","explanation":"`mappedBy` takes the *Java field name* (or property name under property access) on the owning\nclass — never the column name, never the entity name. Typos produce `MappingException` at\ndeployment. Reading `mappedBy=\"x\"` aloud as \"I'm mapped by the field `x` on the other side\" helps\nremember the direction.","example":"```java\n@Entity public class Employee {\n    @ManyToOne @JoinColumn(name=\"DEPT_ID\")\n    private Department department;              // \u003c— field name\n}\n@Entity public class Department {\n    @OneToMany(mappedBy = \"department\")          // points at Employee.department\n    private List\u003cEmployee\u003e employees;\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Default fetch type for \\*ToOne vs \\*ToMany?","answer":"**@ManyToOne, @OneToOne** → EAGER. **@OneToMany, @ManyToMany** → LAZY. Override with fetch=FetchType.X.","explanation":"Rule of thumb: *single* = EAGER (loaded with the parent), *many* = LAZY (loaded only when the\ncollection is accessed). EAGER can silently pull half the schema across a deep object graph, so\nin large apps you often flip `@ManyToOne` to LAZY. LAZY collections throw\n`LazyInitializationException` if accessed after the PC closes — the usual fix is `JOIN FETCH`.","example":"```java\n@ManyToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)                   // override default EAGER\nprivate Department department;\n\n@OneToMany(mappedBy = \"department\", fetch = FetchType.EAGER)\nprivate List\u003cEmployee\u003e employees;                    // override default LAZY\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Six values of CascadeType?","answer":"1. ALL\n2. PERSIST\n3. MERGE\n4. REMOVE\n5. REFRESH\n6. DETACH\n\nDefault = NONE (no cascade). Example: `@OneToMany(cascade=CascadeType.ALL)`.","explanation":"Cascade means \"propagate this `EntityManager` operation to related entities.\" `ALL` bundles all\nfive (remember: PERSIST, MERGE, REMOVE, REFRESH, DETACH — `ALL` is a convenience alias, not a\nseparate behavior). Note: `CascadeType` does NOT include a \"find\" — find doesn't cascade. Apply\ncascade with restraint: `CascadeType.REMOVE` on a big `@ManyToMany` can delete more than you want.","example":"```java\n@OneToMany(mappedBy = \"order\",\n           cascade = { CascadeType.PERSIST, CascadeType.REMOVE })\nprivate List\u003cLineItem\u003e items;\n// em.persist(order) also persists items; em.remove(order) also removes items\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does orphanRemoval=true do?","answer":"When a child is removed from the parent collection, the orphan is deleted from the DB (not just unlinked). Combines well with CascadeType.REMOVE for parent-child lifecycles.","explanation":"`CascadeType.REMOVE` fires only when you call `em.remove(parent)`. `orphanRemoval=true` is\nstronger: when a child is simply pulled out of the parent's collection (`parent.getItems().remove\n(item)`), JPA schedules a DELETE on that orphan at flush. Use it for strict parent-child\nlifecycles where a child has no meaning without its parent.","example":"```java\n@OneToMany(mappedBy = \"order\",\n           cascade = CascadeType.ALL,\n           orphanRemoval = true)\nprivate List\u003cLineItem\u003e items;\n\norder.getItems().remove(item);    // at flush → DELETE FROM LINE_ITEM WHERE id = ?\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"To map 1:1 sharing primary keys, which annotation?","answer":"`@PrimaryKeyJoinColumn` — child uses parent's PK as its own PK (no separate FK column). @JoinColumn = FK-style; @PrimaryKeyJoinColumn = shared-PK-style.","explanation":"A shared-PK 1:1 means the child's `@Id` value *is* the parent's `@Id` — there's no separate FK\ncolumn, the PK itself plays both roles. Classic use case: splitting a wide row into an \"extras\"\ntable without a surrogate FK. Contrast with `@JoinColumn`, which adds a dedicated FK column\ndistinct from the child's own PK.","example":"```java\n@Entity\npublic class Employee {\n    @Id Long id;\n    @OneToOne @PrimaryKeyJoinColumn\n    private EmployeeDetail detail;\n}\n@Entity\npublic class EmployeeDetail {\n    @Id Long id;              // same value as Employee.id — shared PK\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Default mapping for @ManyToMany?","answer":"Join table with two FK columns. Join table name = concat of both entity names. Override with `@JoinTable(name=\"...\", joinColumns=..., inverseJoinColumns=...)`.","explanation":"Without `@JoinTable`, JPA invents the link table name as `STUDENT_COURSE` (owner first, then\ninverse) and the FK column names as `\u003centity\u003e_\u003cpk\u003e`. Explicit `@JoinTable` is the norm because\nlegacy DBs rarely match the default names and you often want a specific order or unique\nconstraint.","example":"```java\n@ManyToMany\n@JoinTable(\n    name = \"STU_CRS\",\n    joinColumns        = @JoinColumn(name = \"STU_ID\"),\n    inverseJoinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = \"CRS_ID\"))\nprivate List\u003cCourse\u003e courses;\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"T/F: @JoinTable can map a 1:1 relationship?","answer":"**TRUE.** @JoinTable can map any relationship (1:1, 1:N, N:N). Though unusual for 1:1 (normally @JoinColumn).","explanation":"A junior-grade MCQ trap: `@JoinTable` is legal on *any* relationship type — the spec puts no\nrestriction on cardinality. It just tends to be overkill for 1:1 and 1:N where a single FK column\nis simpler. You'd reach for it in 1:1 when you can't alter either existing table but can add a\nnew one.","example":"```java\n@OneToOne\n@JoinTable(\n    name = \"USER_PROFILE_LINK\",\n    joinColumns        = @JoinColumn(name = \"USER_ID\"),\n    inverseJoinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = \"PROFILE_ID\"))\nprivate Profile profile;\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Bidirectional relationships — why set both sides manually?","answer":"JPA only reads the owning side for persistence, but Java object graph needs both sides set for correct in-memory traversal. Add convenience methods to keep them consistent.","explanation":"JPA's DB sync only cares about the owning side — it's what gets INSERT/UPDATED. But Java code that\nnavigates `dept.getEmployees()` or `emp.getDepartment()` relies on the in-memory graph. If you only\nset one side, the graph is half-correct until the next reload. The standard pattern is a helper\nthat sets both sides atomically.","example":"```java\npublic class Department {\n    private List\u003cEmployee\u003e employees = new ArrayList\u003c\u003e();\n    public void addEmployee(Employee e) {\n        employees.add(e);           // inverse side\n        e.setDepartment(this);      // owning side — FK will be set here\n    }\n}\n```"}]},{"id":"4911-inheritance","name":"Inheritance","tags":["inheritance","tech"],"prose":"Three JPA inheritance strategies — `SINGLE_TABLE` (default; one table + discriminator column), `JOINED` (table per class joined by FK), and `TABLE_PER_CLASS` (full table per concrete class). Set via `@Inheritance(strategy=…)` on the root entity.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Three JPA inheritance strategies?","answer":"1. **SINGLE\\_TABLE** (default — one table, discriminator column)\n2. **JOINED** (table per class, FK joins)\n3. **TABLE\\_PER\\_CLASS** (separate complete table per concrete type, no joins, UNIONs for polymorphic queries)","explanation":"Pick by tradeoff: `SINGLE_TABLE` is fastest because every query hits one table, but stuffs every\nsubclass's columns into a single wide schema with NULLs. `JOINED` is normalized but polymorphic\nqueries cost a join per level. `TABLE_PER_CLASS` avoids joins entirely but polymorphic queries\nbecome `UNION ALL`s and id generation across tables gets awkward.","example":"```java\n@Entity\n@Inheritance(strategy = InheritanceType.JOINED)\npublic abstract class Vehicle { @Id Long id; }\n\n@Entity public class Car   extends Vehicle { int doors; }   // own table CAR\n@Entity public class Truck extends Vehicle { int payload; } // own table TRUCK\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which annotation specifies the inheritance strategy?","answer":"`@Inheritance(strategy=InheritanceType.X)` on the root entity. (Fake distractors: @InheritanceStrategy, @InheritanceType.)","explanation":"`@Inheritance` is placed only on the *root* entity; subclasses inherit the strategy implicitly.\nChanging strategies later is painful because the schema is fundamentally different, so pick early.\nMCQ trap: `@InheritanceStrategy` and `@InheritanceType` (without the strategy= inside @Inheritance)\ndo not exist as standalone annotations.","example":"```java\n@Entity\n@Inheritance(strategy = InheritanceType.SINGLE_TABLE)\n@DiscriminatorColumn(name = \"KIND\")\npublic abstract class Animal { @Id Long id; }\n\n@Entity @DiscriminatorValue(\"DOG\") public class Dog extends Animal {}\n@Entity @DiscriminatorValue(\"CAT\") public class Cat extends Animal {}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Role of @DiscriminatorColumn?","answer":"In SINGLE\\_TABLE — column that identifies which subclass each row is. Default name=DTYPE, type=STRING. Each subclass uses @DiscriminatorValue(\"X\") to set its value.","explanation":"The discriminator is how the provider knows which Java class to instantiate for a row, since all\nsubclasses share one table. Defaults to a `DTYPE VARCHAR` column containing the entity class name.\nUse `@DiscriminatorValue` to set compact codes (\"D\", \"C\") and `discriminatorType=INTEGER` if you\nprefer numeric codes.","example":"```java\n@Entity\n@Inheritance(strategy = InheritanceType.SINGLE_TABLE)\n@DiscriminatorColumn(name = \"ANIMAL_TYPE\", discriminatorType = DiscriminatorType.STRING)\npublic abstract class Animal { @Id Long id; }\n\n@Entity @DiscriminatorValue(\"DOG\") public class Dog extends Animal { String breed; }\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Pros/cons of SINGLE\\_TABLE?","answer":"Pro: fast queries (no joins), simple schema. Con: many nullable columns (subclass-specific fields), violates normalization, can't NOT NULL subclass fields.","explanation":"The DB can't enforce a NOT NULL on \"dog breed\" because cat rows legitimately leave it blank. This\npushes validation into the application layer. As the hierarchy grows, the table gets ever-wider\nand ever-sparser. The upside is raw speed — `SELECT * FROM ANIMAL WHERE TYPE=?` is one access\npath, no joins, no unions.","example":"```text\nANIMAL\n+----+------+------+-------+--------+\n| id | DTYPE| name | breed | indoor |   ← only Dogs use 'breed', only Cats use 'indoor'\n+----+------+------+-------+--------+\n|  1 | DOG  | Rex  | Lab   | NULL   |\n|  2 | CAT  | Tom  | NULL  | true   |\n+----+------+------+-------+--------+\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Pros/cons of JOINED?","answer":"Pro: normalized, subclass fields NOT NULL, no wasted space. Con: slower queries (joins), schema changes harder.","explanation":"`JOINED` gives you proper normalization — each subclass gets its own table with only its own\nfields, and the root table holds shared columns plus the discriminator/PK. Every polymorphic read\nrequires joining the subclass table, so it's heavier on reads; writes to a new subclass require\ntwo INSERTs. Use when subclass data is substantial and NOT NULL integrity matters.","example":"```text\nANIMAL         DOG                CAT\n+----+-----+   +----+-------+     +----+--------+\n| id | name|   | id | breed |     | id | indoor |\n+----+-----+   +----+-------+     +----+--------+   ← FK joins ANIMAL.id\n```"}]},{"id":"4911-callbacks","name":"Callbacks","tags":["callbacks","tech"],"prose":"Hooks for entity lifecycle events.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Callback fired BEFORE the INSERT runs: \\_\\_\\_.","answer":"`@PrePersist`. Use for setting createdAt, validating, generating computed fields.","explanation":"Fires when the entity transitions New → Managed but *before* the INSERT reaches the DB, so any\nfields you set here end up in the INSERT statement. Ideal for `createdAt`/`updatedAt`\ntimestamping and default value generation. Remember the rule: no `EntityManager` calls and no\naccess to other entities inside a callback.","example":"```java\n@Entity\npublic class Order {\n    @Id Long id;\n    private Date createdAt;\n    @PrePersist void onCreate() { createdAt = new Date(); }   // in INSERT\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Callback fired AFTER INSERT returns (generated id now populated): \\_\\_\\_.","answer":"`@PostPersist`. Do NOT call EntityManager inside — re-entry is forbidden.","explanation":"`@PostPersist` runs *after* the INSERT, so the DB-generated id (from `@GeneratedValue`) is now\npopulated on the entity. Useful for logging or publishing an event. Re-entering the EntityManager\n(e.g. to persist more entities) inside this hook is forbidden — the PC is mid-flush.","example":"```java\n@PostPersist\nvoid logCreated() {\n    log.info(\"Created Order id={}\", id);   // id is set by now\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Callback fired BEFORE an UPDATE statement runs: \\_\\_\\_.","answer":"`@PreUpdate`. Use for audit updatedAt + change validation.","explanation":"Fires once per entity per flush, right before the UPDATE reaches the DB, so setting a field here\nstill makes it into the statement. Perfect for `updatedAt` maintenance or last-minute invariant\nchecks. Only fires for *dirty* entities — a managed entity that wasn't modified triggers no\nUPDATE and therefore no `@PreUpdate`.","example":"```java\n@PreUpdate\nvoid onUpdate() {\n    this.updatedAt = new Date();            // goes into the UPDATE\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Callback fired AFTER an UPDATE commits: \\_\\_\\_.","answer":"`@PostUpdate`.","explanation":"Symmetric to `@PostPersist`: the UPDATE has been sent to the DB (but within the same TX).\nAny change you make to the entity here won't be reflected in the statement that just ran. Usually\nused for audit logging, cache invalidation, or firing domain events.","example":"```java\n@PostUpdate\nvoid onAfterUpdate() {\n    cache.evict(this.id);                   // stale cache invalidated\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Callback fired BEFORE a DELETE runs: \\_\\_\\_.","answer":"`@PreRemove`. Last chance to touch related state before row is gone.","explanation":"Your last opportunity to inspect the entity's state — after the DELETE the row is gone (well,\nscheduled). Good for writing a tombstone record or notifying observers. As always, don't invoke\nthe `EntityManager` inside.","example":"```java\n@PreRemove\nvoid beforeDelete() {\n    log.warn(\"Removing Order {} total={}\", id, total);\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Callback fired AFTER a DELETE commits: \\_\\_\\_.","answer":"`@PostRemove`.","explanation":"Fires after the DELETE statement reaches the DB within the same transaction. Often paired with\n`@PreRemove` when you need both a \"before\" snapshot and an \"after\" confirmation. The entity\nobject still exists in memory, but is now in the *Removed* state.","example":"```java\n@PostRemove\nvoid onDeleted() {\n    metrics.increment(\"orders.deleted\");\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Callback fired AFTER an entity is loaded from the database: \\_\\_\\_.","answer":"`@PostLoad`. Use for deriving transient fields from persistent ones.","explanation":"Fires after a SELECT has populated the entity, whether via `find()`, a JPQL query, or a\nrelationship fetch. Perfect for populating `@Transient` convenience fields (e.g. `fullName` from\nfirst+last) or decrypting at rest. There is deliberately no `@PreLoad` — the provider controls\nwhen loading starts.","example":"```java\n@Transient private String fullName;\n@PostLoad void buildFullName() { fullName = firstName + \" \" + lastName; }\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which lifecycle callback does JPA NOT define: @PreLoad, @PostLoad, @PrePersist?","answer":"**@PreLoad does not exist.** Loading is initiated by the provider; there is no \"before-load\" hook. Only @PostLoad.","explanation":"Classic MCQ trap. The full set is Pre/Post × Persist/Update/Remove plus **only** `@PostLoad`.\nThere's no `@PreLoad`, no `@PreFind`, no `@PreQuery`. Loading is provider-initiated and happens\ninside the JDBC boundary — you get a callback only after the entity is fully populated.","example":"```java\n// Valid:\n@PrePersist @PostPersist @PreUpdate @PostUpdate\n@PreRemove  @PostRemove  @PostLoad\n// Invalid (do not exist):\n// @PreLoad, @PreFind, @PreFlush\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Signature rules for entity callback methods?","answer":"No parameters, void return, any visibility. Must NOT invoke EntityManager or call other entities.","explanation":"When the callback method is *inside* the entity itself it takes no parameters (the entity is\n`this`). When the callback lives on an external `@EntityListeners` class, the signature must take\none `Object` parameter representing the entity being acted on. Either way, the no-EntityManager\nrule is strict — re-entering mid-flush causes undefined behavior.","example":"```java\n@PrePersist void onCreate() { /* no params, void */ }             // on entity\npublic class AuditListener {\n    @PrePersist public void log(Object entity) { /* one param */ }// on listener\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"External listener annotation?","answer":"`@EntityListeners(MyListener.class)` on entity. Listener class has @PrePersist etc. methods that take Object (entity) parameter.","explanation":"External listeners keep cross-cutting logic (auditing, metrics) out of the entity class. You can\nlist multiple listeners; they fire in declaration order, then the entity's own callbacks. A\ncommon pattern is a single `AuditListener` reused across every auditable entity.","example":"```java\n@Entity\n@EntityListeners(AuditListener.class)\npublic class Order { @Id Long id; }\n\npublic class AuditListener {\n    @PrePersist public void log(Object e) { System.out.println(\"Inserting: \" + e); }\n}\n```"}]}]},{"id":"jpql","name":"JPQL / queries & transactions","topics":[{"id":"4911-jpql","name":"JPQL","tags":["jpql","tech"],"prose":"\"Students struggle here. Fair game on final.\" — Bruce.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Basic JPQL SELECT all employees?","answer":"`SELECT e FROM Employee e`. Alias required. Operates on entity names (Employee), not table names (EMPLOYEES).","explanation":"JPQL operates on the *entity model*, not the SQL schema. `Employee` is the `@Entity` name (defaults\nto class simple name), `e` is a mandatory alias. You never write the underlying table name and\nyou never write `SELECT *` — you select the entity itself, field paths, or constructor\nexpressions.","example":"```java\nTypedQuery\u003cEmployee\u003e q = em.createQuery(\n    \"SELECT e FROM Employee e\", Employee.class);\nList\u003cEmployee\u003e all = q.getResultList();\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Write JPQL: employees in Sales department?","answer":"`SELECT e FROM Employee e WHERE e.department.name = :deptName`. Path navigation through relationship: e.department.name.","explanation":"Dot navigation (`e.department.name`) traverses relationships without an explicit JOIN — JPQL\ngenerates the necessary SQL INNER JOIN automatically. Works for any single-valued path. Use a\nnamed parameter (`:deptName`) and `setParameter` so the provider can reuse the parsed plan and\navoid injection risk.","example":"```java\nList\u003cEmployee\u003e emps = em.createQuery(\n    \"SELECT e FROM Employee e WHERE e.department.name = :deptName\",\n    Employee.class)\n  .setParameter(\"deptName\", \"Sales\")\n  .getResultList();\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"How do FETCH JOIN solve the N+1 problem?","answer":"`SELECT b FROM Book b JOIN FETCH b.author` — loads books AND related authors in ONE SQL query. Without FETCH, each book access triggers a separate author query (N+1).","explanation":"Plain `JOIN` lets you filter across a relationship but does NOT populate it. `JOIN FETCH` tells\nthe provider to *initialize* the associated entities in the same SQL, so subsequent field access\nnever triggers a follow-up query. Common fix for lazy collections; just know that you can't\n`JOIN FETCH` more than one collection without risking a Cartesian explosion.","example":"```java\n// Without FETCH: 1 query for books + N queries for each author\nList\u003cBook\u003e books = em.createQuery(\n    \"SELECT b FROM Book b JOIN FETCH b.author\", Book.class).getResultList();\n// Single SQL with INNER JOIN — authors preloaded.\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Named parameter syntax vs positional?","answer":"Named: `:name`, set with `q.setParameter(\"name\", val)`. Positional: `?1`, set with `q.setParameter(1, val)`. Prefer named.","explanation":"Named parameters are self-documenting, reorder-safe, and can appear multiple times in the same\nquery. Positional parameters (`?1`) are legal but discouraged — rename anything and you\nrenumber. Hardcoding values into JPQL is the real sin (SQL injection + parse-cache misses).","example":"```java\n// Named — preferred\nem.createQuery(\"SELECT e FROM Employee e WHERE e.salary \u003e :min\", Employee.class)\n  .setParameter(\"min\", 50000).getResultList();\n\n// Positional — legal but worse\nem.createQuery(\"SELECT e FROM Employee e WHERE e.salary \u003e ?1\", Employee.class)\n  .setParameter(1, 50000);\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"How to paginate JPQL results (page 3, 10 per page)?","answer":"`q.setFirstResult(20).setMaxResults(10).getResultList()`. firstResult is 0-indexed; page 3 = offset 20.","explanation":"`setFirstResult` is a zero-based row offset; `setMaxResults` is the page size. Together they\nbecome LIMIT/OFFSET (or the DB-specific equivalent). For deterministic paging you must ORDER\nBY — otherwise the DB may return rows in a different order between pages and you'll see\nduplicates or gaps.","example":"```java\nList\u003cEmployee\u003e page3 = em.createQuery(\n    \"SELECT e FROM Employee e ORDER BY e.id\", Employee.class)\n  .setFirstResult(20)          // page 3, 10 per page → offset 20\n  .setMaxResults(10)\n  .getResultList();\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"getResultList() vs getSingleResult()?","answer":"**getResultList()** — always returns List, empty if 0. **getSingleResult()** — expects exactly 1; throws NoResultException (0) or NonUniqueResultException (2+).","explanation":"`getSingleResult()` is convenient but throws noisy runtime exceptions for 0 or 2+ rows. If the\n\"exactly one\" expectation isn't guaranteed by your data, prefer `getResultList()` + a null check\nor `.stream().findFirst()`. `executeUpdate()` is the third form, used only for bulk\nUPDATE/DELETE JPQL — returns the affected row count.","example":"```java\ntry {\n    Employee e = em.createQuery(\"SELECT e FROM Employee e WHERE e.email = :x\", Employee.class)\n                   .setParameter(\"x\", email).getSingleResult();\n} catch (NoResultException ex)       { /* 0 rows */ }\n  catch (NonUniqueResultException ex){ /* 2+ rows */ }\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Constructor expression syntax?","answer":"`SELECT new com.x.EmpDTO(e.id, e.name) FROM Employee e`. Fully qualified class. Must have matching constructor. Returns DTO instances directly.","explanation":"Lets you project specific fields into a DTO without loading the full entity, which is great for\nread-only views / API responses. Three requirements: fully qualified class name (no import\nshortcut), a constructor whose parameter types match the SELECT list exactly, and the class\nmust be instantiable (public no-matter-what constructor).","example":"```java\npublic record EmpSummary(Long id, String name) {}   // has matching ctor\n\nList\u003cEmpSummary\u003e view = em.createQuery(\n    \"SELECT new com.x.EmpSummary(e.id, e.name) FROM Employee e\", EmpSummary.class\n).getResultList();\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Bulk UPDATE in JPQL?","answer":"`UPDATE Employee e SET e.salary = e.salary * 1.1 WHERE e.dept = :d`; call `q.executeUpdate()`. Returns row count. Bypasses PC cache.","explanation":"Bulk UPDATE/DELETE ships a single SQL statement — no row-by-row dirty checking, no callbacks\n(no `@PreUpdate`!), and managed entities already in the PC are **not** refreshed. Best practice:\nrun the bulk op then `em.clear()` (or re-fetch) to avoid stale cached entities that disagree with\nthe DB.","example":"```java\nint changed = em.createQuery(\n    \"UPDATE Employee e SET e.salary = e.salary * 1.1 WHERE e.department = :d\")\n  .setParameter(\"d\", dept)\n  .executeUpdate();               // number of rows affected\nem.clear();                       // PC cache now stale — drop it\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is @NamedQuery?","answer":"`@NamedQuery(name=\"X\", query=\"SELECT…\")` on entity class. Pre-parsed at deploy, reused. Called via `em.createNamedQuery(\"X\", Employee.class)`.","explanation":"Named queries are validated at deployment, so a syntax typo fails fast instead of at runtime.\nThey're also pre-parsed and cached, which shaves parse-time off repeated invocations. Use\n`@NamedQueries({@NamedQuery(...), ...})` to declare multiple on the same entity.","example":"```java\n@Entity\n@NamedQuery(name = \"Employee.findByDept\",\n            query = \"SELECT e FROM Employee e WHERE e.department = :d\")\npublic class Employee { ... }\n\nem.createNamedQuery(\"Employee.findByDept\", Employee.class)\n  .setParameter(\"d\", dept).getResultList();\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"JPQL for cruises a customer has reserved (Cust N:N Res, Res N:1 Cruise)?","answer":"`SELECT DISTINCT c FROM Cruise c, Reservation r WHERE r.cruise = c AND :cust MEMBER OF r.customers` — or with explicit JOIN: `SELECT DISTINCT c FROM Cruise c JOIN c.reservations r JOIN r.customers cu WHERE cu = :cust`.","explanation":"The midterm walk-through from the lesson: start by asking *what* you select (Cruise), then *what\nrelationships* you traverse (Cruise → Reservations → Customers). `DISTINCT` is mandatory because\njoining a collection multiplies rows — otherwise a cruise with multiple reservations for the same\ncustomer appears multiple times. `MEMBER OF` is the JPQL idiom for \"x is contained in that\ncollection field.\"","example":"```java\nList\u003cCruise\u003e cruises = em.createQuery(\n    \"SELECT DISTINCT c FROM Cruise c \" +\n    \"JOIN c.reservations r \" +\n    \"JOIN r.customers cu \" +\n    \"WHERE cu = :cust\", Cruise.class)\n  .setParameter(\"cust\", someCustomer)\n  .getResultList();\n```"}]},{"id":"4911-transactions","name":"Transactions","tags":["transactions","tech"],"prose":"ACID properties (Quiz 4 hit each separately) Atomicity — all-or-nothing (Q8) Consistency — integrity of data store (Q15) Isolation — no interference (Q10) Durability — persist after crash 6 Transaction Attributes — the table AttributeCaller HAS TXCaller NO TX REQUIRED (default)Join caller's TXContainer creates new TX REQUIRES_NEWSuspend caller, create NEW TXCreate new TX SUPPORTSJoin caller's TXRun without TX NOT_SUPPORTEDSuspend caller, run without TXRun without TX MANDATORYJoin caller's TXThrows EJBTransactionRequiredException NEVERThrows EJBExceptionRun without TX Quiz 4 transactions — memorize Q4: \"Does NOT propagate, runs WITHOUT TX\" = NotSupported Q5: \"Propagates if exists, else creates new\" = Required Q13: \"Does NOT propagate, runs with NEW TX\" = RequiresNew Rollback behavior System exception (RuntimeException, EJBException) → auto-rollback + logged + wrapped in EJBException Application exception (checked) → NO auto-rollback unless declared @ApplicationException(rollback=true) Programmatic: sessionContext.setRollbackOnly() CMT vs BMT // Container-managed (default) @Stateless @TransactionManagement(TransactionManagementType.CONTAINER) public class OrderService { @TransactionAttribute(TransactionAttributeType.REQUIRES_NEW) public void audit(Event e) { ... } } // Bean-managed @Stateless @TransactionManagement(TransactionManagementType.BEAN) public class ManualTxBean { @Resource UserTransaction utx; public void work() { utx.begin(); try { ...","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What does ACID stand for?","answer":"1. **A**tomicity (all-or-nothing)\n2. **C**onsistency (integrity preserved)\n3. **I**solation (no interference)\n4. **D**urability (persisted after crash)","explanation":"Bruce's Quiz 4 tested each letter separately — know the one-liner for each. A = transfer\nsucceeds in full or rolls back completely. C = invariants (FKs, NOT NULL, check constraints) hold\nbefore and after. I = concurrent TXs can't see each other's partial work. D = once commit\nreturns, the change survives power loss.","example":"```java\n// Classic atomicity example: money transfer\ntx.begin();\naccountA.withdraw(100);       // step 1\naccountB.deposit(100);        // step 2 — either both or neither\ntx.commit();                  // durable once this returns\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which ACID property = execute completely or not at all?","answer":"**Atomicity.**","explanation":"Atomicity is the *all-or-nothing* guarantee. Any crash, exception, or rollback must unwind every\nchange made inside the TX boundary. It is what makes a multi-step business operation safe to\nretry — partial state never leaks out.","example":"```java\n@TransactionAttribute(REQUIRED)\npublic void transfer(Account from, Account to, BigDecimal amt) {\n    from.withdraw(amt);           // if either step fails\n    to.deposit(amt);              // the whole TX rolls back — atomic\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which ACID property = no interference from other transactions?","answer":"**Isolation.**","explanation":"Isolation means concurrent transactions see a consistent view — dirty/non-repeatable/phantom\nreads depend on the configured isolation level, but at minimum no TX can observe another's\nuncommitted state. Trade-off: higher isolation = more locking / MVCC overhead = less throughput.","example":"```text\nTX1 reads balance=100, starts update ...\nTX2 reads balance=100  (still sees pre-TX1 value — isolated)\nTX1 commits balance=90\nTX2 now sees balance=90 (depending on isolation level)\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which ACID property = integrity of data store maintained?","answer":"**Consistency.**","explanation":"Consistency means every TX takes the DB from one *valid* state to another — FKs, NOT NULL, CHECK\nconstraints, and app-level invariants all hold before and after. If a TX would break an invariant,\nthe container or DB rolls it back instead of persisting broken data.","example":"```java\n// A CHECK(balance \u003e= 0) constraint enforces consistency:\naccount.setBalance(new BigDecimal(\"-50\"));\nem.flush();   // SQLException — DB rejects invalid state; TX rolls back\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which ACID property = changes survive after crash?","answer":"**Durability.**","explanation":"Once `commit()` returns, the change is written to durable storage (typically fsync'd WAL/redo\nlog). A power loss a millisecond later must not erase it — on restart, recovery replays the log.\nThis is why commits are expensive compared to reads.","example":"```java\nem.persist(order);\ntx.commit();          // fsync'd to WAL — survives a crash right here\n// Crash. Reboot. Order is still there.\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is the default transaction attribute for EJB methods?","answer":"`REQUIRED`. Uses caller's TX if exists, else starts new one.","explanation":"`REQUIRED` is the attribute you get when you write no `@TransactionAttribute` at all on a CMT\nmethod. It's the pragmatic default because it makes nested calls automatically cooperate —\nouter + inner join the same TX, so rollback semantics are unified. Quiz 4 Q5 tested this\ndefinition verbatim.","example":"```java\n@Stateless\npublic class OrderService {\n    public void placeOrder(Order o) { ... }       // REQUIRED by default\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"REQUIRED — caller has TX vs no TX?","answer":"**Caller HAS TX:** method joins it. **Caller NO TX:** container creates new TX for method. Propagates if exists, creates if not.","explanation":"The \"make sure a TX is running\" attribute. It never suspends and never throws — always leaves the\nmethod inside *a* transaction, joining if present else creating. Works for 95% of business code.","example":"```java\n@TransactionAttribute(TransactionAttributeType.REQUIRED)\npublic void placeOrder(Order o) {\n    em.persist(o);           // always in a TX, either inherited or new\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"REQUIRES\\_NEW — caller has TX vs no TX?","answer":"**Caller HAS TX:** SUSPENDS caller's TX, starts NEW independent one. **Caller NO TX:** starts new TX. ALWAYS runs in its own new TX.","explanation":"Always runs in its *own* TX, even when called from another TX. Classic use: writing an audit log\nthat must commit whether or not the outer business TX commits. **Exam trap** from the lesson:\nstudents assume REQUIRES_NEW \"protects\" the outer TX — it does NOT. If the inner throws a\nsystem exception that escapes, the outer still rolls back. Only a `try/catch` in the caller\nprotects it.","example":"```java\n@TransactionAttribute(REQUIRES_NEW)\npublic void audit(String event) {\n    em.persist(new AuditEntry(event));   // commits independently of caller\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"SUPPORTS — caller has TX vs no TX?","answer":"**Caller HAS TX:** joins it. **Caller NO TX:** runs without TX. Uses TX if available, otherwise none.","explanation":"The \"flexible\" attribute: happy to participate in a TX if one exists, happy to run without if not.\nTypically used for read-only methods where a caller may or may not care about TX context.\nBeware: running without a TX disables dirty checking — changes won't be flushed.","example":"```java\n@TransactionAttribute(SUPPORTS)\npublic Customer load(Long id) { return em.find(Customer.class, id); }\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"NOT\\_SUPPORTED — caller has TX vs no TX?","answer":"**Caller HAS TX:** SUSPENDS it, runs WITHOUT TX. **Caller NO TX:** runs without TX. Method NEVER has TX.","explanation":"Always runs *outside* any TX. If a TX was in progress, the container suspends it for the duration\nof the call and resumes it after. Useful for legacy or non-transactional resources, or slow\noperations you don't want holding locks. Quiz 4 Q4 = \"does NOT propagate, runs WITHOUT TX\" → this.","example":"```java\n@TransactionAttribute(NOT_SUPPORTED)\npublic void writeLogFile(String msg) { /* no DB — don't hold locks */ }\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"MANDATORY — caller has TX vs no TX?","answer":"**Caller HAS TX:** joins it. **Caller NO TX:** THROWS EJBTransactionRequiredException. Requires caller to already be in TX.","explanation":"\"I require that someone else already started a TX.\" Perfect for internal helper methods whose\nbehavior only makes sense inside a larger TX — calling them without one is a programming bug, and\nthe container surfaces that with `EJBTransactionRequiredException`.","example":"```java\n@TransactionAttribute(MANDATORY)\nvoid reserveInventory(Item i) {\n    // presumes caller already has a TX; else we throw\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"NEVER — caller has TX vs no TX?","answer":"**Caller HAS TX:** THROWS EJBException. **Caller NO TX:** runs without TX. Refuses to run in a TX context.","explanation":"The mirror image of MANDATORY — \"I will not tolerate being in a TX.\" Rare; used for code that\ncalls non-transactional systems where enlisting a TX would be harmful or simply unsupported.\nViolation throws `EJBException`, not `EJBTransactionRequiredException`.","example":"```java\n@TransactionAttribute(NEVER)\npublic void callLegacyNonXaSystem() { ... }\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"System exception vs application exception — what rolls back?","answer":"**System** (RuntimeException) → container auto-rolls-back, logs, wraps in EJBException. **Application** (@ApplicationException or any checked) → NO auto-rollback unless @ApplicationException(rollback=true).","explanation":"System exceptions signal \"the bean is broken\" — container rolls back, logs, and wraps in\n`EJBException`. Application exceptions signal \"business-logic issue\" (e.g. `InsufficientFundsException`)\nand by default the TX is NOT rolled back — the caller can catch and retry. Override with\n`@ApplicationException(rollback = true)` when a business exception should also roll back.","example":"```java\n@ApplicationException(rollback = true)\npublic class InsufficientFundsException extends Exception { }\n\npublic void withdraw(BigDecimal amt) throws InsufficientFundsException {\n    if (balance.compareTo(amt) \u003c 0) throw new InsufficientFundsException();\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"CMT vs BMT?","answer":"**Container-Managed Transactions** (default) — declarative via @TransactionAttribute. **Bean-Managed** — use UserTransaction via @Resource, call begin/commit/rollback manually. Annotate with @TransactionManagement(BEAN).","explanation":"CMT is almost always right: annotate and forget. BMT is for edge cases where you genuinely need\nfine-grained control — e.g. committing mid-method, overlapping TXs, or integrating with\nnon-EJB transactional resources. BMT ignores `@TransactionAttribute` entirely, which is a common\nsource of confusion.","example":"```java\n@Stateless\n@TransactionManagement(TransactionManagementType.BEAN)\npublic class ManualTxBean {\n    @Resource UserTransaction utx;\n    public void work() throws Exception {\n        utx.begin();\n        try { /* ... */ utx.commit(); }\n        catch (Exception e) { utx.rollback(); throw e; }\n    }\n}\n```"}]}]},{"id":"jee-infra","name":"Java EE infrastructure","topics":[{"id":"4911-security","name":"Security","tags":["security","tech"],"prose":"EJB security is checked per method invocation, not once per session. When a client calls a business method, the container intercepts the call before executing the bean code and asks two questions: (1) who is the caller's Principal (carried in the invocation context from the authenticated login), and (2) does that Principal hold any role listed in the method's @RolesAllowed?","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Declare roles a bean will use?","answer":"`@DeclareRoles({\"ADMIN\",\"USER\"})` at class level.","explanation":"`@DeclareRoles` announces to the container which role names this bean will reference — mostly\nrelevant for programmatic checks (`isCallerInRole`). Roles used by `@RolesAllowed` are discovered\nautomatically, so `@DeclareRoles` is only strictly needed when you use `isCallerInRole(\"FOO\")`\nwithout FOO appearing in a `@RolesAllowed`.","example":"```java\n@Stateless\n@DeclareRoles({\"ADMIN\", \"USER\", \"GUEST\"})\npublic class AccountService {\n    @Resource SessionContext ctx;\n    public boolean canDelete() { return ctx.isCallerInRole(\"ADMIN\"); }\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Restrict method to specific role(s)?","answer":"`@RolesAllowed({\"ADMIN\"})` on method or class. @RolesAllowed({}) = nobody.","explanation":"`@RolesAllowed` on the class sets a default for all methods; method-level annotations override.\nThe container checks the caller's principal *per method invocation* — if not in one of the roles,\nit throws `EJBAccessException` before the body runs. Empty array = `@DenyAll`.","example":"```java\n@Stateless\n@RolesAllowed(\"USER\")                               // class default\npublic class AccountService {\n    @RolesAllowed({\"ADMIN\", \"USER\"}) public void view(Long id) { }\n    @RolesAllowed(\"ADMIN\")           public void delete(Long id) { } // overrides\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"@PermitAll vs @DenyAll?","answer":"**@PermitAll** — any authenticated user (overrides class-level). **@DenyAll** — no one can call.","explanation":"Both are shorthand. `@PermitAll` on a method carves out a public hole in a locked-down class —\nany authenticated principal can invoke regardless of role. `@DenyAll` is its opposite for\ninternal/utility methods that should never be called from outside. MCQ trap: `@RolesAllowed({})`\nwith empty array is equivalent to `@DenyAll`.","example":"```java\n@Stateless\n@RolesAllowed(\"ADMIN\")\npublic class AdminService {\n    @PermitAll public String ping()     { return \"ok\"; }    // anyone auth'd\n    @DenyAll  public void   internal()  { }                  // blocked always\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does @RunAs do?","answer":"Executes the method under a DIFFERENT principal/role than the caller. Useful when a bean needs elevated privileges to call downstream beans.","explanation":"`@RunAs(\"SYSTEM\")` changes the propagated identity for *outgoing* calls the bean makes, not for\nauthorization of the inbound call. Classic use: a user-triggered action that must call a\nlocked-down audit or scheduling bean requiring a privileged role. Applies at class level.","example":"```java\n@Stateless\n@RunAs(\"SYSTEM\")                          // downstream calls use SYSTEM role\npublic class ScheduledJob {\n    @EJB AuditService audit;\n    public void run() { audit.log(\"job done\"); }   // audit sees SYSTEM, not caller\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Programmatic role check?","answer":"`sessionContext.isCallerInRole(\"ADMIN\")` — returns boolean. `sessionContext.getCallerPrincipal()` — returns Principal.","explanation":"Programmatic checks are for logic finer than an annotation can express — e.g. \"admins can edit\nany order, regular users can edit their own.\" Get the `SessionContext` via\n`@Resource SessionContext ctx;`. The returned `Principal`'s `getName()` is typically the logged-\nin username.","example":"```java\n@Stateless\npublic class OrderService {\n    @Resource SessionContext ctx;\n    public void edit(Order o) {\n        if (!ctx.isCallerInRole(\"ADMIN\") &&\n            !o.getOwner().equals(ctx.getCallerPrincipal().getName()))\n            throw new EJBAccessException();\n    }\n}\n```"}]},{"id":"4911-jndi-injection","name":"JNDI/Injection","tags":["jndi","tech"],"prose":"Every container-managed resource — another bean, a DataSource, an EntityManager — is ultimately bound into the server's JNDI tree at deploy time. Injection is convenience syntax: @EJB private PaymentService payment; tells the container \"at bean-creation time, look up PaymentService in JNDI and assign it to this field.\" The same lookup is available programmatically through InitialContext.lookup(name); injection just hides the string.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Inject another EJB?","answer":"`@EJB private MyBean bean;` — container resolves and injects reference.","explanation":"`@EJB` resolves by type by default — the container finds the matching bean in the JNDI tree and\nassigns it at bean-creation time. When multiple beans implement the same interface, disambiguate\nwith `beanName=\"…\"` or `lookup=\"java:global/...\"`. Works on fields, setters, and constructor\nparameters (in CDI-bridged environments).","example":"```java\n@Stateless\npublic class OrderService {\n    @EJB private PaymentService payment;                 // by type\n    @EJB(beanName = \"PrimaryCache\") private CacheBean p; // by name\n}\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Inject a resource (DataSource, Queue)?","answer":"`@Resource private DataSource ds;`. For JMS: `@Resource private ConnectionFactory cf;`.","explanation":"`@Resource` covers any container-managed *resource* — DataSources, JMS queues/topics, JMS\nConnectionFactories, TimerService, SessionContext, UserTransaction, env-entries. Use\n`lookup=\"...\"` or `name=\"...\"` to pin to a specific JNDI name when ambiguity exists. Think\n\"`@EJB` for EJBs, `@Resource` for everything else in JNDI, `@PersistenceContext` for EntityManager.\"","example":"```java\n@Resource(lookup = \"jdbc/myDS\") private DataSource ds;\n@Resource(lookup = \"jms/OrderQueue\") private Queue auditQueue;\n@Resource private SessionContext ctx;            // container context\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Three portable global JNDI name scopes?","answer":"1. `java:global/[app]/[module]/BeanName`\n2. `java:app/[module]/BeanName`\n3. `java:module/BeanName`\n\nPlus `java:comp/env` (ENC) for local references.","explanation":"`java:global` is visible server-wide; `java:app` is visible within the same EAR; `java:module`\nis visible within the same WAR/EJB-JAR; `java:comp/env` is the private Environment Naming\nContext for the bean. Injection hides the string, but you'll see these names in logs and when\ndoing programmatic `InitialContext.lookup(...)`.","example":"```java\n// Equivalent ways to grab the same bean from code:\nContext ctx = new InitialContext();\nOrderService o1 = (OrderService) ctx.lookup(\n    \"java:global/myApp/myModule/OrderService\");\nOrderService o2 = (OrderService) ctx.lookup(\n    \"java:module/OrderService\");\n```"}]}]},{"id":"process","name":"Unified Process & architecture","topics":[{"id":"4911-rup-phases","name":"RUP Phases","tags":["process","proc"],"prose":"Each iteration includes all workflows (req → analysis → design → impl → test). Number of iterations varies per phase: Inception 1-2, Elaboration 2-3, Construction 3-5, Transition 1-2.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"RUP phase order: Inception → \\_\\_\\_ → Construction → Transition.","answer":"**Elaboration**. Architecture baselined, ~80% of requirements captured here.","explanation":"Elaboration is the risk-reduction phase: you build *executable* slices of the architecturally\nriskiest use cases to prove the design actually works. By end-of-phase (~LCA), the architecture\nis locked and 80% of requirements are known so Construction can scale out. Skipping Elaboration\nis the classic waterfall mistake the iterative process is designed to prevent.","example":"```text\nElaboration iterations (2-3):\n  E1: tracer bullet — login + DB round-trip proven\n  E2: payment + persistence stack proven end-to-end\n  → LCA signed → architecture baseline locked\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"RUP phase order: Inception → Elaboration → \\_\\_\\_ → Transition.","answer":"**Construction**. Build + integrate + test most functionality; ~50% of total effort.","explanation":"Construction sits between architecture-baseline (Elaboration/LCA) and deployment (Transition/PR).\nBy this point the risky pieces have been proven in Elaboration, so Construction is about\n*volume* — turn the remaining use cases into working, integrated, tested code.","example":"```text\nInception (~10%) → Elaboration (~30%) → Construction (~50%) → Transition (~10%)\n    LCO              LCA                    IOC                  PR\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Milestone at the end of Inception: \\_\\_\\_.","answer":"**LCO** — Life-Cycle Objectives. Agrees on vision, scope, feasibility.","explanation":"LCO = \"do we agree on *what* we're building and *why*?\" It's a go/no-go gate where stakeholders\nsign off on vision, scope, initial business case, and rough cost estimate. Failing LCO means\nkilling the project before it burns Elaboration money.","example":"```text\nInception deliverables reviewed at LCO:\n- Vision document\n- Initial use-case model (~20%)\n- Business case\n- Risk list\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Milestone at the end of Elaboration: \\_\\_\\_.","answer":"**LCA** — Life-Cycle Architecture. Stable baseline + major risks mitigated.","explanation":"LCA says \"the architecture is proven, the riskiest use cases have been implemented end-to-end,\nand we can confidently plan Construction.\" Missing LCA = you enter Construction with untested\narchitecture = the RUP anti-pattern that iterative development is designed to avoid.","example":"```text\nElaboration deliverables reviewed at LCA:\n- Baselined architecture description\n- ~80% of use cases captured\n- Executable architecture (runs the hardest UCs)\n- Refined risk list\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Milestone at the end of Construction: \\_\\_\\_.","answer":"**IOC** — Initial Operating Capability. Beta-ready build.","explanation":"IOC means \"the product is good enough to put in front of real users for beta.\" All remaining\nfunctionality is implemented, integrated, and tested to the level that external users can\nmeaningfully try it. Failing IOC pushes the beta release back.","example":"```text\nAt IOC you typically have:\n- All planned features coded + unit/integration tested\n- Beta deployment packaged\n- User docs drafted\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Milestone at the end of Transition: \\_\\_\\_.","answer":"**PR** — Product Release. Deployed, trained, handed off.","explanation":"PR = the project ends. The product is in production, users are trained, support is handed off to\nops / customer service, and the project team closes out. Post-mortem happens here.","example":"```text\nAt PR you typically have:\n- Production deployment\n- Training materials + delivered training\n- Support/ops handoff signed\n- Final project retrospective\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Primary focus of Inception?","answer":"1. Business case\n2. Vision\n3. Scope\n4. Feasibility\n5. Preliminary risks\n\nShort phase (~10% of project). Output: LCO milestone.","explanation":"Inception is the *\"should we do this?\"* phase — tiny investment to answer it. Output is the LCO\nmilestone: a go/no-go decision backed by a vision doc, business case, scope sketch, and a first\npass at the risk list. If any of these don't close out, the project dies here instead of wasting\nConstruction-level money.","example":"```text\nStartup pitches \"AI-powered coffee app\":\nInception (1-2 iterations):\n  - Vision: peer-to-peer coffee recommendations\n  - Business case: $500k dev / 10k users year 1\n  - Scope: MVP = search + save + rate\n  - Risk: ML quality, user acquisition\n→ LCO signed → proceed to Elaboration\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which RUP phase has the greatest analysis workflow?","answer":"**Elaboration.** ~80% of requirements captured, architecture baselined. Longest phase of project by duration.","explanation":"On the \"hump chart,\" the Analysis & Design workflow peaks in Elaboration because this is when\nthe architecture is proven by building executable slices of the hardest use cases. Requirements\nwork also climbs here to reach ~80% captured, so Analysis & Design feeds off a stabilizing req set.","example":"```text\nHump chart peaks:\n  Requirements  → Inception + Elaboration\n  Analysis/Des. → Elaboration      ← HIGHEST\n  Implementation→ Construction\n  Test          → Construction + Transition\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Primary focus of Construction?","answer":"Implement remaining functionality, integrate, comprehensive testing. ~50% of project effort. Output: IOC milestone.","explanation":"Construction is the \"bulk build-out\" phase and carries the largest slice of total effort (~50%).\nMultiple iterations (3-5 typical) each deliver more working features on top of the baselined\narchitecture from Elaboration. Late-breaking architecture changes here are a red flag — they\nshould have surfaced earlier.","example":"```text\nConstruction iterations (3-5):\n  C1: user login + search (2 weeks)\n  C2: save + rate + admin (2 weeks)\n  C3: payment + shipping (2 weeks)\n  C4: reports + hardening (2 weeks)\n→ IOC signed → beta release\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What happens during Transition?","answer":"1. Beta release\n2. User acceptance testing\n3. Deployment\n4. Training\n5. Support handoff\n\nOutput: PR milestone (Product Release). Phase during which product moves to beta.","explanation":"Transition converts a feature-complete build (IOC) into a supported product (PR). Emphasis\nshifts from writing code to validating the system with real users, cleaning up defects, packaging\ndocumentation, training users/ops, and handing the baby to the support org. Short phase (~10%).","example":"```text\nTransition activities:\n  - Beta → gather feedback → bug-fix\n  - UAT with real customer reps\n  - Deploy to production environment\n  - Train end users + support staff\n  - Hand off to ops / close project\n```"}]},{"id":"4911-best-practices","name":"Best Practices","tags":["process","proc"],"prose":"Waterfall: high risk sustained until late → problems surface near end → expensive fix. Iterative: risk reduced continuously → problems surface early → course-correct cheaply.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Six software best practices (RUP)?","answer":"1. Develop iteratively\n2. Manage requirements\n3. Use component-based architectures\n4. Model visually (UML)\n5. Verify quality\n6. Control changes","explanation":"Each best practice maps to a common root cause of software project failure: waterfall-style late\ndiscovery → iterative; requirement drift → traceability; monolithic coupling → components;\nambiguous specs → UML; defect surprise → continuous quality verification; chaos → config/change\ncontrol. Memorize the list — these and the nine workflows are frequent RUP exam fodder.","example":"```text\nPractice                          Addresses\n1 Develop iteratively             → late risk discovery\n2 Manage requirements             → scope creep / drift\n3 Use component-based arch.       → brittle monoliths\n4 Model visually (UML)            → spec ambiguity\n5 Verify quality                  → late defect discovery\n6 Control changes                 → uncontrolled modifications\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Why iterative \u003e waterfall (risk curve)?","answer":"Waterfall: risk stays high, problems found late (expensive to fix). Iterative: each iteration exposes + mitigates risk early → steadily declining risk curve.","explanation":"In waterfall, requirements defects only surface during test (near the end), by which point they're\nbaked into the design + code + everything downstream. Iterative development exposes a slice of\nrisk every iteration, so problems are smaller and cheaper to fix. The risk curve shape — not the\ntotal defects — is the real difference.","example":"```text\nWaterfall: risk ────────────────── STAYS HIGH ─── drops at test\nIterative: risk ╲╱╲╱╲╱╲╱╲╱ steady decline per iteration\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which practice addresses \"brittle architectures\"?","answer":"**Use Component-Based Architectures** — separates concerns, enables reuse, reduces coupling.","explanation":"Brittle = small change ripples everywhere. Component-based architecture hides implementation\nbehind interfaces, allowing parts to evolve independently. EJB itself embodies this: bean types\nare components with well-defined contracts, injected via interface, versionable independently.","example":"```java\n// Brittle: direct coupling to SQL\n// Better: swap-replaceable component behind interface\npublic interface PaymentGateway { void charge(...); }\n@Stateless public class StripeGateway implements PaymentGateway { ... }\n@Stateless public class PaypalGateway implements PaymentGateway { ... }\n```"}]},{"id":"4911-workflows","name":"Workflows","tags":["proc"],"prose":"Cards covering Workflows.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"The nine RUP workflows split into six engineering plus three \\_\\_\\_ workflows.","answer":"**supporting** (cross-cutting). Supporting = Configuration & Change Mgmt, Project Mgmt, Environment.","explanation":"The six *engineering* workflows produce the product (Business Modeling → Requirements → Analysis\n& Design → Implementation → Test → Deployment). The three *supporting* workflows aren't about\nbuilding the product — they keep the team functioning (Config/Change Mgmt, Project Mgmt,\nEnvironment). All nine run in *every* phase, just at different intensities.","example":"```text\nEngineering (6):        Supporting (3):\n1 Business Modeling      7 Configuration & Change Mgmt\n2 Requirements           8 Project Management\n3 Analysis & Design      9 Environment\n4 Implementation\n5 Test\n6 Deployment\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Engineering workflow sequence: Business Modeling → Requirements → \\_\\_\\_ → Implementation → Test → Deployment.","answer":"**Analysis & Design**.","explanation":"Analysis & Design sits between capturing what the user wants (Requirements) and writing the code\n(Implementation). *Analysis* produces technology-independent BCE classes; *Design* refines them\ninto framework-specific classes (e.g. `@Entity`, JSF pages, EJBs). On the hump chart, this\nworkflow peaks in Elaboration.","example":"```text\nBook-a-flight use case:\n  Requirements  → UC narrative + main/alt flows\n  Analysis      → SearchFlights (boundary), BookingCtrl (control), Flight (entity)\n  Design        → JSF page + @Stateless BookingService + @Entity Flight\n  Implementation→ concrete Java + JSF code\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Supporting workflow responsible for tracking change requests + baselines: \\_\\_\\_.","answer":"**Configuration & Change Management**.","explanation":"C&CM owns the who-changed-what-when story: version control, branch strategy, change-request\ntracking, baselines/releases. It is what makes \"which version did the customer see?\" answerable.\nDistinct from Project Management (cost/schedule) and Environment (tooling infrastructure).","example":"```text\nCCM activities: Git/SVN discipline · PR reviews · release tagging ·\n                change-request triage · baseline freeze before LCA\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Supporting workflow responsible for team tooling + process infrastructure: \\_\\_\\_.","answer":"**Environment**. Provides the tools/methods the team uses.","explanation":"Environment is the workflow that *sets up how you work*: CI server, IDEs, build tool, coding\nstandards, the RUP process itself. Easy to confuse with Deployment (which is *delivering the\nproduct* to users). Environment = tooling for the team; Deployment = shipping to the customer.","example":"```text\nEnvironment deliverables:\n  - CI/CD pipeline\n  - Code style + lint rules\n  - Adopted UML tool\n  - Tailored RUP process\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What is a \"hump chart\"?","answer":"Graph showing effort distribution of each workflow across all phases. E.g., requirements hump peaks in Inception/Elaboration; implementation hump peaks in Construction.","explanation":"Each \"hump\" is one workflow's effort over time. The shape makes two RUP claims visually obvious:\n(1) every workflow runs in every phase (no pure-waterfall steps), and (2) different workflows\npeak in different phases (Requirements early, Implementation mid, Test late). Expect an exam\nquestion asking which workflow peaks in which phase.","example":"```text\n           Incep | Elab | Constr | Trans\nRequirements  ▂  |  ▅   |   ▃    |   ▁\nAnalysis/Des. ▁  |  ▆   |   ▂    |   ▁\nImplementation▁  |  ▂   |   ▆    |   ▃\nTest          ▁  |  ▂   |   ▅    |   ▅\nDeployment    ▁  |  ▁   |   ▂    |   ▅\n```"}]},{"id":"4911-use-cases","name":"Use Cases","tags":["use-cases","proc"],"prose":"Cards covering Use Cases.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"How do use cases drive development?","answer":"They are primary artifact. Drive:\n1. Analysis classes + use-case realizations\n2. Design-level realizations\n3. Implementation structure\n4. Test cases\n5. Iteration planning (prioritized UCs picked per iteration)","explanation":"\"Use-case driven\" is RUP's central commitment — one UC threads from requirements to analysis to\ndesign to code to test to iteration plan. That's why the big-picture diagram in the lesson shows\nthe UC as the hub with arrows to all six workflows. Bruce specifically called out the big-picture\nquestion as an exam failure mode: students get lost in details and miss this integrating idea.","example":"```text\nUC \"Book Flight\" →\n  Requirements:   UC narrative (main + alt flows)\n  Analysis:       BookFlightPage (B), BookCtrl (C), Flight (E)\n  Design:         JSF page, @Stateless BookService, @Entity Flight\n  Implementation: concrete code\n  Test:           one test per flow (main + alternates)\n  Plan:           scheduled in iteration 3 due to risk + value\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Three class stereotypes in analysis model?","answer":"1. **Boundary** (UI / external interface)\n2. **Control** (workflow orchestration)\n3. **Entity** (persistent domain objects)\n\n\"BCE\".","explanation":"BCE is a technology-independent way to classify analysis classes by *role*. Boundary faces the\noutside world (UI widgets, external APIs), Entity holds persistent state (domain objects), and\nControl orchestrates the flow between them for a given use case. In design, Boundary becomes JSF\npages, Entity becomes `@Entity`, Control becomes a `@Stateless` service.","example":"```text\nBook Flight UC analysis classes:\n  Boundary: BookFlightPage       ← UI (one per actor/UC)\n  Control:  BookFlightController ← orchestrates workflow\n  Entity:   Flight, Booking      ← domain model\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Rule for number of Boundary classes per use case?","answer":"One Boundary per Actor-UseCase pair (each actor sees a different interface). Control classes: typically one per use case. Entities: from domain model.","explanation":"If two actors participate in the same UC, you get two Boundaries because each actor has a\ndifferent view (e.g. Customer uses a web page; PaymentGateway talks to an adapter). Control = one\nper UC by default because each UC has its own workflow. Entities come from the domain model, so\nmultiple UCs may share an Entity.","example":"```text\nUC \"Book Flight\" (actors: Customer, PaymentGateway):\n  Boundary (×2): BookFlightPage (Customer), PaymentAdapter (Gateway)\n  Control (×1):  BookFlightController\n  Entity (n):    Flight, Booking, Customer, Payment\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Who is responsible for integrity of the analysis model?","answer":"**Architect / System Analyst.** (Quiz 4 answer: System Analyst — owns the analysis model as a whole.)","explanation":"Quiz 4 Q18 gave the canonical answer as *System Analyst*. The role is responsible for ensuring\nthe analysis model stays consistent — naming, responsibilities, BCE stereotypes, use-case\nrealizations. Individual use-case realizations are authored by analysts but the overall model\nintegrity is a single role's responsibility.","example":"```text\nArtifact                          Responsible role\nAnalysis model (whole)            System Analyst\nUse-case realization (one UC)     Use-case engineer / designer\nDesign model                      Architect\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What diagram shows analysis objects interacting?","answer":"**Collaboration Diagram** (shows object interactions with links + messages; emphasizes structure over time).","explanation":"Quiz 4 Q17 answer. A collaboration diagram (UML 1.x; renamed \"communication diagram\" in UML 2)\nshows objects linked together with numbered messages flowing along those links — it highlights\nstructure (who is connected to whom) whereas a sequence diagram emphasizes *time* (vertical\nlifeline ordering). Analysis-level use-case realizations typically use collaboration diagrams.","example":"```text\n(Customer) — 1: book(flight) → [BookFlightPage]\n                  2: process() ↓\n                [BookFlightCtrl] — 3: save → [Booking]\n                                   4: charge → [Payment]\n```"}]},{"id":"4911-architecture","name":"Architecture","tags":["architecture","proc"],"prose":"Bruce: appeared on midterm, NOT on final. Keep light.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"4+1 view model — name the five views?","answer":"1. **Logical** (structure)\n2. **Process** (concurrency)\n3. **Implementation** (code/modules)\n4. **Deployment** (hardware)\n5. **Use-Case** (the +1, ties others)\n\n*Bruce: NOT on final — light knowledge only.*","explanation":"Kruchten's 4+1 view model documents architecture from four stakeholder perspectives plus a\ncross-cutting use-case view that links them. Logical = class/package structure (developer).\nProcess = threads/processes (integrator). Implementation = modules/components (programmer).\nDeployment = nodes/hardware (sysadmin). Bruce flagged this as midterm-only — *light* knowledge\nis enough for the final.","example":"```text\n4+1 view        Audience         Diagram\nLogical         developer        class / package\nProcess         integrator       activity / sequence\nImplementation  programmer       component\nDeployment      sysadmin         deployment\nUse-case (+1)   everyone         use case\n```"}]},{"id":"4911-rup-concepts","name":"RUP Concepts","tags":["process","proc"],"prose":"Cards covering RUP Concepts.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"General term for any information created/used by workers?","answer":"**Artifact.** Documents, models, code, test plans, etc. — anything produced or consumed during the process.","explanation":"RUP vocabulary: *workers* perform *activities* that produce/consume *artifacts*. An artifact is\nthe generic container — the Vision doc, a UML diagram, a Java source file, a test script, a\nrisk list all count. Understanding the term matters because exam questions often phrase\ndeliverables abstractly (\"which artifact captures ...\").","example":"```text\nWorkflow          Typical artifacts\nRequirements      Vision doc · Use-case model · SRS\nAnalysis/Design   Analysis model · Design model · architecture doc\nImplementation    Source code · build scripts\nTest              Test plan · test cases · defect log\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which requirements activity determines order of UC development across iterations?","answer":"**Prioritize Use Cases.** Drives iteration planning — highest-risk + highest-value UCs scheduled early.","explanation":"\"Prioritize Use Cases\" is the bridge from requirements to iteration planning. You order UCs by a\ncombination of risk (build risky ones early so failures are cheap) and business value (customers\nwant the high-value features) plus dependencies. This is why Elaboration iterations tackle the\narchitecturally riskiest UCs — proving them early de-risks Construction.","example":"```text\nUC                     Risk  Value  Iteration\nUser login             low   med    Construction 1\nFlight search          med   high   Elaboration 2\nPayment processing     HIGH  high   Elaboration 1   ← risky → scheduled first\nReports                low   low    Construction 4\n```"}]}]},{"id":"soft-skills","name":"Testing, EVMS & soft skills","topics":[{"id":"4911-evms","name":"EVMS","tags":["evms","proc"],"prose":"Note: some sources use CV = ACWP − BCWP (reversed convention). Stick with the convention in the course slides: CV = BCWP − ACWP.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"What does BCWS / PV stand for?","answer":"**B**udgeted **C**ost of **W**ork **S**cheduled = **P**lanned **V**alue. Cost of work PLANNED through a given date.","explanation":"BCWS is the *plan*: \"by April 20, we said we'd have completed tasks totalling $100k of budgeted\nwork.\" It is a point on the planned spend curve, independent of what actually happened. The\nbaseline against which both progress (BCWP) and spend (ACWP) are compared.","example":"```text\nPlan at week 10: design done ($40k) + half of coding done ($60k)\n→ BCWS = $40k + $60k = $100k\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does BCWP / EV stand for?","answer":"**B**udgeted **C**ost of **W**ork **P**erformed = **E**arned **V**alue. Budgeted cost of work ACTUALLY completed.","explanation":"BCWP measures *how much work has been finished*, priced at the budget rate (not actual cost).\nIt is \"earned\" value because the project earns the budgeted amount each time work is completed.\nCompared against BCWS it tells schedule; compared against ACWP it tells cost efficiency.","example":"```text\nWeek 10: design done ($40k budgeted) + 1/3 of coding done ($40k budgeted of $120k)\n→ BCWP = $40k + $40k = $80k earned\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does ACWP / AC stand for?","answer":"**A**ctual **C**ost of **W**ork **P**erformed. Actual cost incurred for completed work.","explanation":"ACWP is the *real money spent* on whatever work has been completed. Difference between ACWP and\nBCWP tells you whether that completed work was over or under budget. ACWP includes salaries,\ntools, licenses — every dollar actually paid, not estimated.","example":"```text\nWeek 10: design + 1/3 coding completed — invoices totalled $90k\n→ ACWP = $90k  (BCWP = $80k → $10k over budget for work done)\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Cost Variance (CV) formula?","answer":"**CV = BCWP − ACWP**. Positive = under budget. Negative = over budget.","explanation":"The course convention (and Bruce's slides) is **CV = BCWP − ACWP** — earned minus actual.\nMnemonic: \"Earned beats Actual is good\" → positive = under budget. Warning: some textbooks\nreverse the convention; stick with the slides for this class.","example":"```text\nBCWP = $80k, ACWP = $90k\nCV = 80 − 90 = −$10k  → OVER budget\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Schedule Variance (SV) formula?","answer":"**SV = BCWP − BCWS**. Positive = ahead of schedule. Negative = behind.","explanation":"SV compares what we've *earned* against what we *planned* to earn by this date. Expressed in\ndollars, not days, because EVMS abstracts schedule into \"work completed\" terms. Negative SV\nmeans we've completed less than planned.","example":"```text\nBCWP = $80k, BCWS = $100k\nSV = 80 − 100 = −$20k  → BEHIND schedule\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"CPI (Cost Performance Index) formula?","answer":"**CPI = BCWP / ACWP**. \u003e1 = efficient. \u003c1 = over budget.","explanation":"CPI is the *ratio* form of CV: how many dollars of budgeted work did we earn per dollar actually\nspent? CPI = 0.9 means each $1 spent only produces $0.90 of earned work — we're 10% over\nbudget. Simple health indicator often reported on dashboards.","example":"```text\nBCWP = $80k, ACWP = $90k\nCPI = 80 / 90 ≈ 0.89  → 11% over budget\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"SPI (Schedule Performance Index) formula?","answer":"**SPI = BCWP / BCWS**. \u003e1 = ahead. \u003c1 = behind.","explanation":"SPI is the ratio form of SV. SPI = 0.8 means we've earned only 80% of what we planned to earn by\nthis date — 20% behind schedule. Again expressed in work-completed terms, not calendar days.","example":"```text\nBCWP = $80k, BCWS = $100k\nSPI = 80 / 100 = 0.8  → 20% behind schedule\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"What does EAC stand for?","answer":"**E**stimate **A**t **C**ompletion. Projected total cost at project end. **EAC = BAC / CPI**.","explanation":"EAC forecasts the final cost of the project assuming current cost efficiency (CPI) continues.\nBAC = Budget At Completion (the total original budget). If CPI is 0.9, final cost is projected\nto be BAC / 0.9 — about 11% over budget. A gold-standard executive-dashboard metric.","example":"```text\nBAC = $500k (original budget), CPI = 0.89\nEAC = 500 / 0.89 ≈ $562k  → forecast $62k overrun\n```"}]},{"id":"4911-testing","name":"Testing","tags":["testing","proc"],"prose":"Test levels Unit — individual components in isolation (white-box) Integration — component interactions System — end-to-end, full behavior (black-box) Acceptance — user validation against requirements (black-box — Quiz 4 Q9) Test types (Quiz 4 tested) Performance — response time + processing time (Quiz 4 Q6) Load — concurrent users / throughput Volume — large data Configuration — different environments / hardware / OS White-box vs Black-box White-box: knows internal code (unit tests) Black-box: tests I/O behavior only (system, acceptance)","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Which test verifies response + processing time?","answer":"**Performance test.** (Other types: volume = data load, configuration = different envs, load = concurrent users.)","explanation":"Quiz 4 Q6 answer. **Performance** = individual response/processing time under expected load.\n**Load** = many concurrent users / throughput. **Volume** = large data sizes. **Configuration**\n= different environments / hardware / OS. Don't confuse performance with load — a system can be\nfast at low concurrency and collapse under real load.","example":"```text\nType            Asks...\nPerformance     \"How fast does one user's checkout complete?\"\nLoad            \"Can 1000 users check out simultaneously?\"\nVolume          \"Does search work with 10M rows?\"\nConfiguration   \"Does it run on RHEL 8 AND Windows Server?\"\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"User acceptance tests are usually what type?","answer":"**Black-box tests** — exercise system externally, no internal knowledge. (White-box = unit tests with code visibility.)","explanation":"Quiz 4 Q9 answer. UAT is black-box because users validate the system against the requirements\n(use cases) without caring about the implementation. White-box testing is the opposite — tests\nwritten with visibility into the code, typically at unit level (branch/path coverage).","example":"```text\nBlack-box (input → output):         White-box (code visibility):\n  System test                         Unit test\n  Acceptance test                     Branch/path coverage\n  Performance test\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Four main test levels?","answer":"1. Unit (components isolated, white-box)\n2. Integration (component interactions)\n3. System (end-to-end, black-box)\n4. Acceptance (user validation against requirements)","explanation":"The levels ladder up in scope: a *unit* is one method/class in isolation, *integration* is\nseveral units working together, *system* is the full app end-to-end in a prod-like environment,\nand *acceptance* is the user's validation that requirements are met. Unit tests are white-box;\nsystem and acceptance are black-box; integration is usually grey-box.","example":"```text\nLevel        Scope                               Written by\nUnit         single class / method               developers\nIntegration  multiple units + DB / messaging     developers + QA\nSystem       full stack end-to-end               QA\nAcceptance   use-case main + alt flows           users / product\n```"}]},{"id":"4911-mbti","name":"MBTI","tags":["mbti","proc"],"prose":"Quiz 4 was saturated with MBTI questions — high probability on final.","cards":[{"type":"name","prompt":"Four MBTI dimensions?","answer":"1. **E/I** (Extraversion/Introversion — attitude to world)\n2. **S/N** (Sensing/Intuition — perception)\n3. **T/F** (Thinking/Feeling — judging function)\n4. **J/P** (Judging/Perceiving — lifestyle)","explanation":"Bruce hammered MBTI on Quiz 4 — high probability on the final. Memorize the dimension labels\n*and* their meaning tags: E/I = attitude, S/N = perception, T/F = judging function, J/P =\nouter-world lifestyle. The tricky trap is that \"Perceiving\" (J/P pole) is NOT the same as a\n\"perceiving function\" (S or N).","example":"```text\nDimension   Poles              Tag\nE/I         Extra / Intro      attitude toward the world\nS/N         Sensing / iNt.     perception function\nT/F         Think / Feel       judging function\nJ/P         Judge / Perceive   outer-world lifestyle\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which dimension is an \"attitude toward the world\"?","answer":"**Introversion / Extraversion.** (J/P = attitude toward outer world lifestyle; S/N = perception; T/F = judging.)","explanation":"E/I is the \"where does your energy come from / how do you engage the world\" dimension. J/P is a\nrelated but different axis (\"outer-world *lifestyle*\"). If a question says \"attitude toward the\nworld\" — answer is E/I. If it says \"attitude toward the *outer* world\" specifically with a\nlifestyle slant — that's J/P. Read carefully.","example":"```text\nKeyword in question            Dimension\n\"attitude toward the world\"    E / I\n\"outer-world lifestyle\"        J / P\n\"perception\"                   S / N\n\"judging function\"             T / F\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"People who prefer Perceiving…?","answer":"**Enjoy surprises.** Flexible, open-ended, adaptive. (Judging = decide quickly, tight schedules.)","explanation":"Perceivers (P) like keeping options open, adapt well to change, and genuinely *enjoy surprises*.\nJudgers (J) are the mirror: want closure, deadlines, structure. \"Perceiving\" the lifestyle (P on\nJ/P axis) is distinct from \"perceiving functions\" (S and N on the S/N axis) — easy to trip up on.","example":"```text\nPreference   Behavior            Phrase\nPerceiving   flexible, adaptive  \"enjoy surprises\"\nJudging      plan-driven         \"decide quickly\"\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"People who prefer Feeling…?","answer":"**Are fair.** Value-driven, empathetic. (Thinking = analytical, objective.)","explanation":"Feelers make decisions using values and empathy — the slides use the tag \"fair.\" Thinkers decide\nvia logic and objective criteria. Both are *judging* functions (they decide); they just decide\ndifferently.","example":"```text\nFeeling  → \"Are fair\" (values + empathy)\nThinking → analytical, objective, criteria-driven\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"People who prefer Judging…?","answer":"**Decide quickly.** Want closure, schedules, structure.","explanation":"J on the J/P axis manifests as plan-driven behavior: close decisions early, stick to schedules,\nprefer structure. Pair with E/I for team dynamics — an ISTJ will plan meticulously in\nsolitude; an ESTJ will drive group closure visibly.","example":"```text\nSituation: project planning meeting\n  Judging type: \"Let's lock the schedule today\"\n  Perceiving:   \"Let's keep options open a bit longer\"\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"People who prefer Intuition…?","answer":"**Like solving new complex problems.** Pattern-oriented, future-focused. (Sensing = details, facts, practical.)","explanation":"Intuitives (N) think in patterns, abstractions, future possibilities — the slides tag them\n\"like solving new complex problems.\" Sensors (S) trust facts, details, the here and now. Both\nare *perceiving* functions (how you gather information).","example":"```text\nIntuition (N) → \"Like solving new complex problems\" (patterns, future)\nSensing   (S) → details, facts, practical, concrete\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which is a \"judging function\"?","answer":"**Thinking** (and Feeling). Judging functions DECIDE. (Perceiving functions = Sensing + Intuition: they GATHER info.)","explanation":"The \"function\" terminology is separate from the J/P axis — that's Bruce's trap question.\n*Judging functions* = Thinking + Feeling (both decide). *Perceiving functions* = Sensing +\nIntuition (both gather info). The J/P *axis* just names which of those two function types a\nperson prefers to show externally.","example":"```text\nFunction type   Members          What they do\nJudging         Thinking, Feel.  DECIDE\nPerceiving      Sensing, Intu.   GATHER info\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"Which is a \"perceiving function\"?","answer":"**Sensing** (and Intuition). Perceiving functions GATHER info.","explanation":"Sensing and Intuition are the two ways people *perceive* (gather information). Sensing trusts\nconcrete facts; Intuition trusts patterns/possibilities. Do not confuse \"perceiving function\"\n(S or N) with the J/P axis pole \"Perceiving\" — Bruce deliberately sets this as a trap.","example":"```text\nPerceiving functions (gather information):\n  Sensing   — facts, details, concrete\n  Intuition — patterns, possibilities, abstract\n```"},{"type":"name","prompt":"People who prefer Extraversion…?","answer":"**Prefer face-to-face communication.** Think out loud, energized by people. (Introverts: think before responding, prefer written communication.)","explanation":"The slides' short tag for Extraversion is *\"face-to-face communication.\"* Introverts prefer\nwritten/async and need time to formulate responses. Team-building implication: mixing E and I\ntypists on a team means supporting both real-time and async modes of work.","example":"```text\nExtravert (E) — \"face-to-face communication\", thinks out loud\nIntrovert (I) — reflective, prefers written async, needs time to respond\n```"}]}]}],"mockExam":{"duration_seconds":7200,"questions":[{"id":"q1","type":"MCQ","topic":"Session Beans","marks":2,"question":"Which annotation indicates that a Singleton session bean should be instantiated when the application is deployed?","correct":1,"rationale":"@Startup forces container to instantiate at deploy time rather than first-call. @DependsOn controls init ORDER between singletons.","choices":["@PostConstruct","@Startup","@DependsOn","@Eager","@EarlyInit"]},{"id":"q2","type":"MCQ","topic":"Session Beans","marks":2,"question":"Which of the following describes the concurrency behaviour of a Singleton session bean method annotated with @Lock(READ)?","correct":1,"rationale":"READ lock = many readers concurrently, WRITE = exclusive. READ blocks ONLY while a WRITE is active.","choices":["Only one thread at a time","Multiple concurrent readers; exclusive writer","No concurrency control","No access during WRITE lock only","Strict serialized access"]},{"id":"q3","type":"MCQ","topic":"EntityManager","marks":2,"question":"Which of the following will re-attach a detached entity to the persistence context?","correct":3,"rationale":"merge() returns a managed COPY. persist() throws on detached. attach()/reattach() don't exist.","choices":["persist()","attach()","reattach()","merge()","refresh()"]},{"id":"q4","type":"MCQ","topic":"Mapping","marks":2,"question":"What attribute indicates that a field of an entity bean should not be persisted to the database?","correct":1,"rationale":"@Transient. Others are fake distractors (classic trap).","choices":["@Virtual","@Transient","@NoPersist","@Skip","@Exclude"]},{"id":"q5","type":"MCQ","topic":"Mapping","marks":2,"question":"According to the text, which of the following is true of the @Table annotation?","correct":2,"rationale":"Optional. Default table name = class name. Use @Table(name=\"...\") to override.","choices":["Required for every entity","Default table name = property name","Optional; defaults to class name","Cannot be overridden","Only usable with @IdClass"]},{"id":"q6","type":"MCQ","topic":"Relationships","marks":2,"question":"In a one-to-many bidirectional relationship between entity beans, the owning side is","correct":1,"rationale":"MANY side holds the FK → is the owning side. ONE side uses @OneToMany(mappedBy=\"...\").","choices":["The ONE side (uses @OneToMany)","The MANY side (uses @ManyToOne + @JoinColumn)","Whichever side is declared first","Always @OneToMany with @JoinTable","Neither side"]},{"id":"q7","type":"MCQ","topic":"Relationships","marks":2,"question":"Which CascadeType causes a DELETE operation on a parent entity to propagate to its child entities?","correct":2,"rationale":"CascadeType.REMOVE (or ALL). orphanRemoval deletes orphans on removal from collection — a related but different mechanism.","choices":["CascadeType.PERSIST","CascadeType.MERGE","CascadeType.REMOVE","CascadeType.REFRESH","orphanRemoval only"]},{"id":"q8","type":"MCQ","topic":"Inheritance","marks":2,"question":"What is the default entity inheritance strategy in Jakarta Persistence?","correct":2,"rationale":"SINGLE\\_TABLE — all subclasses in one table with a discriminator column. Fast queries, simple schema.","choices":["JOINED","TABLE\\_PER\\_CLASS","SINGLE\\_TABLE","MAPPED\\_SUPERCLASS","NONE"]},{"id":"q9","type":"MCQ","topic":"JPQL","marks":2,"question":"Which JPQL clause is used to eagerly fetch a related entity in the same query, avoiding the N+1 select problem?","correct":2,"rationale":"JOIN FETCH eagerly loads a related entity in the same SQL query.","choices":["SELECT DISTINCT","LEFT JOIN","JOIN FETCH","WHERE EXISTS","ORDER BY"]},{"id":"q10","type":"MCQ","topic":"JPQL","marks":2,"question":"Which method on the Query interface is used to execute an UPDATE or DELETE JPQL statement?","correct":2,"rationale":"executeUpdate() returns affected row count. Only for INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE.","choices":["getResultList()","getSingleResult()","executeUpdate()","commit()","run()"]},{"id":"q11","type":"MCQ","topic":"Transactions","marks":2,"question":"Which transaction attribute does not propagate the transaction scope from the caller, and runs the annotated method with a new transaction?","correct":1,"rationale":"REQUIRES\\_NEW: ALWAYS runs in a new TX, suspending any caller TX. Quiz 4 Q13.","choices":["REQUIRED","REQUIRES\\_NEW","SUPPORTS","NOT\\_SUPPORTED","MANDATORY"]},{"id":"q12","type":"MCQ","topic":"Transactions","marks":2,"question":"Which ACID property requires a transaction to execute completely or not at all?","correct":0,"rationale":"Atomicity. Quiz 4 Q8.","choices":["Atomicity","Consistency","Isolation","Durability"]},{"id":"q13","type":"MCQ","topic":"Transactions","marks":2,"question":"Which transaction attribute requires that the caller have an existing transaction (throwing an exception if not), and runs the annotated method in the caller's transaction?","correct":3,"rationale":"MANDATORY = caller must already be in TX. If not, EJBTransactionRequiredException.","choices":["REQUIRED","REQUIRES\\_NEW","SUPPORTS","MANDATORY","NEVER"]},{"id":"q14","type":"MCQ","topic":"Security","marks":2,"question":"Which annotation is used to declare the role names that a bean will reference?","correct":1,"rationale":"@DeclareRoles lists every role name the bean will reference. @RolesAllowed grants access to a specific method.","choices":["@RolesAllowed","@DeclareRoles","@Security","@PermitAll","@RunAs"]},{"id":"q15","type":"MCQ","topic":"Callbacks","marks":2,"question":"Which entity lifecycle callback is invoked after an entity has been loaded from the database?","correct":1,"rationale":"@PostLoad. There is no @PreLoad in JPA.","choices":["@PreLoad","@PostLoad","@AfterFetch","@PostPersist","@PostUpdate"]},{"id":"q16","type":"MCQ","topic":"RUP Phases","marks":2,"question":"During what Unified Process phase is the architecture baseline established?","correct":1,"rationale":"Elaboration — milestone = LCA (Life-Cycle Architecture).","choices":["Inception","Elaboration","Construction","Transition","All of them"]},{"id":"q17","type":"MCQ","topic":"EVMS","marks":2,"question":"In EVMS, cost variance is defined to be","correct":1,"rationale":"CV = BCWP − ACWP. Positive = under budget.","choices":["BCWP − BCWS","BCWP − ACWP","BAC − ACWP","ACWP − BCWS","BAC / CPI"]},{"id":"q18","type":"MCQ","topic":"Use Cases","marks":2,"question":"According to the text, the three class stereotypes used in analysis modelling are","correct":2,"rationale":"Boundary (UI), Control (workflow), Entity (domain data). \"BCE\".","choices":["Data / Logic / View","Model / View / Controller","Boundary / Control / Entity","Actor / Use Case / System","Presenter / Service / Repository"]},{"id":"q19","type":"MCQ","topic":"MBTI","marks":2,"question":"Which of the following is a judging function?","correct":3,"rationale":"Judging functions = Thinking + Feeling (they decide). Perceiving functions = Sensing + Intuition (they gather).","choices":["Sensing","Intuition","Perceiving","Thinking","Extraversion"]},{"id":"q20","type":"MCQ","topic":"Testing","marks":2,"question":"What type of test verifies the response time and processing time?","correct":2,"rationale":"Performance tests. Quiz 4 Q6.","choices":["Volume","Configuration","Performance","Load","Acceptance"]},{"id":"q21","type":"MCQ","topic":"Mapping","marks":1,"question":"For an entity defined using annotations, @Table is required.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. @Table is OPTIONAL. Default table name = class name. Quiz 4 Q19.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q22","type":"MCQ","topic":"Relationships","marks":1,"question":"@JoinTable can be used to map a one-to-one relationship.","correct":0,"rationale":"TRUE. @JoinTable works for any relationship type. Unusual for 1:1 but legal. Quiz 4 Q20.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q23","type":"MCQ","topic":"EntityManager","marks":1,"question":"Two calls to EntityManager.find() with the same primary key in the same persistence context will return two different Java object references.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. Same Java reference (PC has identity-cached).","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q24","type":"MCQ","topic":"Session Beans","marks":1,"question":"A stateless session bean defines @PrePassivate and @PostActivate callback methods.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. Only SFSBs passivate (they hold conversational state). SLSBs have no state to serialize.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q25","type":"MCQ","topic":"Transactions","marks":1,"question":"The default transaction attribute for a container-managed EJB business method is Required.","correct":0,"rationale":"TRUE. REQUIRED = use caller's TX or create new one.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q26","type":"MCQ","topic":"JPQL","marks":1,"question":"The getSingleResult() method on the Query interface returns null when no matching entity is found.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. Throws NoResultException. Use getResultList() + check isEmpty() for nullable expectations.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q27","type":"MCQ","topic":"RUP","marks":1,"question":"A benefit of the traditional waterfall software development lifecycle is that risks are generally eliminated in the early stages of development.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. Waterfall delays risk discovery until integration → problems surface late. Iterative reduces risk early.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q28","type":"MCQ","topic":"Callbacks","marks":1,"question":"Entity callback methods are permitted to invoke EntityManager operations on other entities.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. Entity callbacks must NOT call EM or access other entities — undefined behavior.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q29","type":"SHORT","topic":"Relationships","marks":3,"question":"Describe how to determine the owning side in a one-to-many bidirectional relationship.","correct":"The owning side is the MANY side — it uses @ManyToOne + @JoinColumn (holds the foreign key). The ONE side uses @OneToMany(mappedBy=\"ownerField\") and is the inverse side. The JPA provider only consults the owning side for persistence; the inverse is for Java object graph navigation.","rationale":"Key terms: MANY side owns, @ManyToOne, @JoinColumn, FK, inverse side uses mappedBy. Common mistake: putting @JoinColumn on the ONE side. mappedBy value = FIELD name on owning side, not class name."},{"id":"q30","type":"SHORT","topic":"Inheritance","marks":3,"question":"What are the three ways to map an inheritance hierarchy in JPA?","correct":"(1) SINGLE_TABLE (default) — one table for entire hierarchy with a discriminator column. (2) JOINED — one table per class with foreign-key join from subclass to superclass. (3) TABLE_PER_CLASS — separate complete table per concrete subclass; parent columns duplicated.","rationale":"Must name all three strategies. Note SINGLE_TABLE is the DEFAULT and requires a discriminator column (@DiscriminatorColumn). Strategy declared via @Inheritance(strategy=InheritanceType.X) on the root entity."},{"id":"q31","type":"SHORT","topic":"Use Cases","marks":3,"question":"What are the three class stereotypes used in analysis modeling?","correct":"Boundary (UI / external interface), Control (workflow orchestration for a use case), Entity (persistent domain objects / important state).","rationale":"Mnemonic: BCE. Boundary = edge/UI, Control = coordinator per UC, Entity = long-lived domain data. Watch for confusion with MVC — stereotypes are an analysis abstraction, not an implementation pattern."},{"id":"q32","type":"SHORT","topic":"RUP","marks":3,"question":"Name the four phases of the Unified Process and their milestones.","correct":"Inception → LCO (Life-Cycle Objectives); Elaboration → LCA (Life-Cycle Architecture); Construction → IOC (Initial Operating Capability); Transition → PR (Product Release).","rationale":"Must pair each phase with its correct milestone. Order matters. Inception = vision/business case; Elaboration = architecture baseline; Construction = build remaining features; Transition = beta → GA."},{"id":"q33","type":"SHORT","topic":"JPQL","marks":3,"question":"Given Customer—(n:n)—Reservation—(n:1)—Cruise, write a JPQL query that returns all Cruises for which a given :cust Customer has a Reservation.","correct":"SELECT DISTINCT c FROM Cruise c, Reservation r WHERE r.cruise = c AND :cust MEMBER OF r.customers &nbsp;—&nbsp; OR equivalently: SELECT DISTINCT c FROM Cruise c JOIN c.reservations r JOIN r.customers cu WHERE cu = :cust. DISTINCT avoids duplicates.","rationale":"DISTINCT is critical — without it, a cruise appears once per reservation. MEMBER OF works against a collection-valued association. Use named parameters (:cust), not positional. Either cartesian-WHERE or explicit JOIN form accepted."},{"id":"q34","type":"SHORT","topic":"EVMS","marks":3,"question":"Given BCWS=$10,000, BCWP=$8,000, ACWP=$12,000, compute CV and SV. Interpret each.","correct":"CV = BCWP − ACWP = 8,000 − 12,000 = −$4,000 (over budget). SV = BCWP − BCWS = 8,000 − 10,000 = −$2,000 (behind schedule). Negative values indicate problems in both cost and schedule.","rationale":"Formulas: CV = BCWP − ACWP, SV = BCWP − BCWS. Sign convention: negative = bad (over budget / behind). Remember BCWP (earned value) is always the first term. Interpret both numbers, not just compute."},{"id":"q35","type":"SHORT","topic":"Use Cases","marks":10,"question":"Discuss how use cases drive the development process in the Unified Process. Explain how use cases drive analysis and design, test, and iteration planning.","correct":"\u003cstrong\u003eModel Answer Outline (connect everything — Bruce: students fail big-picture):\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUse cases are the central artifact\u003c/strong\u003e of RUP — they link requirements all the way to test.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRequirements\u003c/strong\u003e: UCs capture actor-system interactions; they ARE the functional requirements.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAnalysis\u003c/strong\u003e: each UC decomposed into analysis classes (Boundary/Control/Entity); each UC has a realization in the analysis model (class + collaboration diagrams).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDesign\u003c/strong\u003e: analysis model refined into design classes; each UC has a design-level realization using sequence diagrams to show object interactions over time.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eImplementation\u003c/strong\u003e: design classes → code components. UCs guide integration (build in UC-sized increments).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTest\u003c/strong\u003e: every UC → test cases. Main flow + alternate flows → positive + negative tests. Acceptance tests map directly to UCs.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIteration planning\u003c/strong\u003e: UCs prioritized (risk + value + dependency). Each iteration delivers a set of UCs end-to-end (mini-waterfall). UC selection drives WHAT architecture work happens WHEN.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTraceability\u003c/strong\u003e: single thread runs from requirements → design → code → test — all anchored to a UC.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","rationale":"10-mark essay: hit all four drivers (analysis/design, test, iteration planning) with a sentence of explanation each, then add traceability as the unifying idea. Weak answers only describe WHAT a UC is; strong answers show HOW it flows through every workflow. Name the artifacts (analysis classes, sequence diagrams, test cases)."},{"id":"q36","type":"SHORT","topic":"Transactions","marks":10,"question":"Compare and contrast the six EJB transaction attributes. For each, describe what happens when the caller has an active transaction vs no transaction.","correct":"\u003cstrong\u003eModel answer outline:\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003ctable\u003e\u003cthead\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\u003cth\u003eAttribute\u003c/th\u003e\u003cth\u003eCaller HAS TX\u003c/th\u003e\u003cth\u003eCaller NO TX\u003c/th\u003e\u003cth\u003eTypical use\u003c/th\u003e\u003c/tr\u003e\u003c/thead\u003e\u003ctbody\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\u003ctd\u003eREQUIRED (default)\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eJoin caller's TX\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eContainer creates new TX\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eDefault — business method\u003c/td\u003e\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\u003ctd\u003eREQUIRES_NEW\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eSuspend caller; create new independent TX\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eCreate new TX\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eAudit log that must commit separately\u003c/td\u003e\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\u003ctd\u003eSUPPORTS\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eJoin caller's TX\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eRun without TX\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eRead-only method\u003c/td\u003e\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\u003ctd\u003eNOT_SUPPORTED\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eSuspend caller; run without TX\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eRun without TX\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eLegacy non-TX code\u003c/td\u003e\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\u003ctd\u003eMANDATORY\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eJoin caller's TX\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eThrows EJBTransactionRequiredException\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003ePrivate helper expecting a TX\u003c/td\u003e\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\u003ctd\u003eNEVER\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eThrows EJBException\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eRun without TX\u003c/td\u003e\u003ctd\u003eMethods that must not be TX-bound\u003c/td\u003e\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAlso mention: declared via \u003ccode class=\"inline\"\u003e@TransactionAttribute\u003c/code\u003e under CMT. System exceptions (RuntimeException) auto-rollback; application exceptions do NOT unless declared \u003ccode class=\"inline\"\u003e@ApplicationException(rollback=true)\u003c/code\u003e. Can call \u003ccode class=\"inline\"\u003ectx.setRollbackOnly()\u003c/code\u003e to force rollback programmatically.\u003c/p\u003e","rationale":"10-mark essay: table each of six attributes × two caller states (has TX / no TX). Don't forget NEVER and MANDATORY throw exceptions in the \"wrong\" state. Bonus points: mention CMT vs BMT, rollback semantics (system vs app exception), setRollbackOnly(). Partial credit if student misses one attribute but gets TX-propagation logic right."},{"id":"q37","type":"SHORT","topic":"Relationships","marks":10,"question":"Annotate the two classes below so they form a 1:N BIDIRECTIONAL relationship where each Department has many Employees, using FK column DEPT\\_ID in the Employee table. Department.id should be auto-generated. public class Department {     private Long id;     private String name;     private List\u003cEmployee\u003e employees;     // getters/setters... } public class Employee {     private Long id;     private String name;     private Department department;     // getters/setters... }","correct":"\u003cpre class=\"language-java\"\u003e@Entity\n@Table(name = \"DEPARTMENT\")\npublic class Department {\n    @Id\n    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.AUTO)\n    private Long id;\n\n    @Column(name = \"NAME\")\n    private String name;\n\n    @OneToMany(mappedBy = \"department\", cascade = CascadeType.ALL, orphanRemoval = true)\n    private List&lt;Employee&gt; employees = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();\n    // getters/setters...\n}\n\n@Entity\n@Table(name = \"EMPLOYEE\")\npublic class Employee {\n    @Id\n    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.AUTO)\n    private Long id;\n\n    @Column(name = \"NAME\")\n    private String name;\n\n    @ManyToOne\n    @JoinColumn(name = \"DEPT_ID\")\n    private Department department;\n    // getters/setters...\n}\u003c/pre\u003e","rationale":"**Bruce's grading checklist:** -   @Entity on BOTH classes (students forget the Entity itself) -   @Id on PK field -   @GeneratedValue on auto-gen id -   MANY side owns → Employee has @ManyToOne + @JoinColumn(name=\"DEPT\\_ID\") - ONE side is inverse → Department has @OneToMany(mappedBy=\"department\") -   mappedBy value is FIELD name on owning side (\"department\"), NOT class name -   Common mistake: putting @JoinColumn on the ONE side — it belongs on the owning MANY side"},{"id":"q38","type":"MCQ","topic":"EntityManager","marks":2,"question":"Which EntityManager method writes changes from a detached/unmanaged entity back to the database?","correct":2,"rationale":"merge() copies the state of a detached entity into a managed copy and schedules UPDATE. update()/delete() don't exist on EntityManager. refresh() goes the OTHER direction (DB → entity).","choices":["EntityManager.update()","EntityManager.refresh()","EntityManager.merge()","Cabin.update()","PersistenceContext.update()"]},{"id":"q39","type":"MCQ","topic":"EntityManager","marks":2,"question":"Which EntityManager method removes an entity from the database?","correct":0,"rationale":"remove() schedules DELETE at flush. executeUpdate() is a Query method, not EntityManager. clear() detaches everything in the PC without touching the DB. delete() doesn't exist.","choices":["EntityManager.remove()","EntityManager.executeUpdate()","EntityManager.clear()","PersistenceContext.delete()","EntityManager.delete()"]},{"id":"q40","type":"MCQ","topic":"EntityManager","marks":2,"question":"Which call requests the persistence context to push pending updates to the database?","correct":4,"rationale":"EntityManager.flush() synchronizes the PC with the DB (SQL runs, TX not yet committed). PersistenceContext is not a directly-called object in JPA; EntityManager owns the API. update()/saveUpdates() don't exist.","choices":["EntityManager.update()","PersistenceContext.flush()","PersistenceContext.saveUpdates()","PersistenceContext.update()","EntityManager.flush()"]},{"id":"q41","type":"MCQ","topic":"EntityManager","marks":2,"question":"If Cabin is an entity class, which statement creates a NEW instance ready to be persisted?","correct":4,"rationale":"Entities are plain Java objects — you instantiate them with `new`. entityManager.persist() is then called to make the instance managed. persist() does NOT return an instance (void). entityManager.new(...) is fake.","choices":["Cabin myCabin = entityManager.persist(Cabin.class);","Cabin myCabin = new Entity(Cabin.class);","Cabin myCabin = entityManager.new(Cabin.class);","Cabin myCabin = connection.new(Cabin.class);","Cabin myCabin = new Cabin();"]},{"id":"q42","type":"MCQ","topic":"Mapping","marks":2,"question":"Which annotation maps a java.util.Date property to a SQL date/time column?","correct":3,"rationale":"@Temporal(TemporalType.DATE|TIME|TIMESTAMP) is required on java.util.Date / Calendar because SQL doesn't know which date precision to pick. Not needed for java.time.LocalDate etc. in JPA 2.2+.","choices":["@Date","@DateType","@Type","@Temporal","@Mapping"]},{"id":"q43","type":"MCQ","topic":"Mapping","marks":2,"question":"Which is the correct syntax to map an entity to a table named FRED?","correct":4,"rationale":"@Table(name=\"FRED\") on the class — no semicolon (annotation, not a statement); uses `name=` attribute, not a positional String; lowercase keyword. @Table(value=...) doesn't exist.","choices":["@Table(value=\"FRED\")","@Table(name=\"FRED\");","@Table(\"FRED\")","@Table(\"FRED\");","@Table(name=\"FRED\")"]},{"id":"q44","type":"MCQ","topic":"Mapping","marks":2,"question":"The entity inheritance strategy is declared using which annotation?","correct":3,"rationale":"@Inheritance(strategy = InheritanceType.X) on the root entity. InheritanceType is the enum; the annotation itself is @Inheritance. @InheritanceType / @InheritanceStrategy / @Strategy are distractors.","choices":["@EntityInheritance","@InheritanceType","@Strategy","@Inheritance","@InheritanceStrategy"]},{"id":"q45","type":"MCQ","topic":"Mapping","marks":2,"question":"One or more fields that make up an entity's primary key are identified by which annotation?","correct":0,"rationale":"@Id on a single field, or @IdClass / @EmbeddedId for composite keys. @PK / @Identity / @PrimaryKey are not JPA. @Entity has no primaryKey attribute.","choices":["@Id","@PK","@PrimaryKey","@Entity(primaryKey = \"...\")","@Identity"]},{"id":"q46","type":"MCQ","topic":"Mapping","marks":2,"question":"To map a 1:1 relationship using primary-key join columns, which annotation is added alongside @OneToOne?","correct":4,"rationale":"@PrimaryKeyJoinColumn indicates the PK of each row IS the FK to the other table — no separate FK column. @JoinColumn uses a distinct FK column. @ForeignKey is a DDL hint, not a mapping strategy.","choices":["@JoinColumn","@ForeignKey","@OneToOne","@Id","@PrimaryKeyJoinColumn"]},{"id":"q47","type":"MCQ","topic":"Relationships","marks":2,"question":"Which return types are valid for the collection accessor on the \"many\" side of a @OneToMany?","correct":4,"rationale":"JPA supports Collection, List, Set, and Map as collection-valued association types. Pick the one whose semantics match (Set = no dups, Map = keyed lookup, List = ordered). Map requires @MapKey.","choices":["Collection only","List only","Set only","Map only","All of the above"]},{"id":"q48","type":"MCQ","topic":"Persistence","marks":2,"question":"Which data MUST be defined in persistence.xml?","correct":0,"rationale":"persistence-unit name is mandatory (`\u003cpersistence-unit name=\"X\"\u003e`). Transaction type defaults to JTA on EE. Data source, properties, description are optional or provider-supplied.","choices":["persistence-unit name","persistence-unit transaction type","persistence-unit data source","persistence-unit properties","persistence-unit description"]},{"id":"q49","type":"MCQ","topic":"Persistence","marks":2,"question":"What XML file is required by the Jakarta Persistence specification?","correct":3,"rationale":"persistence.xml is the deployment descriptor (in META-INF/). orm.xml is OPTIONAL (replaces annotations). entity.xml / entityManager.xml / ejb.xml are not JPA files.","choices":["ORM.xml","entityManager.xml","entity.xml","persistence.xml","ejb.xml"]},{"id":"q50","type":"MCQ","topic":"JPQL","marks":2,"question":"Given CustomerBean (1)↔(n) OrderBean and OrderBean (1)↔(n) LineitemsBean, which JPQL returns the SET of customers that have orders?\n","correct":4,"rationale":"SELECT DISTINCT c FROM Customer c, Order o WHERE c.custnum = o.custnum — JPQL selects entity aliases, not table columns, and DISTINCT is required to avoid dup rows (one per matching order). Option A selects unaliased \"Customer\" which is illegal in JPQL.","choices":["SELECT DISTINCT Customer FROM Order","SELECT o.custnum FROM Order o, Customer c WHERE c.custnum = o.custnum","SELECT c FROM Customer c, Order o WHERE c.custnum = o.custnum","SELECT Customer FROM Order","SELECT DISTINCT c FROM Customer c, Order o WHERE c.custnum = o.custnum"]},{"id":"q51","type":"MCQ","topic":"JPQL","marks":2,"question":"Which expression is equivalent to `p.discount NOT BETWEEN 10 AND 15`?","correct":2,"rationale":"BETWEEN x AND y is INCLUSIVE on both ends, so NOT BETWEEN 10 AND 15 = `\u003c10 OR \u003e15`. Off-by-one trap: options using `\u003e= 15` would exclude 15, but 15 is outside the range so it must be included in the NOT set.","choices":["p.discount \u003c 10 OR p.discount \u003e= 15","p.discount \u003c= 10 OR p.discount \u003e 15","p.discount \u003c 10 OR p.discount \u003e 15","p.discount \u003c= 10 OR p.discount \u003e= 15","p.discount \u003c 10 OR p.discount = 15"]},{"id":"q52","type":"MCQ","topic":"RUP","marks":2,"question":"Which is NOT a core aspect of the Unified Process?","correct":3,"rationale":"Three UP pillars: use-case driven, architecture-centric, iterative & incremental. \"Object-oriented\" is a paradigm UP happens to use, not a defining aspect.","choices":["Architecture-centric","Iterative","Use-case driven","Object-oriented","All of the above are main aspects"]},{"id":"q53","type":"MCQ","topic":"RUP Phases","marks":2,"question":"Compared to later iterations, early iterations in the Unified Process focus primarily on","correct":2,"rationale":"Early iterations (Inception/Elaboration) attack REQUIREMENTS and RISK — prove the architecture, retire the hardest unknowns first. Feature-adding is Construction; detailed planning is continuous.","choices":["Adding functionality for the external release","Building models representing the system in a particular state","Achieving increased knowledge of requirements and risks","Ensuring testability in later phases","Achieving a detailed plan for the rest of the project"]},{"id":"q54","type":"MCQ","topic":"RUP Phases","marks":2,"question":"During which phase are most use cases specified in detail AND the system architecture designed?","correct":1,"rationale":"Elaboration. Analysis workflow peaks here; architecture is baselined (LCA milestone). Inception = vision only; Construction = build; Transition = deploy.","choices":["Transition","Elaboration","Inception","Requirements","Construction"]},{"id":"q55","type":"MCQ","topic":"Architecture","marks":2,"question":"Which is NOT one of the \"4+1 View\" models of software architecture?","correct":3,"rationale":"4+1 = Logical, Process, Deployment, Implementation (+ Use Case as the unifying \"+1\"). There is no \"Test View\" in Kruchten's 4+1.","choices":["Logical View","Use Case View","Deployment View","Test View","Process View"]},{"id":"q56","type":"MCQ","topic":"Architecture","marks":2,"question":"The model that is MOST complete in the architecture baseline is the","correct":1,"rationale":"Design model — arch baseline (end of Elaboration) has an executable architectural prototype and the design model is the richest artifact at that point. Use-case and analysis models are still partial.","choices":["analysis model","design model","use case model","deployment model","procedure model"]},{"id":"q57","type":"MCQ","topic":"Design","marks":2,"question":"Design subsystems and design classes represent ______ of subsystems and classes in the implementation.","correct":0,"rationale":"Abstractions. Design is a higher-level view; implementation is the realization. \"Realizations\" goes the other direction (impl realizes design).","choices":["Abstractions","Actualizations","Realizations","Implementations","Reifications"]},{"id":"q58","type":"MCQ","topic":"Use Cases","marks":2,"question":"What is an \"actor\" in the UML?","correct":3,"rationale":"Someone or something OUTSIDE the system that interacts with it. Actors can be humans OR other systems. A role, not a specific person.","choices":["A sequence of actions or operations the system performs","A person who fills a user or administrative role","Someone who performs a workflow in building a system","Someone or something outside the system that interacts with it","A person or system who directs others to follow procedures"]},{"id":"q59","type":"MCQ","topic":"Use Cases","marks":2,"question":"Use-case realizations most frequently include","correct":1,"rationale":"Sequence diagrams show how objects collaborate over time to realize a use case. Collaboration diagrams are an alternative. Process/deployment diagrams sit at different abstraction levels.","choices":["Process diagrams","Sequence diagrams","Deployment diagrams","Event lists","Object diagrams"]},{"id":"q60","type":"MCQ","topic":"Use Cases","marks":2,"question":"What diagram type describes how analysis objects interact?","correct":2,"rationale":"Collaboration diagram (now called communication diagram in UML 2) shows object-to-object messages during a use-case realization in the ANALYSIS model. Class diagrams show structure, not interaction.","choices":["Class diagram","Object diagram","Collaboration diagram","Package diagrams","Visit or event diagrams"]},{"id":"q61","type":"MCQ","topic":"Use Cases","marks":2,"question":"Use cases are a major input into","correct":4,"rationale":"Use cases seed test cases, iteration plans, subsystems, and analysis classes. They are the central thread through the UP — \"use-case driven\" means EVERY workflow consumes them.","choices":["finding and specifying test cases","planning development iterations","finding and specifying subsystems","finding and specifying classes","all of the above"]},{"id":"q62","type":"MCQ","topic":"Testing","marks":2,"question":"Tests used for system acceptance are usually","correct":4,"rationale":"Black box tests — acceptance testing validates user-visible behavior against use cases without knowledge of internals. White/grey box = structural tests; unit tests run far earlier.","choices":["white box tests","unit tests","grey box tests","swirly, knobby sorts of tests","black box tests"]},{"id":"q63","type":"MCQ","topic":"Testing","marks":2,"question":"Using ______, test cases can be identified BEFORE design of the system begins.","correct":3,"rationale":"Use-cases. They exist at the requirements stage (Inception/early Elaboration) and directly spawn acceptance test cases. Test plans/procedures come later.","choices":["Test plans","Test procedures","Architecture descriptions","Use-cases","Deployment models"]},{"id":"q64","type":"MCQ","topic":"EVMS","marks":2,"question":"Which EVMS metric answers \"how much did the work-done cost at a given time?\"","correct":2,"rationale":"ACWP = Actual Cost of Work Performed (what we've actually spent on the completed work). BCWP = earned value; BCWS = planned value; BAC/EAC = totals.","choices":["BAC","EAC","ACWP","BCWP","BCWS"]},{"id":"q65","type":"MCQ","topic":"EVMS","marks":2,"question":"Which EVMS metric answers \"how much do we NOW expect the total job to cost?\"","correct":2,"rationale":"EAC = Estimate At Completion (revised total). BAC = original baseline total. ACWP = costs to date (not a forecast).","choices":["BAC","BCWS","EAC","ACWP","BCWP"]},{"id":"q66","type":"MCQ","topic":"MBTI","marks":2,"question":"Which MBTI preference is a \"perceiving function\" (gathers information)?","correct":1,"rationale":"Perceiving functions = Sensing + iNtuition (how you take in information). Judging functions = Thinking + Feeling (how you decide). Extraversion/Introversion are attitudes.","choices":["Thinking","Sensing","Feeling","Perceiving (the attitude)","Judging (the attitude)"]},{"id":"q67","type":"MCQ","topic":"MBTI","marks":2,"question":"People who prefer Intuition tend to","correct":3,"rationale":"Intuitives like big-picture/novel problems, patterns, future possibilities. Sensors prefer details, practical, standard approaches.","choices":["show details of work first","prefer standard ways to solve problems","make few errors in fact","like solving new complex problems","prefer things with a practical bent"]},{"id":"q68","type":"MCQ","topic":"Project Management","marks":2,"question":"Which of the following is the BEST example of a software project risk?","correct":2,"rationale":"A risk is a potential future problem with uncertain outcome. \"System MAY fail to meet performance specs\" is a classic risk statement. Real-time / AI / rehost are CONSTRAINTS (already known); civil unrest is an external threat, not a SOFTWARE risk.","choices":["The project is real-time","The system must be rehosted onto different hardware","The system may fail to meet its performance specifications","The project requires difficult AI programming","The project may be interrupted by civil unrest"]},{"id":"q69","type":"MCQ","topic":"RUP","marks":1,"question":"A benefit of the waterfall lifecycle is that risks are generally eliminated in the early stages.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. Waterfall hides risks — they surface only at integration/test. Iterative models reduce risk early by prototyping architecture and hitting hard problems first.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q70","type":"MCQ","topic":"Mapping","marks":1,"question":"@JoinColumn can be used to map a many-to-many relationship between entity beans.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. M:N needs a JOIN TABLE (two FK columns), so @JoinTable is used. @JoinColumn is a single FK column — fine for M:1 / 1:1, wrong for M:N.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q71","type":"MCQ","topic":"Architecture","marks":1,"question":"A collaboration diagram resembles a class diagram but shows instances and messages instead of classes and associations.","correct":0,"rationale":"TRUE. Collaboration/communication diagram focuses on the object-level interaction in context of a use case realization — nodes are instances, links are messages.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q72","type":"MCQ","topic":"Analysis","marks":1,"question":"The analysis model is usually less formal than the design model.","correct":0,"rationale":"TRUE. Analysis is exploratory/conceptual (BCE stereotypes, loose); design adds implementation-level rigor (interfaces, types, sequence detail).","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q73","type":"MCQ","topic":"RUP","marks":1,"question":"According to the UP, an architecture baseline is a set of models that do NOT involve executable code.","correct":1,"rationale":"FALSE. The architecture baseline (end of Elaboration) includes an EXECUTABLE architectural prototype — running code that validates the key architectural decisions, not just diagrams.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q74","type":"MCQ","topic":"Analysis","marks":1,"question":"It is usually necessary to consider nonfunctional requirements BEFORE the analysis stage.","correct":0,"rationale":"TRUE. NFRs (performance, security, scalability) shape architecture and must be captured during requirements — they constrain analysis/design decisions.","choices":["True","False"]},{"id":"q75","type":"SHORT","topic":"EVMS","marks":3,"question":"What does ACWP stand for, and what does it measure?","correct":"Actual Cost of Work Performed. It measures the actual money spent to date on the work that has actually been completed (as opposed to BCWS = planned cost of planned work, or BCWP = planned cost of work actually done).","rationale":"Full marks require the expansion AND the \"what it measures\" contrast with BCWP/BCWS. Common confusion: ACWP vs BCWP — remember ACWP = Actual cost, BCWP = Budgeted cost (both of work performed)."},{"id":"q76","type":"SHORT","topic":"EntityManager","marks":3,"question":"What are the two types of persistence context in JPA, and how do they differ?","correct":"(1) Transaction-scoped — created at TX start, closed at TX end (default in container-managed EMs); entities detach when TX ends. (2) Extended — outlives a single TX, spans multiple user interactions (used with Stateful Session Beans); entities stay managed across calls until the SFSB is removed.","rationale":"Name both types, give lifetime, give canonical use-case. Extended PC + SFSB is the classic conversational-state pattern."},{"id":"q77","type":"SHORT","topic":"Relationships","marks":3,"question":"Describe how to determine the owning side in a ONE-to-ONE bidirectional relationship.","correct":"There is no automatic \"many side rule\" in 1:1 — the developer designates one side as owning by placing @JoinColumn (or @PrimaryKeyJoinColumn) there. The OTHER side then uses @OneToOne(mappedBy=\"fieldName\") to point back. The owning side holds the FK; the inverse side is read-only from JPA's perspective.","rationale":"Key distinction from 1:N: in 1:1 the choice is arbitrary — pick whichever side makes more sense conceptually. Must mention mappedBy and @JoinColumn / @PrimaryKeyJoinColumn."},{"id":"q78","type":"SHORT","topic":"RUP","marks":3,"question":"Which Unified Process activity during requirements capture determines the order of use-case development across iterations?","correct":"\"Prioritize use cases\" (a.k.a. planning iteration content). Use cases are ranked by risk, architectural significance, and stakeholder value — the architect and project manager drive this activity so each iteration tackles the most critical UCs first.","rationale":"Accept wording like \"prioritize the use cases\" / \"use-case prioritization\". Must tie to risk + architectural significance for full marks."},{"id":"q79","type":"SHORT","topic":"RUP","marks":3,"question":"Define \"artifact\" as used in the Unified Process.","correct":"An artifact is a general term for any information item created, produced, changed, or used by workers while developing a system. Examples: use-case model, analysis model, design model, source code, test plans, iteration plans — anything worth tracking and versioning.","rationale":"Must convey generality (ANY info item) AND give 1-2 concrete examples. \"Just code/diagrams\" is too narrow."},{"id":"q80","type":"SHORT","topic":"Relationships","marks":10,"question":"Annotate the Cruise and Reservation classes below to form a 1:N BIDIRECTIONAL relationship (one Cruise, many Reservations) using a foreign key column named CRUISE_NAME on the Reservation table. id fields are auto-generated. public class Cruise { private int id; private String name; private Ship ship; private Collection&lt;Reservation&gt; reservations = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(); } public class Reservation { private int id; private Date date; private double amountPaid; private Cruise cruise; }","correct":"\u003cpre class=\"language-java\"\u003e@Entity\npublic class Cruise implements java.io.Serializable {\n    @Id\n    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.AUTO)\n    private int id;\n\n    private String name;\n\n    @OneToOne\n    private Ship ship;\n\n    @OneToMany(mappedBy = \"cruise\")\n    private Collection&lt;Reservation&gt; reservations = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();\n    // ...\n}\n\n@Entity\npublic class Reservation implements java.io.Serializable {\n    @Id\n    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.AUTO)\n    private int id;\n\n    @Temporal(TemporalType.DATE)\n    private Date date;\n\n    private double amountPaid;\n\n    @ManyToOne\n    @JoinColumn(name = \"CRUISE_NAME\")\n    private Cruise cruise;\n    // ...\n}\u003c/pre\u003e","rationale":"Grading checklist: @Entity on BOTH; @Id + @GeneratedValue on int ids; @Temporal on java.util.Date (often missed); Reservation (many side) OWNS with @ManyToOne + @JoinColumn(name=\"CRUISE_NAME\"); Cruise has @OneToMany(mappedBy=\"cruise\") — mappedBy value matches the FIELD name on the owning side, NOT class name. Ship reference should get @OneToOne / @ManyToOne. Common errors: @JoinColumn on the one side; missing mappedBy; wrong mappedBy string."},{"id":"q81","type":"SHORT","topic":"Architecture","marks":10,"question":"Describe, in point form, what an \"architecture\" is according to the Unified Process, and how it is described (i.e. what artifacts are produced).","correct":"\u003cstrong\u003eModel answer outline:\u003c/strong\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDefinition\u003c/strong\u003e: architecture = the organization of the software system; key structural elements and their interfaces; collaborations among them; composition into progressively larger subsystems; architectural style guiding the organization.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eArchitecture is captured through the \"4+1\" view model:\u003c/strong\u003e\n\n  \u003cul\u003e\n\n    \u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003eUse-Case View\u003c/em\u003e — the \"+1\"; architecturally significant UCs that drive everything else.\u003c/li\u003e\n\n    \u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003eLogical View\u003c/em\u003e — design model (subsystems, classes, key collaborations).\u003c/li\u003e\n\n    \u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003eProcess View\u003c/em\u003e — concurrency, processes/threads, synchronization.\u003c/li\u003e\n\n    \u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003eImplementation View\u003c/em\u003e — components, packaging, source code organization.\u003c/li\u003e\n\n    \u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003eDeployment View\u003c/em\u003e — physical nodes, hardware, distribution.\u003c/li\u003e\n\n  \u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBaselined at end of Elaboration (LCA milestone)\u003c/strong\u003e with an executable architectural prototype demonstrating the significant decisions.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eKey artifact\u003c/strong\u003e: Software Architecture Document (SAD) containing all five views plus architecturally significant requirements + rationale.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","rationale":"10-mark essay: must name all five views (4+1) with a short description of each; connect to LCA milestone; mention executable prototype; name the SAD artifact. Partial credit for listing views without descriptions."}]},"lessons":[{"n":1,"id":"4911-lesson-what-is-java-ee-ejb-the-foundation","title":"What is Java EE / EJB? (the foundation)","hook":"Before any annotation — why does EJB even exist?","tags":["ejb"],"module":"EJB — session beans","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Forget EJB for a moment. You write a Java program with \u003ccode\u003emain()\u003c/code\u003e. You run it. Simple.","text":"Forget EJB for a moment. You write a Java program with `main()`. You run it. Simple."},{"kind":"p","html":"Now imagine you&#39;re building a \u003cstrong\u003ebanking website\u003c/strong\u003e. Thousands of users. Concurrent transactions. Security. Database connections. User sessions. Crashes. Backups. Your laptop&#39;s \u003ccode\u003emain()\u003c/code\u003e won&#39;t cut it.","text":"Now imagine you're building a **banking website**. Thousands of users. Concurrent transactions. Security. Database connections. User sessions. Crashes. Backups. Your laptop's `main()` won't cut it."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"analogy","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAnalogy:\u003c/strong\u003e You want to open a restaurant. You could build your own building, install plumbing, hire security, handle taxes — OR you rent a spot in a mall that already has those. The mall = the app server.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Analogy:** You want to open a restaurant. You could build your own building, install plumbing, hire security, handle taxes — OR you rent a spot in a mall that already has those. The mall = the app server."},{"kind":"h3","html":"The application server","text":"The application server"},{"kind":"p","html":"An \u003cstrong\u003eapplication server\u003c/strong\u003e is a piece of software that runs your business code and handles the boring infrastructure for you: threads, transactions, database connections, security, remote invocation, crash recovery, lifecycle.","text":"An **application server** is a piece of software that runs your business code and handles the boring infrastructure for you: threads, transactions, database connections, security, remote invocation, crash recovery, lifecycle."},{"kind":"p","html":"You write the business logic. The server wraps it.","text":"You write the business logic. The server wraps it."},{"kind":"h3","html":"EJB = the contract","text":"EJB = the contract"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eEnterprise JavaBeans (EJB)\u003c/strong\u003e is the contract between your code and the server. You write a class. You put annotations on it (\u003ccode\u003e@Stateless\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e@Entity\u003c/code\u003e). The server reads those and wires everything up.","text":"**Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB)** is the contract between your code and the server. You write a class. You put annotations on it (`@Stateless`, `@Entity`). The server reads those and wires everything up."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThe class you write = a \u003cstrong\u003ebean\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThe server = the \u003cstrong\u003econtainer\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   The class you write = a **bean**\n-   The server = the **container**"},{"kind":"diagram","title":"EJB ecosystem — big picture","svg":"\u003csvg viewBox=\"0 0 680 260\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMidYMid meet\"\u003e\u003cdefs\u003e\u003cmarker id=\"arrEJB\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"9\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M0 0 L10 5 L0 10 Z\" fill=\"#a3a3a3\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003c/marker\u003e\u003c/defs\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"100\" width=\"100\" height=\"60\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"70\" y=\"130\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eClient\u003c/text\u003e \u003ctext x=\"70\" y=\"146\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eweb / CLI / another EJB\u003c/text\u003e \u003crect x=\"170\" y=\"20\" width=\"490\" height=\"220\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"8\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"415\" y=\"40\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003eEJB Container (application server)\u003c/text\u003e \u003crect x=\"190\" y=\"60\" width=\"220\" height=\"70\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"300\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eSession Beans\u003c/text\u003e \u003ctext x=\"300\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e@Stateless · @Stateful · @Singleton\u003c/text\u003e \u003ctext x=\"300\" y=\"116\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e(business logic)\u003c/text\u003e \u003crect x=\"440\" y=\"60\" width=\"200\" height=\"70\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"540\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eMessage-Driven Beans\u003c/text\u003e \u003ctext x=\"540\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e@MessageDriven\u003c/text\u003e \u003ctext x=\"540\" y=\"116\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e(async JMS consumers)\u003c/text\u003e \u003crect x=\"190\" y=\"150\" width=\"450\" height=\"70\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"415\" y=\"172\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eJPA Entities + EntityManager\u003c/text\u003e \u003ctext x=\"415\" y=\"190\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e@Entity · @Id · @OneToMany · @PersistenceContext\u003c/text\u003e \u003ctext x=\"415\" y=\"206\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e(persistent data layer)\u003c/text\u003e \u003cpath d=\"M120 130 L190 90\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrEJB)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M300 130 L400 150\" class=\"arrow-line\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M540 130 L440 150\" class=\"arrow-line\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M680 180 L680 220\" class=\"arrow-line\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"668\" y=\"238\" text-anchor=\"end\" class=\"sub\"\u003e→ Database\u003c/text\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e","legend":"\u003cstrong\u003eContainer provides:\u003c/strong\u003e threading · transactions · security · pooling · JNDI · lifecycle callbacks · resource injection.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eYou write:\u003c/strong\u003e annotated classes. The container wires everything together. Three bean types solve three different problems: business logic, async messages, persistent data."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Three flavors of bean (three different problems)","text":"Three flavors of bean (three different problems)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSession beans\u003c/strong\u003e — business logic (&quot;place an order&quot;, &quot;charge credit card&quot;)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMessage-Driven beans\u003c/strong\u003e — async message consumers (&quot;a message arrived, process it&quot;)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEntities (JPA)\u003c/strong\u003e — persistent data (&quot;this is a row in the Customer table&quot;)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **Session beans** — business logic (\"place an order\", \"charge credit card\")\n-   **Message-Driven beans** — async message consumers (\"a message arrived, process it\")\n-   **Entities (JPA)** — persistent data (\"this is a row in the Customer table\")"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e EJB is Java&#39;s way of saying &quot;I&#39;ll focus on business logic, you (container) handle the hard stuff.&quot; Everything else in this course is details on top of this one idea.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Takeaway:** EJB is Java's way of saying \"I'll focus on business logic, you (container) handle the hard stuff.\" Everything else in this course is details on top of this one idea."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"What job does the EJB container do that makes your life easier?","a":"It handles threading, transactions, security, DB connection pooling, lifecycle, crash recovery, remote calls — so you can focus only on business logic."}]},{"n":2,"id":"4911-lesson-three-session-beans-when-to-pick-which","title":"Three session beans — when to pick which","hook":"Why are there 3 kinds? Because there are 3 different state patterns.","tags":["session-beans"],"module":"EJB — session beans","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Imagine running a bank website. Every user click triggers an action. How do you structure the code?","text":"Imagine running a bank website. Every user click triggers an action. How do you structure the code?"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Pattern A — Stateless (pool of workers)","text":"Pattern A — Stateless (pool of workers)"},{"kind":"p","html":"User clicks &quot;get balance.&quot; Code runs → query DB → return number → done. The next click could be handled by a completely fresh worker. Nothing remembered between calls.","text":"User clicks \"get balance.\" Code runs → query DB → return number → done. The next click could be handled by a completely fresh worker. Nothing remembered between calls."},{"kind":"p","html":"This is \u003ccode\u003e@Stateless\u003c/code\u003e. The container keeps a \u003cstrong\u003epool\u003c/strong\u003e of instances. Any worker can handle any request. Fast. Scales horizontally.","text":"This is `@Stateless`. The container keeps a **pool** of instances. Any worker can handle any request. Fast. Scales horizontally."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"analogy","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAnalogy:\u003c/strong\u003e Fast food counter. Any cashier can take your order. Nobody remembers you.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Analogy:** Fast food counter. Any cashier can take your order. Nobody remembers you."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eUse for:\u003c/strong\u003e Most business methods. &quot;Validate this form.&quot; &quot;Send an email.&quot; &quot;Process checkout.&quot;","text":"**Use for:** Most business methods. \"Validate this form.\" \"Send an email.\" \"Process checkout.\""},{"kind":"h3","html":"Pattern B — Stateful (per-client memory)","text":"Pattern B — Stateful (per-client memory)"},{"kind":"p","html":"User starts shopping. Adds item 1. Adds item 2. Then checks out. The bean has to \u003cstrong\u003eremember\u003c/strong\u003e the cart across multiple clicks from THAT user.","text":"User starts shopping. Adds item 1. Adds item 2. Then checks out. The bean has to **remember** the cart across multiple clicks from THAT user."},{"kind":"p","html":"This is \u003ccode\u003e@Stateful\u003c/code\u003e. ONE instance per client. Holds conversational state. When the client idles, the container \u003cstrong\u003epassivates\u003c/strong\u003e it (serializes to disk) to save memory. When they return, it&#39;s \u003cstrong\u003eactivated\u003c/strong\u003e (deserialized).","text":"This is `@Stateful`. ONE instance per client. Holds conversational state. When the client idles, the container **passivates** it (serializes to disk) to save memory. When they return, it's **activated** (deserialized)."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"analogy","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAnalogy:\u003c/strong\u003e Personal banker. Dedicated to you. Remembers your ongoing conversation. Goes on a break (passivated) when you don&#39;t show up.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Analogy:** Personal banker. Dedicated to you. Remembers your ongoing conversation. Goes on a break (passivated) when you don't show up."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eUse for:\u003c/strong\u003e Shopping carts, multi-step wizards, booking workflows.","text":"**Use for:** Shopping carts, multi-step wizards, booking workflows."},{"kind":"p","html":"Lifecycle callbacks: \u003ccode\u003e@PostConstruct\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e@PrePassivate\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e@PostActivate\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e@PreDestroy\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003e@Remove\u003c/code\u003e (marks the method that ends the conversation).","text":"Lifecycle callbacks: `@PostConstruct`, `@PrePassivate`, `@PostActivate`, `@PreDestroy`, `@Remove` (marks the method that ends the conversation)."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Pattern C — Singleton (one shared instance)","text":"Pattern C — Singleton (one shared instance)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Some state is GLOBAL to the app. Configuration. A cache. A counter. One instance. All clients share it.","text":"Some state is GLOBAL to the app. Configuration. A cache. A counter. One instance. All clients share it."},{"kind":"p","html":"This is \u003ccode\u003e@Singleton\u003c/code\u003e. But &quot;shared&quot; = concurrency problem. What if two threads hit it simultaneously?","text":"This is `@Singleton`. But \"shared\" = concurrency problem. What if two threads hit it simultaneously?"},{"kind":"p","html":"You annotate methods with \u003ccode\u003e@Lock(READ)\u003c/code\u003e (many readers OK) or \u003ccode\u003e@Lock(WRITE)\u003c/code\u003e (exclusive — blocks everyone). Plus \u003ccode\u003e@Startup\u003c/code\u003e (eager init) and \u003ccode\u003e@DependsOn(&quot;OtherBean&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e (init order).","text":"You annotate methods with `@Lock(READ)` (many readers OK) or `@Lock(WRITE)` (exclusive — blocks everyone). Plus `@Startup` (eager init) and `@DependsOn(\"OtherBean\")` (init order)."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"analogy","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAnalogy:\u003c/strong\u003e Shared bulletin board in an office lobby. Everyone reads it. Only one person can edit at a time.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Analogy:** Shared bulletin board in an office lobby. Everyone reads it. Only one person can edit at a time."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eUse for:\u003c/strong\u003e App-wide cache, configuration, global counters, scheduling.","text":"**Use for:** App-wide cache, configuration, global counters, scheduling."},{"kind":"diagram","title":"The three session beans — side by side","svg":"\u003csvg viewBox=\"0 0 760 360\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMidYMid meet\"\u003e\u003cdefs\u003e\u003cmarker id=\"arrSB\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"9\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M0 0 L10 5 L0 10 Z\" fill=\"#a3a3a3\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003c/marker\u003e\u003c/defs\u003e\u003ctext x=\"130\" y=\"22\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003e@Stateless (SLSB)\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"380\" y=\"22\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003e@Stateful (SFSB)\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"630\" y=\"22\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003e@Singleton\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"40\" y=\"40\" width=\"180\" height=\"40\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"130\" y=\"65\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eDoesNotExist\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M130 80 L130 110\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrSB)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"146\" y=\"98\" class=\"sub\"\u003e@PostConstruct\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"40\" y=\"115\" width=\"180\" height=\"40\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"130\" y=\"140\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eMethodReady\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"130\" y=\"180\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003ePool of workers\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"130\" y=\"196\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eNo client state\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"130\" y=\"212\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eAny worker handles any call\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"130\" y=\"244\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eConcurrency: container-serialized\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"130\" y=\"262\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e@PostConstruct · @PreDestroy\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"130\" y=\"290\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eUse: business methods\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"290\" y=\"40\" width=\"180\" height=\"40\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"380\" y=\"65\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eDoesNotExist\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M380 80 L380 110\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrSB)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"396\" y=\"98\" class=\"sub\"\u003e@PostConstruct\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"290\" y=\"115\" width=\"180\" height=\"40\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"380\" y=\"140\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eMethodReady\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M380 155 L380 175\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrSB)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"395\" y=\"170\" class=\"sub\"\u003e@PrePassivate (idle)\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M370 175 L370 155\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrSB)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"237\" y=\"170\" class=\"sub\"\u003e@PostActivate (return)\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"290\" y=\"180\" width=\"180\" height=\"40\" class=\"box-warn\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"380\" y=\"205\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003ePassive (on disk)\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"380\" y=\"244\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eOne instance per client\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"380\" y=\"262\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eConversational state\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"380\" y=\"290\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eUse: carts, wizards\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"540\" y=\"40\" width=\"180\" height=\"40\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"630\" y=\"65\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eDoesNotExist\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M630 80 L630 110\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrSB)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"646\" y=\"98\" class=\"sub\"\u003e@Startup (eager)\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"540\" y=\"115\" width=\"180\" height=\"40\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"630\" y=\"140\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eShared Instance\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"630\" y=\"180\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eONE instance app-wide\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"630\" y=\"196\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eShared mutable state\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"630\" y=\"212\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e@DependsOn for init order\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"630\" y=\"244\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e@Lock(READ) parallel\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"630\" y=\"262\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e@Lock(WRITE) exclusive\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"630\" y=\"290\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eUse: cache, config, counters\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"40\" y=\"320\" width=\"680\" height=\"28\" class=\"box\" rx=\"4\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"380\" y=\"338\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eAccent border = active/running state · Warn border = serialized to disk (passivated)\u003c/text\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e","legend":null},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e State pattern picks the bean type. No state → Stateless. Per-client state → Stateful. Global state → Singleton.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Takeaway:** State pattern picks the bean type. No state → Stateless. Per-client state → Stateful. Global state → Singleton."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You're building a multi-step hotel booking wizard. Which bean type?","a":"Stateful — you need to remember the user's selections (dates, room, guests) across multiple HTTP requests."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A singleton method that only READS data — which lock type?","a":"@Lock(READ). Allows multiple concurrent readers. Use @Lock(WRITE) only when mutating shared state."}]},{"n":3,"id":"4911-lesson-jpa-from-zero-mapping-objects-to-tables","title":"JPA from zero — mapping objects to tables","hook":"The \"O\" in ORM: how Java objects become database rows.","tags":["jpa"],"module":"JPA — entities & persistence","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"You have a \u003ccode\u003eCustomer\u003c/code\u003e class in Java. The data lives in a \u003ccode\u003eCUSTOMER\u003c/code\u003e table in PostgreSQL. You want to save/load/delete.","text":"You have a `Customer` class in Java. The data lives in a `CUSTOMER` table in PostgreSQL. You want to save/load/delete."},{"kind":"h3","html":"The hard way (without JPA)","text":"The hard way (without JPA)"},{"kind":"p","html":"You&#39;d write:","text":"You'd write:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"PreparedStatement ps = conn.prepareStatement(\n    \"INSERT INTO CUSTOMER (id, name) VALUES (?, ?)\");\nps.setLong(1, c.getId());\nps.setString(2, c.getName());\nps.executeUpdate();"},{"kind":"p","html":"Boring. Error-prone. Every table needs its own boilerplate. Doesn&#39;t scale.","text":"Boring. Error-prone. Every table needs its own boilerplate. Doesn't scale."},{"kind":"h3","html":"The JPA way","text":"The JPA way"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eJPA (Java Persistence API)\u003c/strong\u003e is an \u003cstrong\u003eObject-Relational Mapper (ORM)\u003c/strong\u003e. It converts Java objects to SQL automatically.","text":"**JPA (Java Persistence API)** is an **Object-Relational Mapper (ORM)**. It converts Java objects to SQL automatically."},{"kind":"p","html":"You annotate the class:","text":"You annotate the class:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"@Entity\n@Table(name = \"CUSTOMER\")\npublic class Customer {\n    @Id\n    @GeneratedValue\n    private Long id;\n\n    @Column(name = \"NAME\")\n    private String name;\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Translation:","text":"Translation:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@Entity\u003c/code\u003e — &quot;this class maps to a DB table&quot;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@Table(name=&quot;CUSTOMER&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e — &quot;specifically the CUSTOMER table&quot; (optional; default = class name)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@Id\u003c/code\u003e — &quot;this field is the primary key&quot;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@GeneratedValue\u003c/code\u003e — &quot;DB auto-generates the id&quot;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@Column(name=&quot;NAME&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e — &quot;map to the NAME column&quot; (optional; default = field name)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   `@Entity` — \"this class maps to a DB table\"\n-   `@Table(name=\"CUSTOMER\")` — \"specifically the CUSTOMER table\" (optional; default = class name)\n-   `@Id` — \"this field is the primary key\"\n-   `@GeneratedValue` — \"DB auto-generates the id\"\n-   `@Column(name=\"NAME\")` — \"map to the NAME column\" (optional; default = field name)"},{"kind":"diagram","title":"JPA persistence stack — how a Java call becomes a SQL statement","svg":"\u003csvg viewBox=\"0 0 640 460\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMidYMid meet\"\u003e\u003cdefs\u003e\u003cmarker id=\"arrJPA\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"9\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M0 0 L10 5 L0 10 Z\" fill=\"#a3a3a3\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003c/marker\u003e\u003c/defs\u003e\u003crect x=\"60\" y=\"20\" width=\"520\" height=\"50\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"42\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eYour Business Code\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"60\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003ecustomer.setName(&quot;Alice&quot;)\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M320 70 L320 90\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrJPA)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003crect x=\"60\" y=\"90\" width=\"520\" height=\"50\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"112\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eEntityManager\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"130\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e@PersistenceContext injects this · API surface\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M320 140 L320 160\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrJPA)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003crect x=\"60\" y=\"160\" width=\"520\" height=\"50\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"182\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003ePersistence Context\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"200\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003etracks managed entities · dirty checking · 1st-level cache\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M320 210 L320 230\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrJPA)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003crect x=\"60\" y=\"230\" width=\"520\" height=\"50\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"252\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003ePersistence Unit\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"270\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003epersistence.xml · defines provider + datasource\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M320 280 L320 300\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrJPA)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003crect x=\"60\" y=\"300\" width=\"520\" height=\"50\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"322\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eJPA Provider\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"340\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eHibernate / EclipseLink — generates SQL\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M320 350 L320 370\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrJPA)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003crect x=\"60\" y=\"370\" width=\"520\" height=\"40\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"395\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eJDBC Connection Pool · container-managed\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M320 410 L320 425\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrJPA)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003crect x=\"60\" y=\"425\" width=\"520\" height=\"30\" class=\"box-ok\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"445\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eDatabase — PostgreSQL / MySQL / Oracle\u003c/text\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e","legend":"\u003cstrong\u003eBig picture:\u003c/strong\u003e you touch Java objects. The EntityManager + Persistence Context track changes. At TX commit, the provider emits SQL through JDBC. You never write INSERT/UPDATE directly (unless you want to).\u003cbr\u003eLazy loading fails on detached entities because the Persistence Context (middle layer) is no longer watching."},{"kind":"h3","html":"The EntityManager — the helper","text":"The EntityManager — the helper"},{"kind":"p","html":"Annotations describe the mapping. The \u003cstrong\u003eEntityManager\u003c/strong\u003e does the actual work.","text":"Annotations describe the mapping. The **EntityManager** does the actual work."},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"@PersistenceContext\nEntityManager em;\n\nCustomer c = new Customer();\nc.setName(\"Alice\");\nem.persist(c);                          // INSERT\n\nCustomer found = em.find(Customer.class, 1L);  // SELECT\nfound.setName(\"Bob\");                    // Java setter...\n// UPDATE runs automatically on TX commit\n\nem.remove(found);                        // DELETE"},{"kind":"h3","html":"The magic: dirty checking","text":"The magic: dirty checking"},{"kind":"p","html":"The EntityManager tracks every object you load. If you modify a tracked object, when the transaction commits, JPA diffs the old vs new state and generates the right UPDATE statement \u003cstrong\u003eautomatically\u003c/strong\u003e.","text":"The EntityManager tracks every object you load. If you modify a tracked object, when the transaction commits, JPA diffs the old vs new state and generates the right UPDATE statement **automatically**."},{"kind":"p","html":"You never write SQL again (mostly).","text":"You never write SQL again (mostly)."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e JPA = annotations describe mapping; EntityManager is the API that does SQL for you. @Entity marks a class, @Id marks the key, @Column maps a field. Everything else is details.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Takeaway:** JPA = annotations describe mapping; EntityManager is the API that does SQL for you. @Entity marks a class, @Id marks the key, @Column maps a field. Everything else is details."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"If you forget @Table on an entity, what table name does JPA use?","a":"The class name. So a Customer class maps to a \"Customer\" table by default. @Table(name=\"X\") overrides this."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You load a Customer, change its name, then call... what to save?","a":"Nothing! On transaction commit, JPA's dirty checking detects the change and generates UPDATE automatically. That's the whole point of managed entities."}]},{"n":4,"id":"4911-lesson-entity-lifecycle-4-states-4-methods","title":"Entity lifecycle — 4 states, 4 methods","hook":"Every entity is in one of 4 states. Each EntityManager method moves between them.","tags":["jpa"],"module":"JPA — entities & persistence","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"At any moment, every entity object is in exactly one of four states. Understanding these states → understanding JPA.","text":"At any moment, every entity object is in exactly one of four states. Understanding these states → understanding JPA."},{"kind":"h3","html":"The four states","text":"The four states"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eState\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMeaning\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eIn DB?\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eTracked by EM?\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eNew\u003c/strong\u003e (Transient)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eJust \u003ccode\u003enew Customer()\u003c/code\u003e; never persisted\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eManaged\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eTracked in persistence context\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes (or will be)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes — changes auto-saved\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDetached\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eWas managed, now outside PC (e.g. after TX ends)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo — changes NOT saved\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRemoved\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eScheduled for DELETE\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes (for now)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eYes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h3","html":"The state machine","text":"The state machine"},{"kind":"diagram","title":"Entity lifecycle — 4 states + EntityManager transitions","svg":"\u003csvg viewBox=\"0 0 760 320\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMidYMid meet\"\u003e\u003cdefs\u003e\u003cmarker id=\"arrEL\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"9\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M0 0 L10 5 L0 10 Z\" fill=\"#a3a3a3\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003c/marker\u003e\u003c/defs\u003e\u003ccircle cx=\"40\" cy=\"160\" r=\"8\" class=\"box-accent\"\u003e\u003c/circle\u003e\u003crect x=\"100\" y=\"135\" width=\"120\" height=\"50\" class=\"box\" rx=\"6\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"158\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eNew\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"174\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e(Transient)\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"320\" y=\"60\" width=\"160\" height=\"60\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"6\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"400\" y=\"84\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003eManaged\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"400\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003etracked by PC\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"400\" y=\"114\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003echanges auto-saved\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"320\" y=\"200\" width=\"160\" height=\"60\" class=\"box-warn\" rx=\"6\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"400\" y=\"224\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eDetached\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"400\" y=\"240\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eoutside PC\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"400\" y=\"254\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eremove() throws — merge() first\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"580\" y=\"135\" width=\"140\" height=\"50\" class=\"box-bad\" rx=\"6\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"650\" y=\"158\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eRemoved\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"650\" y=\"174\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003escheduled DELETE\u003c/text\u003e\u003ccircle cx=\"740\" cy=\"160\" r=\"8\" class=\"box-accent\"\u003e\u003c/circle\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M48 160 L100 160\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrEL)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"74\" y=\"152\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003enew\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M48 160 Q200 40 320 90\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrEL)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"180\" y=\"60\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003efind() / query\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M220 150 Q270 110 320 95\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrEL)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"270\" y=\"120\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003epersist()\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M395 120 L395 200\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrEL)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"295\" y=\"165\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eTX commit / clear() / detach()\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M405 200 L405 120\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrEL)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"500\" y=\"165\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003emerge() (returns copy)\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M480 90 L580 155\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrEL)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"540\" y=\"115\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eremove()\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M720 160 L732 160\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrEL)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"700\" y=\"200\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eTX commit (DELETE)\u003c/text\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e","legend":"\u003cstrong\u003eTracked by PC:\u003c/strong\u003e Managed + Removed. \u003cstrong\u003eNot tracked:\u003c/strong\u003e New + Detached (changes lost unless re-attached via merge).\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTrap:\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eremove()\u003c/code\u003e throws on Detached — must \u003ccode\u003emerge()\u003c/code\u003e first."},{"kind":"h3","html":"The 5 EntityManager methods you MUST know","text":"The 5 EntityManager methods you MUST know"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003epersist(e)\u003c/code\u003e — New → Managed (schedules INSERT)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003emerge(e)\u003c/code\u003e — Detached → Managed COPY (returns new reference, original still detached)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eremove(e)\u003c/code\u003e — Managed → Removed (schedules DELETE). \u003cstrong\u003eThrows on detached!\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003efind(Class, pk)\u003c/code\u003e — SELECT; returns Managed or null\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eflush()\u003c/code\u003e — Push pending SQL to DB (TX stays open)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   `persist(e)` — New → Managed (schedules INSERT)\n-   `merge(e)` — Detached → Managed COPY (returns new reference, original still detached)\n-   `remove(e)` — Managed → Removed (schedules DELETE). **Throws on detached!**\n-   `find(Class, pk)` — SELECT; returns Managed or null\n-   `flush()` — Push pending SQL to DB (TX stays open)"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"analogy","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAnalogy:\u003c/strong\u003e Think of the persistence context as a teacher&#39;s mental list of students in class.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eNew\u003c/strong\u003e = a kid on the playground, not enrolled\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eManaged\u003c/strong\u003e = enrolled, on the teacher&#39;s roster, the teacher tracks them\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDetached\u003c/strong\u003e = graduated, off the roster, teacher ignores changes\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRemoved\u003c/strong\u003e = getting kicked out at end of day\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"**Analogy:** Think of the persistence context as a teacher's mental list of students in class.\n-   **New** = a kid on the playground, not enrolled\n-   **Managed** = enrolled, on the teacher's roster, the teacher tracks them\n-   **Detached** = graduated, off the roster, teacher ignores changes\n-   **Removed** = getting kicked out at end of day"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Why merge() exists","text":"Why merge() exists"},{"kind":"p","html":"You call an EJB, get a Customer, TX ends → entity is now detached. You modify it on the client, send it back, call a new EJB method. The new method&#39;s EM has no idea about this entity.","text":"You call an EJB, get a Customer, TX ends → entity is now detached. You modify it on the client, send it back, call a new EJB method. The new method's EM has no idea about this entity."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eem.merge(c)\u003c/code\u003e = &quot;reattach this detached entity&#39;s state.&quot; It finds the DB row, copies the new state in, and returns a NEW managed reference. The original stays detached.","text":"`em.merge(c)` = \"reattach this detached entity's state.\" It finds the DB row, copies the new state in, and returns a NEW managed reference. The original stays detached."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Why remove() fails on detached","text":"Why remove() fails on detached"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003eremove()\u003c/code\u003e requires the entity to be in the PC. Detached = not in PC = exception. To delete a detached entity: \u003ccode\u003eem.remove(em.merge(c))\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"`remove()` requires the entity to be in the PC. Detached = not in PC = exception. To delete a detached entity: `em.remove(em.merge(c))`."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e New → persist. Detached → merge. Managed → just modify, saved automatically at commit. Remove requires managed.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Takeaway:** New → persist. Detached → merge. Managed → just modify, saved automatically at commit. Remove requires managed."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A customer object was loaded in a previous transaction. It's now detached. You change its name and want to save. Which method?","a":"merge(). It reattaches the state into a managed copy. On commit, UPDATE runs. persist() would throw — persist is for NEW entities, not detached ones."}]},{"n":5,"id":"4911-lesson-relationships-owning-side-demystified-high-priority","title":"Relationships — owning side demystified (HIGH PRIORITY)","hook":"Why does the \"many\" side own the FK? Because of how databases work.","tags":["relationships"],"module":"JPA — entities & persistence","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Entities don&#39;t live alone. An \u003ccode\u003eEmployee\u003c/code\u003e belongs to a \u003ccode\u003eDepartment\u003c/code\u003e. A \u003ccode\u003eBook\u003c/code\u003e has \u003ccode\u003eAuthor\u003c/code\u003es. Relationships.","text":"Entities don't live alone. An `Employee` belongs to a `Department`. A `Book` has `Author`s. Relationships."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Start with the database","text":"Start with the database"},{"kind":"p","html":"In a relational DB, foreign keys go in ONE place. Look at this:","text":"In a relational DB, foreign keys go in ONE place. Look at this:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"text","code":"DEPARTMENT                    EMPLOYEE\n+----+--------+              +----+--------+----------+\n| id | name   |              | id | name   | dept_id  |  ← FK\n+----+--------+              +----+--------+----------+\n|  1 | Sales  |              | 10 | Alice  | 1        |\n|  2 | Eng    |              | 11 | Bob    | 1        |\n+----+--------+              | 12 | Carol  | 2        |\n                             +----+--------+----------+"},{"kind":"p","html":"The FK \u003ccode\u003edept_id\u003c/code\u003e is in the Employee row. \u003cstrong\u003eWhy?\u003c/strong\u003e Because an employee has exactly ONE department, but a department can have MANY employees. You can&#39;t store &quot;list of employee ids&quot; in the Department row (1:N doesn&#39;t fit in a single cell).","text":"The FK `dept_id` is in the Employee row. **Why?** Because an employee has exactly ONE department, but a department can have MANY employees. You can't store \"list of employee ids\" in the Department row (1:N doesn't fit in a single cell)."},{"kind":"p","html":"So: \u003cstrong\u003ein any 1:N, the FK lives on the MANY side.\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"So: **in any 1:N, the FK lives on the MANY side.**"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Owning side = the side with the FK","text":"Owning side = the side with the FK"},{"kind":"p","html":"JPA calls the side with the FK the \u003cstrong\u003eowning side\u003c/strong\u003e. The other side is the \u003cstrong\u003einverse side\u003c/strong\u003e.","text":"JPA calls the side with the FK the **owning side**. The other side is the **inverse side**."},{"kind":"p","html":"For 1:N bidirectional:","text":"For 1:N bidirectional:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"// MANY side — OWNING (holds FK)\n@Entity\npublic class Employee {\n    @Id private Long id;\n\n    @ManyToOne                              // relationship type\n    @JoinColumn(name = \"DEPT_ID\")            // FK column\n    private Department department;\n}\n\n// ONE side — INVERSE\n@Entity\npublic class Department {\n    @Id private Long id;\n\n    @OneToMany(mappedBy = \"department\")     // \"I'm the inverse.\n    private List\u003cEmployee\u003e employees;       //  Owner's field is 'department'\"\n}"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Why mappedBy?","text":"Why mappedBy?"},{"kind":"p","html":"JPA reads \u003cstrong\u003eonly the owning side\u003c/strong\u003e when deciding what SQL to run. If you forget \u003ccode\u003emappedBy\u003c/code\u003e on the inverse, JPA thinks there are TWO separate relationships and creates a second FK or join table. Disaster.","text":"JPA reads **only the owning side** when deciding what SQL to run. If you forget `mappedBy` on the inverse, JPA thinks there are TWO separate relationships and creates a second FK or join table. Disaster."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003emappedBy=&quot;department&quot;\u003c/code\u003e literally means: &quot;Hey JPA, I&#39;m the inverse. The OWNING side is the Employee class, and the relationship field on it is called \u003ccode\u003edepartment\u003c/code\u003e.&quot;","text":"`mappedBy=\"department\"` literally means: \"Hey JPA, I'm the inverse. The OWNING side is the Employee class, and the relationship field on it is called `department`.\""},{"kind":"h3","html":"The 7 flavors — visual reference","text":"The 7 flavors — visual reference"},{"kind":"diagram","title":"Seven relationship types — annotation + FK location","svg":"\u003csvg viewBox=\"0 0 760 720\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMidYMid meet\"\u003e\u003cdefs\u003e\u003cmarker id=\"arrREL\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"9\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M0 0 L10 5 L0 10 Z\" fill=\"#a3a3a3\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003c/marker\u003e\u003c/defs\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"20\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003e1. 1:1 unidirectional\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"30\" width=\"100\" height=\"40\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"70\" y=\"55\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eUser\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M120 50 L200 50\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrREL)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"44\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e1 ── 1\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"200\" y=\"30\" width=\"100\" height=\"40\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"250\" y=\"55\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eProfile\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"42\" class=\"sub\"\u003eUser: @OneToOne + @JoinColumn\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"58\" class=\"sub\"\u003eFK: User.profile_id\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"100\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003e2. 1:1 bidirectional\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"110\" width=\"100\" height=\"40\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"70\" y=\"135\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eUser\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M120 130 L200 130\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrREL)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M200 138 L120 138\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrREL)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003crect x=\"200\" y=\"110\" width=\"100\" height=\"40\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"250\" y=\"135\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eProfile\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"118\" class=\"sub\"\u003eUser: @OneToOne + @JoinColumn\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"134\" class=\"sub\"\u003eProfile: @OneToOne(mappedBy=&quot;profile&quot;)\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"150\" class=\"sub\"\u003eFK: User.profile_id\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"180\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003e3. 1:N unidirectional\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"190\" width=\"100\" height=\"40\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"70\" y=\"215\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eDept\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M120 210 L200 210\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrREL)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"204\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003e1 ── N\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"200\" y=\"190\" width=\"100\" height=\"40\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"250\" y=\"215\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eEmp\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"198\" class=\"sub\"\u003eDept: @OneToMany + @JoinColumn (or @JoinTable)\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"214\" class=\"sub\"\u003eFK: Emp.dept_id (or join table) — owning is on the ONE side here\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"260\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003e4. N:1 unidirectional\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"270\" width=\"100\" height=\"40\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"70\" y=\"295\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eDept\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M200 290 L120 290\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrREL)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"284\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eN ── 1\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"200\" y=\"270\" width=\"100\" height=\"40\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"250\" y=\"295\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eEmp\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"278\" class=\"sub\"\u003eEmp: @ManyToOne + @JoinColumn\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"294\" class=\"sub\"\u003eFK: Emp.dept_id (MANY side owns — the natural place)\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"340\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003e5. 1:N / N:1 bidirectional ★ COMMON\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"350\" width=\"100\" height=\"40\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"70\" y=\"375\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eDept\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M120 370 L200 370\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrREL)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M200 378 L120 378\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrREL)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003crect x=\"200\" y=\"350\" width=\"100\" height=\"40\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"250\" y=\"375\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eEmp\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"358\" class=\"sub\"\u003eEmp: @ManyToOne + @JoinColumn (OWNING)\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"374\" class=\"sub\"\u003eDept: @OneToMany(mappedBy=&quot;dept&quot;)\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"390\" class=\"sub\"\u003eFK: Emp.dept_id · MANY side ALWAYS owns\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"420\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003e6. M:N unidirectional\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"430\" width=\"100\" height=\"40\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"70\" y=\"455\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eStudent\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M120 450 L200 450\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrREL)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"444\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eM ── N\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"200\" y=\"430\" width=\"100\" height=\"40\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"250\" y=\"455\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eCourse\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"438\" class=\"sub\"\u003eStudent: @ManyToMany + @JoinTable\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"454\" class=\"sub\"\u003eJoin table: STUDENT_COURSE\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"500\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003e7. M:N bidirectional\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"510\" width=\"100\" height=\"40\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"70\" y=\"535\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eStudent\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M120 530 L200 530\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrREL)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M200 538 L120 538\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrREL)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003crect x=\"200\" y=\"510\" width=\"100\" height=\"40\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"250\" y=\"535\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eCourse\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"518\" class=\"sub\"\u003eStudent: @ManyToMany + @JoinTable (OWNING)\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"534\" class=\"sub\"\u003eCourse: @ManyToMany(mappedBy=&quot;courses&quot;)\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"320\" y=\"550\" class=\"sub\"\u003eJoin table: STUDENT_COURSE\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"600\" width=\"720\" height=\"100\" class=\"box\" rx=\"5\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"380\" y=\"624\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003eReading guide\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"380\" y=\"646\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eAccent-bordered box = OWNING SIDE — has @JoinColumn / @JoinTable, holds the FK\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"380\" y=\"664\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003ePlain box = INVERSE SIDE — has mappedBy=&quot;ownerFieldName&quot;\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"380\" y=\"682\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eIn any 1:N or N:1, the MANY side owns. In M:N, either side may own (your choice).\u003c/text\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e","legend":null},{"kind":"h3","html":"Cascade + Fetch","text":"Cascade + Fetch"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCascadeType.ALL\u003c/strong\u003e — ops on parent cascade to children (persist, merge, remove, refresh, detach)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFetchType\u003c/strong\u003e: *ToOne = EAGER by default. *ToMany = LAZY by default.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eorphanRemoval=true\u003c/strong\u003e — remove child from parent&#39;s collection → DB DELETE\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **CascadeType.ALL** — ops on parent cascade to children (persist, merge, remove, refresh, detach)\n-   **FetchType**: \\*ToOne = EAGER by default. \\*ToMany = LAZY by default.\n-   **orphanRemoval=true** — remove child from parent's collection → DB DELETE"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e In 1:N, MANY side owns (has FK). In bidirectional, the owner has @JoinColumn; the inverse has mappedBy pointing to the owner&#39;s FIELD name.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Takeaway:** In 1:N, MANY side owns (has FK). In bidirectional, the owner has @JoinColumn; the inverse has mappedBy pointing to the owner's FIELD name."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"In a bidirectional M:N relationship between Student and Course, which side owns?","a":"Either can own. Whoever has @ManyToMany + @JoinTable = owner. The other has @ManyToMany(mappedBy=\"...\"). Usually the more \"active\" side is made owner by convention."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You write @OneToMany on the ONE side WITHOUT mappedBy. What happens?","a":"JPA assumes it's unidirectional and creates a join table (or FK based on defaults) — likely producing duplicate/conflicting mappings. Always use mappedBy on the inverse side of bidirectional."}]},{"n":6,"id":"4911-lesson-jpql-building-a-query-step-by-step","title":"JPQL — building a query step by step","hook":"Stop reading JPQL syntax. Start writing queries.","tags":["jpql"],"module":"JPQL / queries & transactions","blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"JPQL (Java Persistence Query Language) looks like SQL but operates on \u003cstrong\u003eentities + fields\u003c/strong\u003e, not tables + columns.","text":"JPQL (Java Persistence Query Language) looks like SQL but operates on **entities + fields**, not tables + columns."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Start simple","text":"Start simple"},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"-- All employees\nSELECT e FROM Employee e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Note: \u003ccode\u003eEmployee\u003c/code\u003e = entity class name (not &quot;EMPLOYEE&quot; table). \u003ccode\u003ee\u003c/code\u003e = alias. Alias is required.","text":"Note: `Employee` = entity class name (not \"EMPLOYEE\" table). `e` = alias. Alias is required."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Filter: WHERE","text":"Filter: WHERE"},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"SELECT e FROM Employee e WHERE e.salary \u003e 50000"},{"kind":"p","html":"Hardcoded values are bad. Use \u003cstrong\u003eparameters\u003c/strong\u003e:","text":"Hardcoded values are bad. Use **parameters**:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"SELECT e FROM Employee e WHERE e.salary \u003e :minSal"},{"kind":"p","html":"Then: \u003ccode\u003eq.setParameter(&quot;minSal&quot;, 50000)\u003c/code\u003e. Named params (\u003ccode\u003e:name\u003c/code\u003e) &gt; positional (\u003ccode\u003e?1\u003c/code\u003e).","text":"Then: `q.setParameter(\"minSal\", 50000)`. Named params (`:name`) \u003e positional (`?1`)."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Navigate relationships with dots","text":"Navigate relationships with dots"},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"SELECT e FROM Employee e WHERE e.department.name = :dept"},{"kind":"p","html":"JPA joins automatically. You don&#39;t write JOIN for simple paths. \u003ccode\u003ee.department\u003c/code\u003e = the Department entity, \u003ccode\u003ee.department.name\u003c/code\u003e = its name field.","text":"JPA joins automatically. You don't write JOIN for simple paths. `e.department` = the Department entity, `e.department.name` = its name field."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Explicit JOINs — when you need them","text":"Explicit JOINs — when you need them"},{"kind":"p","html":"You need JOIN when you want to project joined fields or filter by the joined side without navigation:","text":"You need JOIN when you want to project joined fields or filter by the joined side without navigation:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"SELECT e FROM Employee e JOIN e.projects p WHERE p.active = true"},{"kind":"h3","html":"JOIN FETCH — solve N+1 problem","text":"JOIN FETCH — solve N+1 problem"},{"kind":"p","html":"Without FETCH: load 100 employees, iterate, access \u003ccode\u003eemp.getDepartment().getName()\u003c/code\u003e → 100 extra SQL queries. N+1 disaster.","text":"Without FETCH: load 100 employees, iterate, access `emp.getDepartment().getName()` → 100 extra SQL queries. N+1 disaster."},{"kind":"p","html":"With FETCH: load both in ONE query.","text":"With FETCH: load both in ONE query."},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"SELECT e FROM Employee e JOIN FETCH e.department"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Aggregates","text":"Aggregates"},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"SELECT AVG(e.salary), COUNT(e), MAX(e.salary) FROM Employee e;\nSELECT e.department.name, COUNT(e) FROM Employee e\n  GROUP BY e.department.name\n  HAVING COUNT(e) \u003e 10"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Constructor expression — DTOs","text":"Constructor expression — DTOs"},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"SELECT new com.x.EmpSummary(e.id, e.name, e.salary) FROM Employee e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Returns \u003ccode\u003eEmpSummary\u003c/code\u003e DTOs directly (needs matching constructor).","text":"Returns `EmpSummary` DTOs directly (needs matching constructor)."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Practice: walk through a real query","text":"Practice: walk through a real query"},{"kind":"p","html":"From the midterm: given Customer⟷Reservation (N:N) and Reservation→Cruise (N:1), write &quot;all cruises that \u003ccode\u003e:cust\u003c/code\u003e has reserved.&quot;","text":"From the midterm: given Customer⟷Reservation (N:N) and Reservation→Cruise (N:1), write \"all cruises that `:cust` has reserved.\""},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 1 — what do you select?\u003c/strong\u003e Cruise objects. \u003ccode\u003eSELECT c FROM Cruise c\u003c/code\u003e","text":"**Step 1 — what do you select?** Cruise objects. `SELECT c FROM Cruise c`"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 2 — you need Reservations linked to Cruise.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eSELECT c FROM Cruise c JOIN c.reservations r\u003c/code\u003e","text":"**Step 2 — you need Reservations linked to Cruise.** `SELECT c FROM Cruise c JOIN c.reservations r`"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 3 — filter by customer.\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eJOIN r.customers cu WHERE cu = :cust\u003c/code\u003e","text":"**Step 3 — filter by customer.** `JOIN r.customers cu WHERE cu = :cust`"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eStep 4 — avoid duplicate cruises.\u003c/strong\u003e Add DISTINCT:","text":"**Step 4 — avoid duplicate cruises.** Add DISTINCT:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"SELECT DISTINCT c FROM Cruise c\n  JOIN c.reservations r\n  JOIN r.customers cu\n  WHERE cu = :cust"},{"kind":"h3","html":"EntityManager query methods","text":"EntityManager query methods"},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"TypedQuery\u003cCruise\u003e q = em.createQuery(jpql, Cruise.class);\nq.setParameter(\"cust\", someCustomer);\nList\u003cCruise\u003e results = q.getResultList();      // 0+ results\n\nCruise one = q.getSingleResult();               // EXACTLY 1 — or exception\n\nint count = em.createQuery(\"UPDATE Employee e SET e.salary = e.salary * 1.1\")\n              .executeUpdate();                 // bulk UPDATE/DELETE"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Entity names + field paths + aliases. Named parameters. DISTINCT for collection-based queries. FETCH to avoid N+1. Write queries yourself to build the reflex.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Takeaway:** Entity names + field paths + aliases. Named parameters. DISTINCT for collection-based queries. FETCH to avoid N+1. Write queries yourself to build the reflex."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Write JPQL: all employees whose manager has name \"Carol.\"","a":"SELECT e FROM Employee e WHERE e.manager.name = 'Carol' — assuming Employee has a self-referencing manager field."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Your query returns 5 duplicate Cruise rows. What's missing?","a":"DISTINCT. Joins on collections naturally produce duplicates when there are multiple matching children."}]},{"n":7,"id":"4911-lesson-transactions-acid-6-attributes-from-zero","title":"Transactions — ACID + 6 attributes from zero","hook":"What's a transaction? Why do we care? Then: the 6 attributes on a map.","tags":["transactions"],"module":"JPQL / queries & transactions","blocks":[{"kind":"h3","html":"What is a transaction?","text":"What is a transaction?"},{"kind":"p","html":"Imagine transferring $100 from Account A to Account B. Two steps:","text":"Imagine transferring $100 from Account A to Account B. Two steps:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSubtract $100 from A\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAdd $100 to B\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1.  Subtract $100 from A\n2.  Add $100 to B"},{"kind":"p","html":"What if step 1 succeeds but the server crashes before step 2? Money vanishes. Disaster.","text":"What if step 1 succeeds but the server crashes before step 2? Money vanishes. Disaster."},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003etransaction\u003c/strong\u003e wraps both steps: either both succeed, or \u003cstrong\u003eneither\u003c/strong\u003e takes effect.","text":"A **transaction** wraps both steps: either both succeed, or **neither** takes effect."},{"kind":"h3","html":"ACID properties","text":"ACID properties"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eA\u003c/strong\u003etomicity — all-or-nothing (the transfer example)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eC\u003c/strong\u003eonsistency — DB goes from valid state to valid state (no corrupt data)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eI\u003c/strong\u003esolation — concurrent transactions don&#39;t see each other&#39;s partial work\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eD\u003c/strong\u003eurability — once committed, survives crashes (written to disk)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **A**tomicity — all-or-nothing (the transfer example)\n-   **C**onsistency — DB goes from valid state to valid state (no corrupt data)\n-   **I**solation — concurrent transactions don't see each other's partial work\n-   **D**urability — once committed, survives crashes (written to disk)"},{"kind":"h3","html":"EJB handles transactions for you","text":"EJB handles transactions for you"},{"kind":"p","html":"You don&#39;t write \u003ccode\u003eBEGIN TRANSACTION\u003c/code\u003e. You annotate methods; the container handles the rest. Two modes:","text":"You don't write `BEGIN TRANSACTION`. You annotate methods; the container handles the rest. Two modes:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eContainer-Managed (CMT)\u003c/strong\u003e — default; declarative via \u003ccode\u003e@TransactionAttribute\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBean-Managed (BMT)\u003c/strong\u003e — you call \u003ccode\u003eutx.begin()\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003eutx.commit()\u003c/code\u003e manually. Rarely used.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **Container-Managed (CMT)** — default; declarative via `@TransactionAttribute`\n-   **Bean-Managed (BMT)** — you call `utx.begin()`, `utx.commit()` manually. Rarely used."},{"kind":"h3","html":"The 6 CMT attributes — the master table","text":"The 6 CMT attributes — the master table"},{"kind":"p","html":"When method \u003ccode\u003efoo()\u003c/code\u003e is called, the container asks: &quot;Does the caller already have an active TX?&quot; Based on \u003ccode\u003e@TransactionAttribute\u003c/code\u003e, it does one of 6 things:","text":"When method `foo()` is called, the container asks: \"Does the caller already have an active TX?\" Based on `@TransactionAttribute`, it does one of 6 things:"},{"kind":"diagram","title":"Transaction attribute decision matrix — color-coded","svg":"\u003csvg viewBox=\"0 0 720 320\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMidYMid meet\"\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"22\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003eContainer&#39;s decision per @TransactionAttribute\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"50\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eAttribute\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"340\" y=\"50\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eCaller HAS TX\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"500\" y=\"50\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eCaller NO TX\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"640\" y=\"50\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eTypical use\u003c/text\u003e\u003cline x1=\"20\" y1=\"58\" x2=\"700\" y2=\"58\" class=\"arrow-line\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"68\" width=\"280\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-ok\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003crect x=\"300\" y=\"68\" width=\"120\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"88\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eREQUIRED (default)\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"360\" y=\"88\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eJoin caller TX\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"420\" y=\"68\" width=\"120\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"480\" y=\"88\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eCreate new TX\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"620\" y=\"88\" class=\"sub\"\u003eDefault business methods\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"105\" width=\"280\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-warn\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003crect x=\"300\" y=\"105\" width=\"120\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-warn\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"125\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eREQUIRES_NEW\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"360\" y=\"125\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eSuspend + NEW TX\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"420\" y=\"105\" width=\"120\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"480\" y=\"125\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eCreate new TX\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"620\" y=\"125\" class=\"sub\"\u003eAudit log (independent commit)\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"142\" width=\"280\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-ok\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003crect x=\"300\" y=\"142\" width=\"120\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"162\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eSUPPORTS\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"360\" y=\"162\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eJoin caller TX\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"420\" y=\"142\" width=\"120\" height=\"32\" class=\"box\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"480\" y=\"162\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eNo TX\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"620\" y=\"162\" class=\"sub\"\u003eRead-only methods\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"179\" width=\"280\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-warn\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003crect x=\"300\" y=\"179\" width=\"120\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-warn\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"199\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eNOT_SUPPORTED\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"360\" y=\"199\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eSuspend + no TX\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"420\" y=\"179\" width=\"120\" height=\"32\" class=\"box\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"480\" y=\"199\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eNo TX\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"620\" y=\"199\" class=\"sub\"\u003eLegacy non-TX code\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"216\" width=\"280\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-ok\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003crect x=\"300\" y=\"216\" width=\"120\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"236\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eMANDATORY\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"360\" y=\"236\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eJoin caller TX\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"420\" y=\"216\" width=\"120\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-bad\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"480\" y=\"236\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eTHROW!\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"620\" y=\"236\" class=\"sub\"\u003eHelper expecting caller TX\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"253\" width=\"280\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-bad\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003crect x=\"300\" y=\"253\" width=\"120\" height=\"32\" class=\"box-bad\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"273\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eNEVER\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"360\" y=\"273\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eTHROW!\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"420\" y=\"253\" width=\"120\" height=\"32\" class=\"box\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"480\" y=\"273\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eNo TX\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"620\" y=\"273\" class=\"sub\"\u003eMust NOT be in TX\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"295\" width=\"14\" height=\"14\" class=\"box-accent\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"40\" y=\"306\" class=\"sub\"\u003enew/own TX\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"120\" y=\"295\" width=\"14\" height=\"14\" class=\"box-ok\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"140\" y=\"306\" class=\"sub\"\u003ejoin caller\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"210\" y=\"295\" width=\"14\" height=\"14\" class=\"box-warn\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"230\" y=\"306\" class=\"sub\"\u003esuspend\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"290\" y=\"295\" width=\"14\" height=\"14\" class=\"box-bad\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"310\" y=\"306\" class=\"sub\"\u003ethrow / no TX rejected\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"430\" y=\"295\" width=\"14\" height=\"14\" class=\"box\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"450\" y=\"306\" class=\"sub\"\u003eno TX\u003c/text\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e","legend":"\u003cstrong\u003eMemorize this grid.\u003c/strong\u003e Quiz 4 Q4/Q5/Q13 asked these distinctions directly."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Worked trace — REQUIRED calls REQUIRES_NEW that throws","text":"Worked trace — REQUIRED calls REQUIRES\\_NEW that throws"},{"kind":"p","html":"The matrix tells you the policy. A trace tells you what actually happens when policies compose. Walk through this one step by step.","text":"The matrix tells you the policy. A trace tells you what actually happens when policies compose. Walk through this one step by step."},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"@Stateless\npublic class OrderService {\n    @EJB private AuditService audit;\n\n    @TransactionAttribute(REQUIRED)              // method A\n    public void placeOrder(Order o) {\n        em.persist(o);                           //  line A1\n        audit.log(\"order \" + o.getId());         //  line A2 — calls B\n        em.persist(new Shipment(o));             //  line A3\n    }\n}\n\n@Stateless\npublic class AuditService {\n    @TransactionAttribute(REQUIRES_NEW)          // method B\n    public void log(String msg) {\n        em.persist(new AuditEntry(msg));         //  line B1\n        throw new RuntimeException(\"disk full\"); //  line B2 — system exception\n    }\n}"},{"kind":"diagram","title":"Client calls `placeOrder(o)` with NO active TX. Step through:","svg":"\u003csvg viewBox=\"0 0 760 280\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMidYMid meet\"\u003e\u003cdefs\u003e\u003cmarker id=\"arrTX\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"9\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto\"\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M0 0 L10 5 L0 10 Z\" fill=\"#a3a3a3\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003c/marker\u003e\u003c/defs\u003e\u003ctext x=\"20\" y=\"20\" class=\"label-accent\"\u003eREQUIRED → calls REQUIRES_NEW that throws\u003c/text\u003e\u003cline x1=\"80\" y1=\"50\" x2=\"740\" y2=\"50\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrTX)\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003ctext x=\"740\" y=\"42\" text-anchor=\"end\" class=\"sub\"\u003etime →\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"40\" y=\"80\" class=\"label\"\u003eTX-1\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"40\" y=\"94\" class=\"sub\"\u003e(REQUIRED)\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"80\" y=\"65\" width=\"160\" height=\"30\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"160\" y=\"85\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003ebegin · persist(o)\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"240\" y=\"65\" width=\"200\" height=\"30\" class=\"box-warn\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"340\" y=\"85\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eSUSPENDED (waiting on TX-2)\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"440\" y=\"65\" width=\"140\" height=\"30\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"510\" y=\"85\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eresumed (exception)\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"580\" y=\"65\" width=\"160\" height=\"30\" class=\"box-bad\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"660\" y=\"85\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eROLLBACK · o discarded\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"40\" y=\"140\" class=\"label\"\u003eTX-2\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"40\" y=\"154\" class=\"sub\"\u003e(REQUIRES_NEW)\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"240\" y=\"125\" width=\"100\" height=\"30\" class=\"box-accent\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"290\" y=\"145\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003ebegin · persist\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"340\" y=\"125\" width=\"60\" height=\"30\" class=\"box-bad\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"370\" y=\"145\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003ethrow\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"400\" y=\"125\" width=\"40\" height=\"30\" class=\"box-bad\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"420\" y=\"145\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eRB\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M240 95 L240 125\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrTX)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"180\" y=\"118\" class=\"sub\"\u003esuspend TX-1, start TX-2\u003c/text\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M420 155 L440 95\" class=\"arrow-line\" marker-end=\"url(#arrTX)\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ctext x=\"445\" y=\"160\" class=\"sub\"\u003eresume TX-1, propagate exception\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"40\" y=\"200\" class=\"label\"\u003eDB result\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"80\" y=\"185\" width=\"660\" height=\"30\" class=\"box-bad\" rx=\"3\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"410\" y=\"205\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eno Order · no Shipment · no AuditEntry — caller sees EJBException\u003c/text\u003e\u003crect x=\"20\" y=\"230\" width=\"200\" height=\"40\" class=\"box-ok\" rx=\"4\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"120\" y=\"250\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eIf A CATCHES the exception:\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"120\" y=\"264\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eTX-1 commits · only TX-2 lost\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"240\" y=\"252\" class=\"sub\"\u003eREQUIRES_NEW makes the inner TX independent —\u003c/text\u003e\u003ctext x=\"240\" y=\"268\" class=\"sub\"\u003ebut only the catch in A protects the outer TX from system-exception rollback.\u003c/text\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e","legend":null},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEnter A.\u003c/strong\u003e Caller has no TX. REQUIRED policy → container creates \u003cstrong\u003eTX-1\u003c/strong\u003e. A runs in TX-1. \u003ccode\u003eem.persist(o)\u003c/code\u003e enlists in TX-1.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eA calls B (line A2).\u003c/strong\u003e TX-1 is active. REQUIRES_NEW policy → container \u003cstrong\u003esuspends TX-1\u003c/strong\u003e and creates \u003cstrong\u003eTX-2\u003c/strong\u003e. B runs in TX-2. \u003ccode\u003eem.persist(AuditEntry)\u003c/code\u003e enlists in TX-2.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eB throws RuntimeException (line B2).\u003c/strong\u003e System exception → container marks \u003cstrong\u003eTX-2 rollback-only\u003c/strong\u003e, rolls it back (AuditEntry is discarded), then \u003cstrong\u003eresumes TX-1\u003c/strong\u003e and re-throws to A wrapped as \u003ccode\u003eEJBException\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBack in A.\u003c/strong\u003e A did not catch. The exception propagates out of A. Container marks \u003cstrong\u003eTX-1 rollback-only\u003c/strong\u003e (system exception escaping a bean method), rolls it back. \u003ccode\u003eo\u003c/code\u003e from line A1 is discarded. Line A3 never runs.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCaller sees\u003c/strong\u003e \u003ccode\u003eEJBException\u003c/code\u003e. Database has neither the Order, nor the Shipment, nor the AuditEntry.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1.  **Enter A.** Caller has no TX. REQUIRED policy → container creates **TX-1**. A runs in TX-1. `em.persist(o)` enlists in TX-1.\n2.  **A calls B (line A2).** TX-1 is active. REQUIRES\\_NEW policy → container **suspends TX-1** and creates **TX-2**. B runs in TX-2. `em.persist(AuditEntry)` enlists in TX-2.\n3.  **B throws RuntimeException (line B2).** System exception → container marks **TX-2 rollback-only**, rolls it back (AuditEntry is discarded), then **resumes TX-1** and re-throws to A wrapped as `EJBException`.\n4.  **Back in A.** A did not catch. The exception propagates out of A. Container marks **TX-1 rollback-only** (system exception escaping a bean method), rolls it back. `o` from line A1 is discarded. Line A3 never runs.\n5.  **Caller sees** `EJBException`. Database has neither the Order, nor the Shipment, nor the AuditEntry."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eContrast: what if A CATCHES the exception?\u003c/strong\u003e","text":"**Contrast: what if A CATCHES the exception?**"},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"try { audit.log(msg); }\ncatch (EJBException e) { /* swallow */ }"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSteps 1–3 identical. TX-2 rolls back. TX-1 resumes.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eA catches — exception does NOT escape A. TX-1 is NOT marked rollback-only.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eLine A3 runs, enlisted in TX-1. A returns normally.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eContainer commits TX-1. Order + Shipment persist. AuditEntry is GONE (TX-2 rolled back independently).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1.  Steps 1–3 identical. TX-2 rolls back. TX-1 resumes.\n2.  A catches — exception does NOT escape A. TX-1 is NOT marked rollback-only.\n3.  Line A3 runs, enlisted in TX-1. A returns normally.\n4.  Container commits TX-1. Order + Shipment persist. AuditEntry is GONE (TX-2 rolled back independently)."},{"kind":"p","html":"The decoupling is the point: REQUIRES_NEW lets the outer transaction survive a failure in the inner one, or fail independently — caller&#39;s choice via catch.","text":"The decoupling is the point: REQUIRES\\_NEW lets the outer transaction survive a failure in the inner one, or fail independently — caller's choice via catch."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"analogy","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExam-trap:\u003c/strong\u003e students assume REQUIRES_NEW &quot;protects&quot; the outer TX automatically. It does not — only the inner TX is isolated. If the exception escapes, the container rolls the outer TX back just like any other system exception. Catching the exception is what preserves the outer TX.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Exam-trap:** students assume REQUIRES\\_NEW \"protects\" the outer TX automatically. It does not — only the inner TX is isolated. If the exception escapes, the container rolls the outer TX back just like any other system exception. Catching the exception is what preserves the outer TX."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Mental model: two axes","text":"Mental model: two axes"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"analogy","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThink of each attribute as answering two questions:\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e&quot;If the caller has a TX, should I \u003cem\u003ejoin\u003c/em\u003e, \u003cem\u003esuspend\u003c/em\u003e, or \u003cem\u003ereject\u003c/em\u003e?&quot;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e&quot;If the caller has no TX, should I \u003cem\u003ecreate\u003c/em\u003e one, \u003cem\u003erun without\u003c/em\u003e, or \u003cem\u003ereject\u003c/em\u003e?&quot;\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"**Think of each attribute as answering two questions:**\n1.  \"If the caller has a TX, should I *join*, *suspend*, or *reject*?\"\n2.  \"If the caller has no TX, should I *create* one, *run without*, or *reject*?\""},{"kind":"h3","html":"Why REQUIRES_NEW matters","text":"Why REQUIRES\\_NEW matters"},{"kind":"p","html":"Scenario: a business method transfers money. Mid-transfer, you want to log an audit entry. If the transfer FAILS and rolls back, you still want the audit log. Solution: mark \u003ccode\u003elogAudit()\u003c/code\u003e as \u003ccode\u003eREQUIRES_NEW\u003c/code\u003e — its own TX. The outer TX can roll back without affecting the audit log.","text":"Scenario: a business method transfers money. Mid-transfer, you want to log an audit entry. If the transfer FAILS and rolls back, you still want the audit log. Solution: mark `logAudit()` as `REQUIRES_NEW` — its own TX. The outer TX can roll back without affecting the audit log."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Exceptions and rollback","text":"Exceptions and rollback"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSystem exceptions\u003c/strong\u003e (RuntimeException) → container auto-rolls back the TX\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eApplication exceptions\u003c/strong\u003e (checked) → DO NOT auto-rollback. Unless declared \u003ccode\u003e@ApplicationException(rollback=true)\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eManual: \u003ccode\u003esessionContext.setRollbackOnly()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **System exceptions** (RuntimeException) → container auto-rolls back the TX\n-   **Application exceptions** (checked) → DO NOT auto-rollback. Unless declared `@ApplicationException(rollback=true)`.\n-   Manual: `sessionContext.setRollbackOnly()`"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Default REQUIRED works for 95% of code. REQUIRES_NEW for independent sub-tasks (audit). MANDATORY for helper methods. Memorize the 6 × 2 table — Quiz 4 hammered these distinctions and they reappear.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Takeaway:** Default REQUIRED works for 95% of code. REQUIRES\\_NEW for independent sub-tasks (audit). MANDATORY for helper methods. Memorize the 6 × 2 table — Quiz 4 hammered these distinctions and they reappear."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Method A (REQUIRED) calls method B (REQUIRES\\_NEW). B throws RuntimeException. What happens to A's transaction?","a":"B's TX rolls back (system exception). A's TX is independent — it continues unless A explicitly handles/re-throws the exception. If A doesn't catch it, A's TX rolls back too."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"You want a method that REFUSES to run unless the caller already has a transaction. Which attribute?","a":"MANDATORY. Throws EJBTransactionRequiredException if no caller TX."}]},{"n":8,"id":"4911-lesson-reference-summary-callbacks-security-injection","title":"Reference summary — callbacks, security, injection","hook":"Overview only. Three smaller topics bundled for orientation. See Topic Deep-Dives for each concept (Ch 14, Ch 15, Ch 16) separately before the exam.","tags":["callbacks","security","jndi"],"module":"EJB — session beans","blocks":[{"kind":"h3","html":"Entity callbacks (Ch 14)","text":"Entity callbacks (Ch 14)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Lifecycle hooks fire automatically on entity events. Useful for audit timestamps, validation, computed fields.","text":"Lifecycle hooks fire automatically on entity events. Useful for audit timestamps, validation, computed fields."},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"@Entity\npublic class Order {\n    @Id private Long id;\n    private Date createdAt;\n    private Date updatedAt;\n\n    @PrePersist\n    void onCreate() {\n        createdAt = new Date();\n        updatedAt = new Date();\n    }\n\n    @PreUpdate\n    void onUpdate() {\n        updatedAt = new Date();\n    }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Seven callbacks:","text":"Seven callbacks:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@PrePersist\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e@PostPersist\u003c/code\u003e — around INSERT\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@PreUpdate\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e@PostUpdate\u003c/code\u003e — around UPDATE\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@PreRemove\u003c/code\u003e / \u003ccode\u003e@PostRemove\u003c/code\u003e — around DELETE\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@PostLoad\u003c/code\u003e — after SELECT loads entity (no @PreLoad exists)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   `@PrePersist` / `@PostPersist` — around INSERT\n-   `@PreUpdate` / `@PostUpdate` — around UPDATE\n-   `@PreRemove` / `@PostRemove` — around DELETE\n-   `@PostLoad` — after SELECT loads entity (no @PreLoad exists)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eRules:\u003c/strong\u003e no parameters, void return, MUST NOT call EntityManager or touch other entities.","text":"**Rules:** no parameters, void return, MUST NOT call EntityManager or touch other entities."},{"kind":"h3","html":"External listener","text":"External listener"},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"@Entity\n@EntityListeners(AuditListener.class)\npublic class Order { ... }\n\npublic class AuditListener {\n    @PrePersist\n    public void log(Object entity) {   // takes entity as parameter\n        System.out.println(\"Inserting: \" + entity);\n    }\n}"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Security (Ch 15)","text":"Security (Ch 15)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Role-based access control at method level. Container enforces.","text":"Role-based access control at method level. Container enforces."},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"@Stateless\n@DeclareRoles({\"ADMIN\",\"USER\",\"GUEST\"})      // all roles used\npublic class AccountService {\n\n    @PermitAll\n    public Account getAccount(Long id) { ... }        // anyone authenticated\n\n    @RolesAllowed({\"ADMIN\",\"USER\"})\n    public void update(Account a) { ... }             // specific roles\n\n    @RolesAllowed(\"ADMIN\")\n    public void delete(Long id) { ... }               // single role\n\n    @DenyAll\n    void internalOnly() { ... }                       // nobody can call\n\n    @RunAs(\"SYSTEM\")                                  // elevate identity\n    public void spawnAudit() { ... }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Programmatic: \u003ccode\u003ectx.isCallerInRole(&quot;ADMIN&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e, \u003ccode\u003ectx.getCallerPrincipal()\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"Programmatic: `ctx.isCallerInRole(\"ADMIN\")`, `ctx.getCallerPrincipal()`."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Injection (Ch 16)","text":"Injection (Ch 16)"},{"kind":"p","html":"The container wires dependencies via annotations at deployment:","text":"The container wires dependencies via annotations at deployment:"},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"@Stateless\npublic class OrderService {\n    @EJB private PaymentService payment;         // another EJB\n    @Resource private DataSource ds;             // JDBC datasource\n    @Resource(lookup=\"java:/jms/MyQueue\")\n        private Queue auditQueue;                 // JMS\n    @Resource private SessionContext ctx;        // container context\n    @PersistenceContext private EntityManager em;  // JPA\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003ePortable JNDI names\u003c/strong\u003e (when you can&#39;t inject):","text":"**Portable JNDI names** (when you can't inject):"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ejava:global/app/module/BeanName\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ejava:app/module/BeanName\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ejava:module/BeanName\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ejava:comp/env\u003c/code\u003e — local Environment Naming Context\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   `java:global/app/module/BeanName`\n-   `java:app/module/BeanName`\n-   `java:module/BeanName`\n-   `java:comp/env` — local Environment Naming Context"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Callbacks = lifecycle hooks (Pre/Post × Persist/Update/Remove + PostLoad). Security = @DeclareRoles + @RolesAllowed/@PermitAll/@DenyAll. Injection = @EJB/@Resource/@PersistenceContext.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Takeaway:** Callbacks = lifecycle hooks (Pre/Post × Persist/Update/Remove + PostLoad). Security = @DeclareRoles + @RolesAllowed/@PermitAll/@DenyAll. Injection = @EJB/@Resource/@PersistenceContext."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Which callback updates a \"lastModified\" timestamp on save?","a":"@PreUpdate (for updates) and @PrePersist (for initial insert). Use both if you want it set on create AND every update."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"A method marked @RolesAllowed({}) is callable by...?","a":"Nobody. Empty array = no roles permitted = equivalent to @DenyAll."}]},{"n":9,"id":"4911-lesson-reference-summary-rup-big-picture","title":"Reference summary — RUP big picture","hook":"Overview only. Covers waterfall-vs-iterative, the four RUP phases, nine workflows, six best practices, and EVMS at a high level. For deep study, drill each sub-topic from Topic Deep-Dives individually — the explain-it-back test fails when these are mashed together.","tags":["process"],"module":"Unified Process & architecture","blocks":[{"kind":"h3","html":"The old way: Waterfall","text":"The old way: Waterfall"},{"kind":"p","html":"Traditional: do all requirements → do all design → do all implementation → do all testing → deploy. One pass, top to bottom.","text":"Traditional: do all requirements → do all design → do all implementation → do all testing → deploy. One pass, top to bottom."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eProblem:\u003c/strong\u003e you don&#39;t discover real issues until testing (near the end). By then, requirements errors from step 1 are baked into every layer. Fixing is expensive. Risk STAYS HIGH until late.","text":"**Problem:** you don't discover real issues until testing (near the end). By then, requirements errors from step 1 are baked into every layer. Fixing is expensive. Risk STAYS HIGH until late."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"analogy","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAnalogy:\u003c/strong\u003e Building a house by drawing complete blueprints, then constructing everything in one shot, THEN having the client walk through. They hate the kitchen layout. You rebuild walls.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Analogy:** Building a house by drawing complete blueprints, then constructing everything in one shot, THEN having the client walk through. They hate the kitchen layout. You rebuild walls."},{"kind":"h3","html":"The RUP way: iterative","text":"The RUP way: iterative"},{"kind":"p","html":"Break the project into \u003cstrong\u003eiterations\u003c/strong\u003e. Each iteration = a mini-waterfall: requirements → analysis → design → code → test → assess. Usually 2-6 weeks.","text":"Break the project into **iterations**. Each iteration = a mini-waterfall: requirements → analysis → design → code → test → assess. Usually 2-6 weeks."},{"kind":"p","html":"After each iteration, you have a working (partial) system. You show it. You learn. Then you plan the next iteration.","text":"After each iteration, you have a working (partial) system. You show it. You learn. Then you plan the next iteration."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eRisk reduces continuously.\u003c/strong\u003e Problems found early = cheap to fix.","text":"**Risk reduces continuously.** Problems found early = cheap to fix."},{"kind":"diagram","title":"Risk over time — waterfall vs iterative (01BestPracticesMod / 02rup)","svg":"\u003csvg viewBox=\"0 0 680 260\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMidYMid meet\"\u003e\u003cline x1=\"50\" y1=\"210\" x2=\"670\" y2=\"210\" class=\"arrow-line\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003cline x1=\"50\" y1=\"30\" x2=\"50\" y2=\"210\" class=\"arrow-line\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003ctext x=\"360\" y=\"235\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003etime →\u003c/text\u003e \u003ctext x=\"25\" y=\"120\" transform=\"rotate(-90 25 120)\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003erisk →\u003c/text\u003e \u003ctext x=\"50\" y=\"25\" text-anchor=\"start\" class=\"sub\"\u003eHIGH\u003c/text\u003e \u003ctext x=\"50\" y=\"218\" text-anchor=\"start\" class=\"sub\" dx=\"-6\" dy=\"14\"\u003eLOW\u003c/text\u003e \u003cpath d=\"M 60 50 L 380 55 L 450 150 L 560 195 L 660 200\" stroke=\"#f7768e\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"2.5\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ccircle cx=\"660\" cy=\"200\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#f7768e\"\u003e\u003c/circle\u003e\u003ctext x=\"655\" y=\"70\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#f7768e\" font-size=\"11\"\u003eWaterfall — risk stays high, drops only after late testing\u003c/text\u003e \u003cpath d=\"M 60 55 Q 140 140 220 120 Q 300 100 360 140 Q 420 175 500 165 Q 570 175 640 195\" stroke=\"#9ece6a\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"2.5\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003ccircle cx=\"640\" cy=\"195\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#9ece6a\"\u003e\u003c/circle\u003e\u003ctext x=\"180\" y=\"200\" text-anchor=\"start\" fill=\"#9ece6a\" font-size=\"11\"\u003eIterative — each iteration exposes + mitigates risk\u003c/text\u003e \u003cg font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#565f89\"\u003e\u003cline x1=\"165\" y1=\"210\" x2=\"165\" y2=\"214\" stroke=\"#565f89\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003ctext x=\"165\" y=\"225\" text-anchor=\"middle\"\u003eiter 1\u003c/text\u003e \u003cline x1=\"280\" y1=\"210\" x2=\"280\" y2=\"214\" stroke=\"#565f89\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003ctext x=\"280\" y=\"225\" text-anchor=\"middle\"\u003eiter 2\u003c/text\u003e \u003cline x1=\"395\" y1=\"210\" x2=\"395\" y2=\"214\" stroke=\"#565f89\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003ctext x=\"395\" y=\"225\" text-anchor=\"middle\"\u003eiter 3\u003c/text\u003e \u003cline x1=\"510\" y1=\"210\" x2=\"510\" y2=\"214\" stroke=\"#565f89\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003ctext x=\"510\" y=\"225\" text-anchor=\"middle\"\u003eiter 4\u003c/text\u003e\u003c/g\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e","legend":null},{"kind":"p","html":"Waterfall discovers defects at the testing phase — one massive late drop. Iterative discovers defects per iteration in smaller, cheaper increments. Both eventually finish; only the cost curve differs.","text":"Waterfall discovers defects at the testing phase — one massive late drop. Iterative discovers defects per iteration in smaller, cheaper increments. Both eventually finish; only the cost curve differs."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Four phases of the project","text":"Four phases of the project"},{"kind":"p","html":"RUP lifecycle — phases, milestones, effort distribution","text":"RUP lifecycle — phases, milestones, effort distribution"},{"kind":"p","html":"Inception~10%","text":"Inception~10%"},{"kind":"p","html":"Elaboration~30%","text":"Elaboration~30%"},{"kind":"p","html":"Construction~50%","text":"Construction~50%"},{"kind":"p","html":"Transition~10%","text":"Transition~10%"},{"kind":"p","html":"LCO","text":"LCO"},{"kind":"p","html":"LCA","text":"LCA"},{"kind":"p","html":"IOC","text":"IOC"},{"kind":"p","html":"PR","text":"PR"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eLCO\u003c/strong\u003e Life-Cycle Objectives · \u003cstrong\u003eLCA\u003c/strong\u003e Life-Cycle Architecture · \u003cstrong\u003eIOC\u003c/strong\u003e Initial Operating Capability · \u003cstrong\u003ePR\u003c/strong\u003e Product Release\u003cbr\u003eEach phase contains 1-5 iterations. Bar widths show approximate effort % — Elaboration is longest in duration, Construction highest in effort.","text":"**LCO** Life-Cycle Objectives · **LCA** Life-Cycle Architecture · **IOC** Initial Operating Capability · **PR** Product Release  \nEach phase contains 1-5 iterations. Bar widths show approximate effort % — Elaboration is longest in duration, Construction highest in effort."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePhase\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMilestone\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eFocus\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003e% effort\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eInception\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eLCO (Life-Cycle Objectives)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eVision, business case, scope, feasibility\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~10%\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eElaboration\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eLCA (Life-Cycle Architecture)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eArchitecture baselined, ~80% requirements, major risks mitigated\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~30%\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eConstruction\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eIOC (Initial Operating Capability)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBuild, integrate, test most functionality\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~50%\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTransition\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePR (Product Release)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDeploy, UAT, training, handoff\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~10%\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"Each phase contains 1-5 iterations. Phases and iterations are \u003cstrong\u003eorthogonal\u003c/strong\u003e: iterations happen WITHIN phases.","text":"Each phase contains 1-5 iterations. Phases and iterations are **orthogonal**: iterations happen WITHIN phases."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Nine workflows (parallel processes)","text":"Nine workflows (parallel processes)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eBusiness Modeling\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRequirements\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAnalysis &amp; Design\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eImplementation\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTest\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDeployment\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eConfiguration &amp; Change Management\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eProject Management\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEnvironment\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1.  Business Modeling\n2.  Requirements\n3.  Analysis & Design\n4.  Implementation\n5.  Test\n6.  Deployment\n7.  Configuration & Change Management\n8.  Project Management\n9.  Environment"},{"kind":"p","html":"Each workflow runs through ALL phases but with different intensity. The &quot;hump chart&quot; shows this:","text":"Each workflow runs through ALL phases but with different intensity. The \"hump chart\" shows this:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRequirements hump peaks in Inception + Elaboration\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDesign hump peaks in Elaboration\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eImplementation hump peaks in Construction\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTest hump peaks in Construction + Transition\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   Requirements hump peaks in Inception + Elaboration\n-   Design hump peaks in Elaboration\n-   Implementation hump peaks in Construction\n-   Test hump peaks in Construction + Transition"},{"kind":"diagram","title":"Hump chart — workflow effort across phases (ReviewProcess)","svg":"\u003csvg viewBox=\"0 0 680 300\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMidYMid meet\"\u003e\u003cline x1=\"50\" y1=\"240\" x2=\"670\" y2=\"240\" class=\"arrow-line\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003cline x1=\"205\" y1=\"240\" x2=\"205\" y2=\"40\" stroke=\"#565f89\" stroke-width=\"0.6\" stroke-dasharray=\"2,3\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003cline x1=\"360\" y1=\"240\" x2=\"360\" y2=\"40\" stroke=\"#565f89\" stroke-width=\"0.6\" stroke-dasharray=\"2,3\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003cline x1=\"515\" y1=\"240\" x2=\"515\" y2=\"40\" stroke=\"#565f89\" stroke-width=\"0.6\" stroke-dasharray=\"2,3\"\u003e\u003c/line\u003e\u003ctext x=\"127\" y=\"258\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eInception\u003c/text\u003e \u003ctext x=\"282\" y=\"258\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eElaboration\u003c/text\u003e \u003ctext x=\"437\" y=\"258\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eConstruction\u003c/text\u003e \u003ctext x=\"592\" y=\"258\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"label\"\u003eTransition\u003c/text\u003e \u003ctext x=\"25\" y=\"150\" transform=\"rotate(-90 25 150)\" text-anchor=\"middle\" class=\"sub\"\u003eeffort →\u003c/text\u003e \u003cpath d=\"M 50 238 Q 127 150 215 235\" stroke=\"#e3af68\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"2\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M 90 238 Q 210 95 345 236\" stroke=\"#7aa2f7\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"2\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M 160 236 Q 290 55 430 238\" stroke=\"#bb9af7\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"2\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M 260 236 Q 437 45 610 236\" stroke=\"#9ece6a\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"2.5\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M 330 236 Q 495 70 640 235\" stroke=\"#f7768e\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"2\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003cpath d=\"M 475 238 Q 592 135 660 236\" stroke=\"#7dcfff\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"2\"\u003e\u003c/path\u003e\u003cg font-size=\"11\" font-family=\"sans-serif\"\u003e\u003crect x=\"60\" y=\"275\" width=\"12\" height=\"3\" fill=\"#e3af68\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"78\" y=\"279\" class=\"sub\"\u003eBusiness Modeling\u003c/text\u003e \u003crect x=\"190\" y=\"275\" width=\"12\" height=\"3\" fill=\"#7aa2f7\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"208\" y=\"279\" class=\"sub\"\u003eRequirements\u003c/text\u003e \u003crect x=\"298\" y=\"275\" width=\"12\" height=\"3\" fill=\"#bb9af7\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"316\" y=\"279\" class=\"sub\"\u003eAnalysis &amp; Design\u003c/text\u003e \u003crect x=\"420\" y=\"275\" width=\"12\" height=\"3\" fill=\"#9ece6a\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"438\" y=\"279\" class=\"sub\"\u003eImplementation\u003c/text\u003e \u003crect x=\"540\" y=\"275\" width=\"12\" height=\"3\" fill=\"#f7768e\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"558\" y=\"279\" class=\"sub\"\u003eTest\u003c/text\u003e \u003crect x=\"580\" y=\"290\" width=\"12\" height=\"3\" fill=\"#7dcfff\"\u003e\u003c/rect\u003e\u003ctext x=\"598\" y=\"294\" class=\"sub\"\u003eDeployment\u003c/text\u003e\u003c/g\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e","legend":null},{"kind":"p","html":"Each hump = one workflow. Height = effort intensity. Humps peak in different phases but every workflow runs in every phase (no waterfall). Three supporting workflows (Config &amp; Change Mgmt, Project Mgmt, Environment) run flat across all phases and are omitted from the curve chart to reduce clutter.","text":"Each hump = one workflow. Height = effort intensity. Humps peak in different phases but every workflow runs in every phase (no waterfall). Three supporting workflows (Config & Change Mgmt, Project Mgmt, Environment) run flat across all phases and are omitted from the curve chart to reduce clutter."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Six best practices (foundation of RUP)","text":"Six best practices (foundation of RUP)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDevelop iteratively\u003c/strong\u003e — discover problems early\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eManage requirements\u003c/strong\u003e — traceable from capture to test\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUse component-based architectures\u003c/strong\u003e — reduce brittleness\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eModel visually (UML)\u003c/strong\u003e — reduce ambiguity\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eVerify quality\u003c/strong\u003e — continuous testing\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eControl changes\u003c/strong\u003e — configuration management\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1.  **Develop iteratively** — discover problems early\n2.  **Manage requirements** — traceable from capture to test\n3.  **Use component-based architectures** — reduce brittleness\n4.  **Model visually (UML)** — reduce ambiguity\n5.  **Verify quality** — continuous testing\n6.  **Control changes** — configuration management"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Earned Value Management (EVMS) — the project math","text":"Earned Value Management (EVMS) — the project math"},{"kind":"p","html":"Track project health with 3 numbers:","text":"Track project health with 3 numbers:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBCWS\u003c/strong\u003e (planned value) — budget for work SCHEDULED by this date\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBCWP\u003c/strong\u003e (earned value) — budget for work ACTUALLY completed\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eACWP\u003c/strong\u003e — ACTUAL money spent\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **BCWS** (planned value) — budget for work SCHEDULED by this date\n-   **BCWP** (earned value) — budget for work ACTUALLY completed\n-   **ACWP** — ACTUAL money spent"},{"kind":"p","html":"Derived:","text":"Derived:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCV = BCWP − ACWP\u003c/strong\u003e → cost variance. + = under budget.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSV = BCWP − BCWS\u003c/strong\u003e → schedule variance. + = ahead.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCPI = BCWP / ACWP\u003c/strong\u003e → cost efficiency. &gt;1 = good.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSPI = BCWP / BCWS\u003c/strong\u003e → schedule efficiency. &gt;1 = ahead.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEAC = BAC / CPI\u003c/strong\u003e → projected final cost.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **CV = BCWP − ACWP** → cost variance. + = under budget.\n-   **SV = BCWP − BCWS** → schedule variance. + = ahead.\n-   **CPI = BCWP / ACWP** → cost efficiency. \u003e1 = good.\n-   **SPI = BCWP / BCWS** → schedule efficiency. \u003e1 = ahead.\n-   **EAC = BAC / CPI** → projected final cost."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e 4 phases (IECt with milestones LCO/LCA/IOC/PR), 9 workflows, 6 best practices. Iterative = continuous risk reduction. EVMS uses BCWS/BCWP/ACWP + simple subtraction/division.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Takeaway:** 4 phases (IECt with milestones LCO/LCA/IOC/PR), 9 workflows, 6 best practices. Iterative = continuous risk reduction. EVMS uses BCWS/BCWP/ACWP + simple subtraction/division."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"BCWS = $100k, BCWP = $80k, ACWP = $90k. Is the project ahead or behind? Under or over budget?","a":"SV = 80 − 100 = −20k → BEHIND schedule. CV = 80 − 90 = −10k → OVER budget. Both negative = bad."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"During which phase is the architecture baselined?","a":"Elaboration. Milestone = LCA (Life-Cycle Architecture). Architecture must be stable before Construction begins, so risks are mitigated."}]},{"n":10,"id":"4911-lesson-reference-summary-uc-driven-bce-design-testing-mbti","title":"Reference summary — UC-driven, BCE, design, testing, MBTI","hook":"Overview only. Bundles use-case driven development, BCE analysis stereotypes, analysis-vs-design contrast, testing levels, and MBTI preferences. Each sub-topic has its own deep-dive — use this lesson for orientation, not primary study.","tags":["mbti","testing","analysis"],"module":"Testing, EVMS & soft skills","blocks":[{"kind":"h3","html":"The central idea","text":"The central idea"},{"kind":"p","html":"RUP is \u003cstrong\u003euse-case driven\u003c/strong\u003e. Use cases aren&#39;t just documentation — they are the primary artifact that drives every other workflow.","text":"RUP is **use-case driven**. Use cases aren't just documentation — they are the primary artifact that drives every other workflow."},{"kind":"h3","html":"What is a use case?","text":"What is a use case?"},{"kind":"p","html":"A \u003cstrong\u003euse case\u003c/strong\u003e describes a sequence of interactions between an \u003cstrong\u003eactor\u003c/strong\u003e (user or external system) and the system, achieving a goal.","text":"A **use case** describes a sequence of interactions between an **actor** (user or external system) and the system, achieving a goal."},{"kind":"p","html":"Structure:","text":"Structure:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eActor\u003c/strong\u003e — who initiates it (Customer, Admin, PaymentGateway)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePreconditions\u003c/strong\u003e — what must be true before\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMain flow\u003c/strong\u003e — the happy path, step by step\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAlternate flows\u003c/strong\u003e — variations, error recovery\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePostconditions\u003c/strong\u003e — what&#39;s true after\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **Actor** — who initiates it (Customer, Admin, PaymentGateway)\n-   **Preconditions** — what must be true before\n-   **Main flow** — the happy path, step by step\n-   **Alternate flows** — variations, error recovery\n-   **Postconditions** — what's true after"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eExample:\u003c/strong\u003e &quot;Book a Flight&quot;\u003cbr\u003eActor: Customer.\u003cbr\u003eMain flow: Customer searches flights → selects one → enters payment → system confirms → booking created.\u003cbr\u003eAlternate: payment declined → retry prompt.","text":"**Example:** \"Book a Flight\"  \nActor: Customer.  \nMain flow: Customer searches flights → selects one → enters payment → system confirms → booking created.  \nAlternate: payment declined → retry prompt."},{"kind":"p","html":"Use cases drive every workflow (big picture)","text":"Use cases drive every workflow (big picture)"},{"kind":"mermaid","source":"flowchart TB\n  UC((\"USE CASE\"))\n  R[\"Requirements\u003cbr/\u003ecapture functional reqs\"]\n  A[\"Analysis\u003cbr/\u003eBCE realization\"]\n  D[\"Design\u003cbr/\u003esequence diagrams\"]\n  I[\"Implementation\u003cbr/\u003ecomponents\"]\n  T[\"Test\u003cbr/\u003etest cases per flow\"]\n  P[\"Iteration Plan\u003cbr/\u003eprioritized UCs\"]\n  UC --\u003e R\n  UC --\u003e A\n  UC --\u003e D\n  UC --\u003e I\n  UC --\u003e T\n  UC --\u003e P\n  classDef hub fill:#2a3a4a,stroke:#7aa2f7,color:#7aa2f7,stroke-width:2px\n  class UC hub"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eOne use case threads through all six workflows.\u003c/strong\u003e Requirements → Analysis classes → Design classes → Code → Test cases → Iteration scheduling. This is why &quot;use-case driven&quot; matters — single source of truth links the entire lifecycle.\u003cbr\u003eBruce: &quot;Students fail big-picture questions by getting stuck in details.&quot; This diagram IS the big picture.","text":"**One use case threads through all six workflows.** Requirements → Analysis classes → Design classes → Code → Test cases → Iteration scheduling. This is why \"use-case driven\" matters — single source of truth links the entire lifecycle.  \nBruce: \"Students fail big-picture questions by getting stuck in details.\" This diagram IS the big picture."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Use cases drive EVERYTHING","text":"Use cases drive EVERYTHING"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRequirements\u003c/strong\u003e: UCs ARE the functional requirements — no need to duplicate\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAnalysis\u003c/strong\u003e: each UC decomposed into analysis classes (BCE); a \u003cstrong\u003euse-case realization\u003c/strong\u003e shows which classes collaborate\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDesign\u003c/strong\u003e: analysis refined into design classes; realization becomes a sequence diagram of design objects\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eImplementation\u003c/strong\u003e: design classes → code; components map to UCs\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTest\u003c/strong\u003e: every UC → test cases (main flow + alternates)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIteration planning\u003c/strong\u003e: UCs prioritized (by risk + value + dependencies); each iteration delivers a set end-to-end\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1.  **Requirements**: UCs ARE the functional requirements — no need to duplicate\n2.  **Analysis**: each UC decomposed into analysis classes (BCE); a **use-case realization** shows which classes collaborate\n3.  **Design**: analysis refined into design classes; realization becomes a sequence diagram of design objects\n4.  **Implementation**: design classes → code; components map to UCs\n5.  **Test**: every UC → test cases (main flow + alternates)\n6.  **Iteration planning**: UCs prioritized (by risk + value + dependencies); each iteration delivers a set end-to-end"},{"kind":"callout","variant":"analogy","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAnalogy:\u003c/strong\u003e A use case is like a movie script. The same script is used by the director (architect), cinematographer (designer), actors (programmers), editor (testers). Everyone works from the same source of truth.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Analogy:** A use case is like a movie script. The same script is used by the director (architect), cinematographer (designer), actors (programmers), editor (testers). Everyone works from the same source of truth."},{"kind":"h3","html":"BCE — the three analysis class stereotypes","text":"BCE — the three analysis class stereotypes"},{"kind":"p","html":"When analyzing a use case, classify every class into one of three roles:","text":"When analyzing a use case, classify every class into one of three roles:"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eStereotype\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eRole\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eRule\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eReal example\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBoundary\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eInterface with the outside world (UI, external APIs)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOne per actor-usecase pair\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBookFlightPage, PaymentGatewayAdapter\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eControl\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOrchestrates the workflow of a use case\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eTypically one per use case\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBookFlightController\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEntity\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePersistent domain objects / important state\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDerived from the domain model\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eFlight, Booking, Customer, Payment\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"A use-case realization is typically drawn as a \u003cstrong\u003ecollaboration diagram\u003c/strong\u003e (Quiz 4 Q17) showing these classes collaborating.","text":"A use-case realization is typically drawn as a **collaboration diagram** (Quiz 4 Q17) showing these classes collaborating."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Analysis vs Design model","text":"Analysis vs Design model"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAnalysis model\u003c/strong\u003e — technology-independent. &quot;What needs to exist.&quot; Uses BCE stereotypes.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDesign model\u003c/strong\u003e — technology-specific. &quot;How it&#39;s actually built.&quot; Becomes @Entity, JSF pages, EJBs.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **Analysis model** — technology-independent. \"What needs to exist.\" Uses BCE stereotypes.\n-   **Design model** — technology-specific. \"How it's actually built.\" Becomes @Entity, JSF pages, EJBs."},{"kind":"p","html":"The System Analyst owns the integrity of the analysis model (Quiz 4 Q18).","text":"The System Analyst owns the integrity of the analysis model (Quiz 4 Q18)."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Testing types you need to know","text":"Testing types you need to know"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUnit\u003c/strong\u003e (white-box, code visibility) vs \u003cstrong\u003eIntegration\u003c/strong\u003e vs \u003cstrong\u003eSystem\u003c/strong\u003e (black-box) vs \u003cstrong\u003eAcceptance\u003c/strong\u003e (black-box, user validates)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePerformance\u003c/strong\u003e — response + processing time (Quiz 4 Q6)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLoad\u003c/strong\u003e — concurrent users\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eVolume\u003c/strong\u003e — large data\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eConfiguration\u003c/strong\u003e — different environments\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **Unit** (white-box, code visibility) vs **Integration** vs **System** (black-box) vs **Acceptance** (black-box, user validates)\n-   **Performance** — response + processing time (Quiz 4 Q6)\n-   **Load** — concurrent users\n-   **Volume** — large data\n-   **Configuration** — different environments"},{"kind":"h3","html":"MBTI — preferences on the team (Quiz 4 heavy)","text":"MBTI — preferences on the team (Quiz 4 heavy)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eE/I\u003c/strong\u003e — Extraversion/Introversion (attitude toward world; E = face-to-face)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eS/N\u003c/strong\u003e — Sensing/Intuition (perception function; N = new complex problems)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eT/F\u003c/strong\u003e — Thinking/Feeling (judging function; F = fair)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eJ/P\u003c/strong\u003e — Judging/Perceiving (outer-world lifestyle; J = decide quickly; P = enjoy surprises)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **E/I** — Extraversion/Introversion (attitude toward world; E = face-to-face)\n-   **S/N** — Sensing/Intuition (perception function; N = new complex problems)\n-   **T/F** — Thinking/Feeling (judging function; F = fair)\n-   **J/P** — Judging/Perceiving (outer-world lifestyle; J = decide quickly; P = enjoy surprises)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Perceiving functions = S + N (gather info). Judging functions = T + F (decide).","text":"Perceiving functions = S + N (gather info). Judging functions = T + F (decide)."},{"kind":"callout","variant":"takeaway","html":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTakeaway:\u003c/strong\u003e Use cases drive the entire process. Three BCE stereotypes classify analysis classes. Collaboration diagrams show interactions. Testing types + MBTI dimensions are high-yield rote memorization.\u003c/p\u003e","text":"**Takeaway:** Use cases drive the entire process. Three BCE stereotypes classify analysis classes. Collaboration diagrams show interactions. Testing types + MBTI dimensions are high-yield rote memorization."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"In a \"Book Flight\" use case, which BCE would \"BookFlightPage\" be?","a":"Boundary — it's the UI interface between the Customer actor and the system."},{"kind":"checkpoint","q":"Is \"Perceiving\" (the J/P pole) the same as a \"perceiving function\"?","a":"No — tricky distinction. J/P is the \"attitude toward the outer world\" dimension. Perceiving FUNCTIONS are Sensing + Intuition (info gathering). Confusing terminology; Bruce will trap you on this."}]}],"codePractice":[{"n":1,"id":"4911-cp-p1-simple-entity-with-auto-gen-pk","title":"P1 · Simple entity with auto-gen PK","lang":"java","tags":["jpa"],"variant":"annotation","code":"@Entity\n@Table(name = \"CUSTOMER\")\npublic class Customer {\n    @Id\n    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.AUTO)\n    private Long id;\n\n    @Column(name = \"FIRST_NAME\")\n    private String firstName;\n\n    @Column(name = \"LAST_NAME\")\n    private String lastName;\n\n    @Column(nullable = false, unique = true)\n    private String email;\n\n    @Temporal(TemporalType.TIMESTAMP)\n    @Column(name = \"REGISTRATION_DATE\")\n    private java.util.Date registrationDate;\n\n    @Transient\n    private String computedFullName;\n    // getters/setters...\n}","notes":[{"line":1,"tag":"`@Entity`","text":"@Entity + @Table first."},{"line":4,"tag":"`@Id`","text":"@Id + @GeneratedValue for auto-gen."},{"line":8,"tag":"`@Column`","text":"@Column constraints on email."},{"line":17,"tag":"`@Temporal`","text":"@Temporal required for java.util.Date."},{"line":21,"tag":"`@Transient`","text":"@Transient on computed field."}]},{"n":2,"id":"4911-cp-p2-1-1-bidirectional-relationship","title":"P2 · 1:1 bidirectional relationship","lang":"java","tags":["relationships"],"variant":"annotation","code":"@Entity\npublic class User {\n    @Id\n    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.AUTO)\n    private Long id;\n\n    @Column(nullable = false)\n    private String username;\n\n    @OneToOne(mappedBy = \"user\", cascade = CascadeType.ALL, orphanRemoval = true)\n    private UserProfile profile;\n}\n\n@Entity\npublic class UserProfile {\n    @Id\n    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.AUTO)\n    private Long id;\n\n    private String bio;\n\n    @OneToOne\n    @JoinColumn(name = \"USER_ID\")\n    private User user;\n}","notes":[{"line":23,"tag":"`@JoinColumn`","text":"Owning side = side with @JoinColumn (UserProfile)."},{"line":2,"tag":"User inverse →","text":"User inverse → mappedBy=\"user\" (field name on UserProfile)."},{"line":10,"tag":"Cascade + orphanRemoval","text":"Cascade + orphanRemoval on User propagates delete."}]},{"n":3,"id":"4911-cp-p3-m-n-bidirectional-relationship","title":"P3 · M:N bidirectional relationship","lang":"java","tags":["relationships"],"variant":"annotation","code":"@Entity\npublic class Student {\n    @Id\n    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.AUTO)\n    private Long id;\n\n    private String name;\n\n    @ManyToMany\n    @JoinTable(\n        name = \"STUDENT_COURSE\",\n        joinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = \"STUDENT_ID\"),\n        inverseJoinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = \"COURSE_ID\")\n    )\n    private Set\u003cCourse\u003e courses = new HashSet\u003c\u003e();\n}\n\n@Entity\npublic class Course {\n    @Id\n    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.AUTO)\n    private Long id;\n\n    private String title;\n\n    @ManyToMany(mappedBy = \"courses\")\n    private Set\u003cStudent\u003e students = new HashSet\u003c\u003e();\n}","notes":[{"line":10,"tag":"`@JoinTable`","text":"Owning side has @JoinTable with joinColumns (owner's FK) + inverseJoinColumns (other side's FK)."},{"line":26,"tag":"Inverse side uses","text":"Inverse side uses mappedBy pointing to owner's field name (\"courses\")."}]},{"n":4,"id":"4911-cp-p4-inheritance-single-table","title":"P4 · Inheritance — SINGLE_TABLE","lang":"java","tags":["inheritance"],"variant":"annotation","code":"@Entity\n@Inheritance(strategy = InheritanceType.SINGLE_TABLE)\n@DiscriminatorColumn(name = \"SHAPE_TYPE\", discriminatorType = DiscriminatorType.STRING)\npublic class Shape {\n    @Id\n    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.AUTO)\n    private Long id;\n\n    private String color;\n}\n\n@Entity\n@DiscriminatorValue(\"CIRCLE\")\npublic class Circle extends Shape {\n    private double radius;\n}\n\n@Entity\n@DiscriminatorValue(\"RECTANGLE\")\npublic class Rectangle extends Shape {\n    private double width;\n    private double height;\n}","notes":[{"line":1,"tag":"`@Entity`","text":"Parent: @Entity + @Inheritance + @DiscriminatorColumn."},{"line":13,"tag":"`@Entity`","text":"Subclass: @Entity + @DiscriminatorValue."},{"line":5,"tag":"`@Id`","text":"Parent holds @Id — subclasses inherit it."},{"line":1,"tag":"All columns in","text":"All columns in one table."}]},{"n":5,"id":"4911-cp-p5-composite-key-embeddedid","title":"P5 · Composite key (@EmbeddedId)","lang":"java","tags":["ejb"],"variant":"annotation","code":"@Embeddable\npublic class OrderLineKey implements Serializable {\n    @Column(name = \"ORDER_ID\")\n    private Long orderId;\n\n    @Column(name = \"LINE_NUMBER\")\n    private int lineNumber;\n\n    public OrderLineKey() { }\n    public OrderLineKey(Long orderId, int lineNumber) {\n        this.orderId = orderId;\n        this.lineNumber = lineNumber;\n    }\n\n    @Override\n    public boolean equals(Object o) {\n        if (!(o instanceof OrderLineKey)) return false;\n        OrderLineKey k = (OrderLineKey) o;\n        return orderId.equals(k.orderId) && lineNumber == k.lineNumber;\n    }\n\n    @Override\n    public int hashCode() {\n        return orderId.hashCode() * 31 + lineNumber;\n    }\n}\n\n@Entity\npublic class OrderLine {\n    @EmbeddedId\n    private OrderLineKey id;\n\n    private String productName;\n    private int quantity;\n}","notes":[{"line":1,"tag":"`@Embeddable`","text":"@Embeddable on PK class + implements Serializable + equals/hashCode + no-arg ctor."},{"line":28,"tag":"`@EmbeddedId`","text":"Entity uses @EmbeddedId (single field)."},{"line":1,"tag":"Access via orderLine.getId().getOrderId()","text":"Access via orderLine.getId().getOrderId()."},{"line":1,"tag":"`@IdClass`","text":"Alternative: @IdClass with two @Id fields in entity."}]}],"topicDives":[{"id":"4911-topic-analysis-bce-stereotypes","title":"Analysis — BCE Stereotypes","pillar":"process","priority":"high","chapter":"","tags":["analysis","process"],"blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Analysis model = technology-independent (what), Design model = technology-dependent (how).","text":"Analysis model = technology-independent (what), Design model = technology-dependent (how)."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eStereotype\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eRole\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eRule\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBoundary\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUI, external interfaces (web page, API client)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOne per \u003cem\u003eactor-usecase\u003c/em\u003e pair\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eControl\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOrchestrates workflow for a use case\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eTypically one per use case\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEntity\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePersistent domain object, important state\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDerived from domain model\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDiagrams used: class diagram (structure), \u003cstrong\u003ecollaboration diagram\u003c/strong\u003e (interactions — Quiz 4 Q17)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSystem Analyst\u003c/strong\u003e owns integrity of the analysis model as a whole (Quiz 4 Q18)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eArchitect\u003c/strong\u003e defines architecture-significant classes\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUse-case engineer\u003c/strong\u003e owns individual UC realizations\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   Diagrams used: class diagram (structure), **collaboration diagram** (interactions — Quiz 4 Q17)\n-   **System Analyst** owns integrity of the analysis model as a whole (Quiz 4 Q18)\n-   **Architect** defines architecture-significant classes\n-   **Use-case engineer** owns individual UC realizations\n"}]},{"id":"4911-topic-earned-value-management-evms","title":"Earned Value Management (EVMS)","pillar":"process","priority":"high","chapter":"","tags":["evms","process"],"blocks":[{"kind":"h3","html":"The acronyms","text":"The acronyms"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eTerm\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMeaning\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBCWS\u003c/strong\u003e / PV\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBudgeted Cost of Work Scheduled — planned value through date\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBCWP\u003c/strong\u003e / EV\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBudgeted Cost of Work Performed — earned value\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eACWP\u003c/strong\u003e / AC\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eActual Cost of Work Performed\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBAC\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBudget At Completion — total planned budget\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEAC\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eEstimate At Completion — projected final cost\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Formulas","text":"Formulas"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCost Variance\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eCV = BCWP − ACWP\u003c/code\u003e    (positive = under budget)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSchedule Variance\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eSV = BCWP − BCWS\u003c/code\u003e    (positive = ahead)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCost Performance Index\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eCPI = BCWP / ACWP\u003c/code\u003e    (&gt;1 = efficient)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSchedule Performance Index\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eSPI = BCWP / BCWS\u003c/code\u003e    (&gt;1 = ahead)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEstimate At Completion\u003c/strong\u003e: \u003ccode\u003eEAC = BAC / CPI\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **Cost Variance**: `CV = BCWP − ACWP`    (positive = under budget)\n-   **Schedule Variance**: `SV = BCWP − BCWS`    (positive = ahead)\n-   **Cost Performance Index**: `CPI = BCWP / ACWP`    (\u003e1 = efficient)\n-   **Schedule Performance Index**: `SPI = BCWP / BCWS`    (\u003e1 = ahead)\n-   **Estimate At Completion**: `EAC = BAC / CPI`"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cem\u003eNote: some sources use CV = ACWP − BCWP (reversed convention). Stick with the convention in the course slides: CV = BCWP − ACWP.\u003c/em\u003e","text":"*Note: some sources use CV = ACWP − BCWP (reversed convention). Stick with the convention in the course slides: CV = BCWP − ACWP.*"}]},{"id":"4911-topic-ejb-security","title":"EJB Security","pillar":"tech","priority":"med","chapter":"Ch 15","tags":["ejb","security","tech"],"blocks":[{"kind":"h3","html":"Mechanism — how declarative security is evaluated","text":"Mechanism — how declarative security is evaluated"},{"kind":"p","html":"EJB security is checked \u003cstrong\u003eper method invocation\u003c/strong\u003e, not once per session. When a client calls a business method, the container intercepts the call before executing the bean code and asks two questions: (1) who is the caller&#39;s Principal (carried in the invocation context from the authenticated login), and (2) does that Principal hold any role listed in the method&#39;s \u003ccode\u003e@RolesAllowed\u003c/code\u003e?","text":"EJB security is checked **per method invocation**, not once per session. When a client calls a business method, the container intercepts the call before executing the bean code and asks two questions: (1) who is the caller's Principal (carried in the invocation context from the authenticated login), and (2) does that Principal hold any role listed in the method's `@RolesAllowed`?"},{"kind":"p","html":"Precedence rule: method-level annotations override class-level. \u003ccode\u003e@RolesAllowed(&quot;ADMIN&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e on a single method overrides a class-level \u003ccode\u003e@PermitAll\u003c/code\u003e. \u003ccode\u003e@DenyAll\u003c/code\u003e on a method blocks it for everyone regardless of class policy. If no annotation applies, the default is unchecked (open). If the check fails, the container throws \u003ccode\u003eEJBAccessException\u003c/code\u003e \u003cem\u003ebefore\u003c/em\u003e your method body runs — the bean never sees the call.","text":"Precedence rule: method-level annotations override class-level. `@RolesAllowed(\"ADMIN\")` on a single method overrides a class-level `@PermitAll`. `@DenyAll` on a method blocks it for everyone regardless of class policy. If no annotation applies, the default is unchecked (open). If the check fails, the container throws `EJBAccessException` *before* your method body runs — the bean never sees the call."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e@RunAs(&quot;SYSTEM&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e does not affect the caller check on THIS method. It changes the Principal used for \u003cem\u003edownstream\u003c/em\u003e calls the bean makes. Use this when a bean needs elevated privileges to call another bean.","text":"`@RunAs(\"SYSTEM\")` does not affect the caller check on THIS method. It changes the Principal used for *downstream* calls the bean makes. Use this when a bean needs elevated privileges to call another bean."},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"@Stateless\n@DeclareRoles({\"ADMIN\",\"USER\",\"GUEST\"})\npublic class AccountService {\n\n    @PermitAll                          // any authenticated user\n    public Account getAccount(Long id) { ... }\n\n    @RolesAllowed({\"ADMIN\",\"USER\"})     // only these roles\n    public void update(Account a) { ... }\n\n    @RolesAllowed(\"ADMIN\")              // single role\n    public void delete(Long id) { ... }\n\n    @DenyAll                            // no one can call\n    public void internalOnly() { ... }\n\n    @RunAs(\"SYSTEM\")                    // elevates identity for downstream\n    public void spawnAudit() { ... }\n}"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Programmatic checks","text":"Programmatic checks"},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"@Resource SessionContext ctx;\n...\nif (ctx.isCallerInRole(\"ADMIN\")) { ... }\nPrincipal caller = ctx.getCallerPrincipal();"}]},{"id":"4911-topic-ejb-transactions-acid-6-attributes","title":"EJB Transactions (ACID + 6 Attributes)","pillar":"tech","priority":"high","chapter":"Ch 17","tags":["ejb","transactions","tech"],"blocks":[{"kind":"h3","html":"ACID properties (Quiz 4 hit each separately)","text":"ACID properties (Quiz 4 hit each separately)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAtomicity\u003c/strong\u003e — all-or-nothing (Q8)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eConsistency\u003c/strong\u003e — integrity of data store (Q15)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIsolation\u003c/strong\u003e — no interference (Q10)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDurability\u003c/strong\u003e — persist after crash\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **Atomicity** — all-or-nothing (Q8)\n-   **Consistency** — integrity of data store (Q15)\n-   **Isolation** — no interference (Q10)\n-   **Durability** — persist after crash"},{"kind":"h3","html":"6 Transaction Attributes — the table","text":"6 Transaction Attributes — the table"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eAttribute\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eCaller HAS TX\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eCaller NO TX\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eREQUIRED\u003c/strong\u003e (default)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eJoin caller&#39;s TX\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eContainer creates new TX\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eREQUIRES_NEW\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSuspend caller, create NEW TX\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCreate new TX\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSUPPORTS\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eJoin caller&#39;s TX\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRun without TX\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eNOT_SUPPORTED\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSuspend caller, run without TX\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRun without TX\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMANDATORY\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eJoin caller&#39;s TX\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThrows EJBTransactionRequiredException\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eNEVER\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThrows EJBException\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eRun without TX\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Quiz 4 transactions — memorize","text":"Quiz 4 transactions — memorize"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eQ4: &quot;Does NOT propagate, runs WITHOUT TX&quot; = \u003cstrong\u003eNotSupported\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eQ5: &quot;Propagates if exists, else creates new&quot; = \u003cstrong\u003eRequired\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eQ13: &quot;Does NOT propagate, runs with NEW TX&quot; = \u003cstrong\u003eRequiresNew\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   Q4: \"Does NOT propagate, runs WITHOUT TX\" = **NotSupported**\n-   Q5: \"Propagates if exists, else creates new\" = **Required**\n-   Q13: \"Does NOT propagate, runs with NEW TX\" = **RequiresNew**"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Rollback behavior","text":"Rollback behavior"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSystem exception\u003c/strong\u003e (RuntimeException, EJBException) → auto-rollback + logged + wrapped in EJBException\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eApplication exception\u003c/strong\u003e (checked) → \u003cstrong\u003eNO auto-rollback\u003c/strong\u003e unless declared \u003ccode\u003e@ApplicationException(rollback=true)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eProgrammatic: \u003ccode\u003esessionContext.setRollbackOnly()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **System exception** (RuntimeException, EJBException) → auto-rollback + logged + wrapped in EJBException\n-   **Application exception** (checked) → **NO auto-rollback** unless declared `@ApplicationException(rollback=true)`\n-   Programmatic: `sessionContext.setRollbackOnly()`"},{"kind":"h3","html":"CMT vs BMT","text":"CMT vs BMT"},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"// Container-managed (default)\n@Stateless\n@TransactionManagement(TransactionManagementType.CONTAINER)\npublic class OrderService {\n    @TransactionAttribute(TransactionAttributeType.REQUIRES_NEW)\n    public void audit(Event e) { ... }\n}\n\n// Bean-managed\n@Stateless\n@TransactionManagement(TransactionManagementType.BEAN)\npublic class ManualTxBean {\n    @Resource UserTransaction utx;\n    public void work() {\n        utx.begin();\n        try { ... ; utx.commit(); }\n        catch (Exception e) { utx.rollback(); }\n    }\n}"}]},{"id":"4911-topic-entity-callbacks-listeners","title":"Entity Callbacks & Listeners","pillar":"tech","priority":"med","chapter":"Ch 14","tags":["jpa","callbacks","tech"],"blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Hooks for entity lifecycle events.","text":"Hooks for entity lifecycle events."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Mechanism — why callbacks fire and why they are restricted","text":"Mechanism — why callbacks fire and why they are restricted"},{"kind":"p","html":"The persistence provider runs callbacks as part of its own flush/load cycle. When you call \u003ccode\u003eem.persist(o)\u003c/code\u003e, the provider schedules an INSERT for the next flush. Just before issuing the SQL, it invokes every \u003ccode\u003e@PrePersist\u003c/code\u003e method on the entity (and on any \u003ccode\u003e@EntityListeners\u003c/code\u003e). Just after the SQL returns and the generated id is populated, it invokes \u003ccode\u003e@PostPersist\u003c/code\u003e. Same pattern for update, remove, and load.","text":"The persistence provider runs callbacks as part of its own flush/load cycle. When you call `em.persist(o)`, the provider schedules an INSERT for the next flush. Just before issuing the SQL, it invokes every `@PrePersist` method on the entity (and on any `@EntityListeners`). Just after the SQL returns and the generated id is populated, it invokes `@PostPersist`. Same pattern for update, remove, and load."},{"kind":"p","html":"Because the callback runs \u003cem\u003einside\u003c/em\u003e the provider&#39;s flush, it must not re-enter the EntityManager. If \u003ccode\u003e@PrePersist\u003c/code\u003e called \u003ccode\u003eem.persist(other)\u003c/code\u003e or \u003ccode\u003eem.createQuery(...)\u003c/code\u003e, the provider would recursively flush while already flushing — undefined behavior in the JPA spec. That is the mechanism behind the restriction: no EM access, no relationship navigation that triggers a lazy load. Safe work is confined to in-memory fields on the entity itself (\u003ccode\u003ethis.createdAt = new Date()\u003c/code\u003e, validation, derived fields).","text":"Because the callback runs *inside* the provider's flush, it must not re-enter the EntityManager. If `@PrePersist` called `em.persist(other)` or `em.createQuery(...)`, the provider would recursively flush while already flushing — undefined behavior in the JPA spec. That is the mechanism behind the restriction: no EM access, no relationship navigation that triggers a lazy load. Safe work is confined to in-memory fields on the entity itself (`this.createdAt = new Date()`, validation, derived fields)."},{"kind":"p","html":"This connects to prior knowledge: the same re-entrancy reason is why you avoid business-method callbacks across beans inside a single transaction flush.","text":"This connects to prior knowledge: the same re-entrancy reason is why you avoid business-method callbacks across beans inside a single transaction flush."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eCallback\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eWhen\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e@PrePersist\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBefore INSERT (on persist())\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e@PostPersist\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAfter INSERT (inside same TX)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e@PreUpdate\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBefore UPDATE\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e@PostUpdate\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAfter UPDATE\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e@PreRemove\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBefore DELETE\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e@PostRemove\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAfter DELETE\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e@PostLoad\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAfter SELECT loads entity into PC\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Rules for callback methods on entity","text":"Rules for callback methods on entity"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eNo parameters; void return; any visibility\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eMust NOT invoke EntityManager or access other entities\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   No parameters; void return; any visibility\n-   Must NOT invoke EntityManager or access other entities"},{"kind":"h3","html":"External listener","text":"External listener"},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"@Entity\n@EntityListeners(AuditListener.class)\npublic class Order { ... }\n\npublic class AuditListener {\n    @PrePersist\n    public void onInsert(Object entity) {   // takes entity as parameter\n        System.out.println(\"Inserting: \" + entity);\n    }\n}"}]},{"id":"4911-topic-entity-inheritance-3-strategies","title":"Entity Inheritance — 3 Strategies","pillar":"tech","priority":"med","chapter":"Ch 12","tags":["jpa","inheritance","tech"],"blocks":[{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eStrategy\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eDB layout\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePros\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eCons\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSINGLE_TABLE\u003c/strong\u003e (default)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOne table, discriminator column\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eFast (no joins), simple\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNullable subclass cols; violates normalization\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eJOINED\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eTable per class; FK joins subclass↔parent\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNormalized; NOT NULL subclass fields\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSlower (joins); schema changes harder\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTABLE_PER_CLASS\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eFull table per concrete class (parent fields duplicated)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo joins for single-type queries\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePolymorphic queries use UNION; duplicated schema\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"// SINGLE_TABLE (default + discriminator)\n@Entity\n@Inheritance(strategy = InheritanceType.SINGLE_TABLE)\n@DiscriminatorColumn(name = \"DTYPE\", discriminatorType = DiscriminatorType.STRING)\npublic class Shape { @Id Long id; ... }\n\n@Entity\n@DiscriminatorValue(\"CIRCLE\")\npublic class Circle extends Shape { private double radius; }"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@MappedSuperclass\u003c/code\u003e — share mapping without being an entity (abstract base).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eQuiz 3 Q4: strategy specified by \u003ccode\u003e@Inheritance\u003c/code\u003e (NOT @InheritanceStrategy/@InheritanceType — those are fakes).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   `@MappedSuperclass` — share mapping without being an entity (abstract base).\n-   Quiz 3 Q4: strategy specified by `@Inheritance` (NOT @InheritanceStrategy/@InheritanceType — those are fakes).\n"}]},{"id":"4911-topic-entity-relationships-all-7-types-high-priority","title":"Entity Relationships — All 7 Types (HIGH PRIORITY)","pillar":"tech","priority":"high","chapter":"Ch 11","tags":["jpa","relationships","tech"],"blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"&quot;Technically difficult. He CAN ask hard questions here.&quot; — Bruce","text":"\"Technically difficult. He CAN ask hard questions here.\" — Bruce"},{"kind":"h3","html":"The seven flavors","text":"The seven flavors"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003e#\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eRelationship\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eDirection\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eOwning side\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eInverse side\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e1:1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUni\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e@OneToOne + @JoinColumn\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e2\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e1:1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBi\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e@OneToOne + @JoinColumn\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e@OneToOne(mappedBy=&quot;...&quot;)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e3\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e1:N\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUni (from one)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e@OneToMany + @JoinColumn / @JoinTable\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e4\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eN:1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUni (from many)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e@ManyToOne + @JoinColumn\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e5\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e1:N / N:1\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBi\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMany side\u003c/strong\u003e: @ManyToOne + @JoinColumn\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOne side: @OneToMany(mappedBy=&quot;...&quot;)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e6\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eM:N\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUni\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e@ManyToMany + @JoinTable\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e7\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eM:N\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBi\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eEither side: @ManyToMany + @JoinTable\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOther: @ManyToMany(mappedBy=&quot;...&quot;)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Owning side rule","text":"Owning side rule"},{"kind":"p","html":"The side with the \u003cstrong\u003e@JoinColumn (or @JoinTable)\u003c/strong\u003e is the owner — holds the FK. The inverse side uses \u003ccode\u003emappedBy=&quot;ownerFieldName&quot;\u003c/code\u003e.","text":"The side with the **@JoinColumn (or @JoinTable)** is the owner — holds the FK. The inverse side uses `mappedBy=\"ownerFieldName\"`."},{"kind":"p","html":"In 1:N bidirectional, the \u003cstrong\u003eMANY side always owns\u003c/strong\u003e (holds the FK in its row).","text":"In 1:N bidirectional, the **MANY side always owns** (holds the FK in its row)."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Cascade + Fetch","text":"Cascade + Fetch"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCascadeType\u003c/strong\u003e: ALL, PERSIST, MERGE, REMOVE, REFRESH, DETACH. Default = none.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFetchType\u003c/strong\u003e: EAGER default for *ToOne, LAZY default for *ToMany.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eorphanRemoval=true\u003c/strong\u003e on @OneToMany: orphaned children deleted from DB, not just unlinked.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **CascadeType**: ALL, PERSIST, MERGE, REMOVE, REFRESH, DETACH. Default = none.\n-   **FetchType**: EAGER default for \\*ToOne, LAZY default for \\*ToMany.\n-   **orphanRemoval=true** on @OneToMany: orphaned children deleted from DB, not just unlinked."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Bidirectional 1:N example (the code annotation pattern)","text":"Bidirectional 1:N example (the code annotation pattern)"},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"// ONE side (inverse)\n@Entity\npublic class Department {\n    @Id private Long id;\n    @OneToMany(mappedBy = \"department\", cascade = CascadeType.ALL, orphanRemoval = true)\n    private List\u003cEmployee\u003e employees = new ArrayList\u003c\u003e();\n}\n\n// MANY side (owning — holds FK)\n@Entity\npublic class Employee {\n    @Id private Long id;\n    @ManyToOne\n    @JoinColumn(name = \"DEPT_ID\")    // FK column\n    private Department department;\n}"}]},{"id":"4911-topic-entitymanager-persistence-context","title":"EntityManager & Persistence Context","pillar":"tech","priority":"high","chapter":"Ch 9","tags":["jpa","tech"],"blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"EntityManager is the gateway between Java entities and the database. It maintains a Persistence Context (PC) — the set of managed entities within a transaction.","text":"EntityManager is the gateway between Java entities and the database. It maintains a Persistence Context (PC) — the set of managed entities within a transaction."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Core API methods","text":"Core API methods"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMethod\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eEffect\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eInput state\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003epersist(e)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNew → Managed; schedules INSERT\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNew (or Managed; noop). Throws on Detached.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003emerge(e)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDetached → Managed COPY (returns copy)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAny. Does NOT modify passed-in instance.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eremove(e)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eManaged → Removed; schedules DELETE\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eManaged only. Throws on Detached.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003efind(cls, pk)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSELECT; null if missing\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReturns Managed\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003egetReference(cls, pk)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eProxy; no DB hit until accessed\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReturns Managed proxy\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003erefresh(e)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eReload from DB, overwrite memory\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eManaged only\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eflush()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePush pending SQL to DB; TX stays open\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAny managed state\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003edetach(e)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eManaged → Detached (JPA 2.0+)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003eclear()\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDetach ALL; unsaved changes lost\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003econtains(e)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eTrue if entity is managed\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Persistence context scope","text":"Persistence context scope"},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"// Transaction-scoped (default): lives for one TX\n@PersistenceContext\nprivate EntityManager em;\n\n// Extended: spans multiple TXs — SFSB only\n@PersistenceContext(type = PersistenceContextType.EXTENDED)\nprivate EntityManager em;"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Key rules","text":"Key rules"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTwo find()s with same PK in same PC return the \u003cstrong\u003esame Java instance\u003c/strong\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eFlush happens automatically: before queries; at TX commit; on explicit flush().\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eremove() on detached → IllegalArgumentException. merge() first, THEN remove.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eLazy-loaded fields throw LazyInitializationException if accessed on detached entity.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   Two find()s with same PK in same PC return the **same Java instance**.\n-   Flush happens automatically: before queries; at TX commit; on explicit flush().\n-   remove() on detached → IllegalArgumentException. merge() first, THEN remove.\n-   Lazy-loaded fields throw LazyInitializationException if accessed on detached entity.\n"}]},{"id":"4911-topic-jndi-enc-injection","title":"JNDI, ENC & Injection","pillar":"tech","priority":"med","chapter":"Ch 16","tags":["jndi","tech"],"blocks":[{"kind":"h3","html":"Mechanism — how injection and JNDI connect","text":"Mechanism — how injection and JNDI connect"},{"kind":"p","html":"Every container-managed resource — another bean, a DataSource, an EntityManager — is ultimately bound into the server&#39;s JNDI tree at deploy time. Injection is convenience syntax: \u003ccode\u003e@EJB private PaymentService payment;\u003c/code\u003e tells the container &quot;at bean-creation time, look up PaymentService in JNDI and assign it to this field.&quot; The same lookup is available programmatically through \u003ccode\u003eInitialContext.lookup(name)\u003c/code\u003e; injection just hides the string.","text":"Every container-managed resource — another bean, a DataSource, an EntityManager — is ultimately bound into the server's JNDI tree at deploy time. Injection is convenience syntax: `@EJB private PaymentService payment;` tells the container \"at bean-creation time, look up PaymentService in JNDI and assign it to this field.\" The same lookup is available programmatically through `InitialContext.lookup(name)`; injection just hides the string."},{"kind":"p","html":"The portable JNDI name scopes define \u003cem\u003ewho can see what\u003c/em\u003e. Each scope answers a different reach:","text":"The portable JNDI name scopes define *who can see what*. Each scope answers a different reach:"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ejava:global/[app]/[module]/BeanName\u003c/code\u003e — visible across the whole application server. Use when one app must look up a bean in a different app.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ejava:app/[module]/BeanName\u003c/code\u003e — visible within one EAR. Use across modules of the same deployed application.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ejava:module/BeanName\u003c/code\u003e — visible within a single EJB jar or WAR. Use for beans in the same module.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ejava:comp/env/...\u003c/code\u003e — the Environment Naming Context, a bean&#39;s \u003cstrong\u003eprivate\u003c/strong\u003e view of its resources. Each component gets its own \u003ccode\u003ecomp\u003c/code\u003e space; this is where \u003ccode\u003e@Resource(name=&quot;...&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e entries land.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   `java:global/[app]/[module]/BeanName` — visible across the whole application server. Use when one app must look up a bean in a different app.\n-   `java:app/[module]/BeanName` — visible within one EAR. Use across modules of the same deployed application.\n-   `java:module/BeanName` — visible within a single EJB jar or WAR. Use for beans in the same module.\n-   `java:comp/env/...` — the Environment Naming Context, a bean's **private** view of its resources. Each component gets its own `comp` space; this is where `@Resource(name=\"...\")` entries land."},{"kind":"p","html":"Pick the narrowest scope that works: \u003ccode\u003ejava:module\u003c/code\u003e for intra-module lookups, \u003ccode\u003ejava:app\u003c/code\u003e across modules in the same EAR, \u003ccode\u003ejava:global\u003c/code\u003e only when crossing applications. Narrower scope = fewer naming collisions + clearer deployment boundaries.","text":"Pick the narrowest scope that works: `java:module` for intra-module lookups, `java:app` across modules in the same EAR, `java:global` only when crossing applications. Narrower scope = fewer naming collisions + clearer deployment boundaries."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e@EJB\u003c/strong\u003e — inject another session bean\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e@Resource\u003c/strong\u003e — inject DataSource, Queue, ConnectionFactory, env-entry\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e@PersistenceContext\u003c/strong\u003e — inject container-managed EntityManager\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e@PersistenceUnit\u003c/strong\u003e — inject EntityManagerFactory (application-managed)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **@EJB** — inject another session bean\n-   **@Resource** — inject DataSource, Queue, ConnectionFactory, env-entry\n-   **@PersistenceContext** — inject container-managed EntityManager\n-   **@PersistenceUnit** — inject EntityManagerFactory (application-managed)"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Portable global JNDI names (Java EE 6+)","text":"Portable global JNDI names (Java EE 6+)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ejava:global/[app]/[module]/BeanName\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ejava:app/[module]/BeanName\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ejava:module/BeanName\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003ejava:comp/env/...\u003c/code\u003e — Environment Naming Context (local refs)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   `java:global/[app]/[module]/BeanName`\n-   `java:app/[module]/BeanName`\n-   `java:module/BeanName`\n-   `java:comp/env/...` — Environment Naming Context (local refs)"},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"@Stateless\npublic class OrderService {\n    @EJB private PaymentService payment;\n    @Resource(lookup = \"java:/jms/MyQueue\") private Queue auditQueue;\n    @Resource private SessionContext ctx;\n    @PersistenceContext private EntityManager em;\n}"}]},{"id":"4911-topic-jpql-queries-high-priority","title":"JPQL — Queries (HIGH PRIORITY)","pillar":"tech","priority":"high","chapter":"Ch 13","tags":["jpql","tech"],"blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"&quot;Students struggle here. Fair game on final.&quot; — Bruce. Practice WRITING queries, not just recognizing.","text":"\"Students struggle here. Fair game on final.\" — Bruce. Practice WRITING queries, not just recognizing."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Syntax essentials (JPQL)","text":"Syntax essentials (JPQL)"},{"kind":"code","lang":"sql","code":"-- Basic\nSELECT e FROM Employee e WHERE e.salary \u003e :min;\n\n-- Path navigation\nSELECT e FROM Employee e WHERE e.department.name = :deptName;\n\n-- INNER JOIN (only employees with a dept)\nSELECT e FROM Employee e JOIN e.department d WHERE d.name = :n;\n\n-- LEFT JOIN (include those without)\nSELECT e FROM Employee e LEFT JOIN e.department d;\n\n-- FETCH JOIN (avoid N+1)\nSELECT b FROM Book b JOIN FETCH b.author;\n\n-- Aggregates\nSELECT COUNT(e), AVG(e.salary), MAX(e.salary) FROM Employee e;\n\n-- GROUP BY / HAVING\nSELECT e.department, COUNT(e) FROM Employee e\nGROUP BY e.department HAVING COUNT(e) \u003e 10;\n\n-- Constructor expression (DTO)\nSELECT new com.x.EmpDto(e.id, e.name) FROM Employee e;\n\n-- Subquery\nSELECT e FROM Employee e WHERE e.salary \u003e\n    (SELECT AVG(e2.salary) FROM Employee e2);\n\n-- IN operator (treat collection as source)\nSELECT p FROM Employee e, IN(e.phones) p;"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Named params + pagination (Java side)","text":"Named params + pagination (Java side)"},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"q.setParameter(\"min\", 50000);  // :min\nq.setParameter(1, 50000);       // ?1\n\nq.setFirstResult(20).setMaxResults(10).getResultList();\n\nem.createQuery(\"UPDATE Employee e SET e.salary = e.salary * 1.1\")\n  .executeUpdate();"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Query API methods","text":"Query API methods"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eem.createQuery(jpql, Type.class)\u003c/code\u003e → \u003cstrong\u003eTypedQuery\u003cT\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eem.createNamedQuery(&quot;name&quot;, Type.class)\u003c/code\u003e → uses @NamedQuery\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eem.createNativeQuery(sql)\u003c/code\u003e → raw SQL\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eq.getResultList()\u003c/code\u003e — List (empty if 0)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eq.getSingleResult()\u003c/code\u003e — expect exactly 1 (NoResult/NonUniqueResult exceptions)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003eq.executeUpdate()\u003c/code\u003e — INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE; returns count\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   `em.createQuery(jpql, Type.class)` → **TypedQuery\u003cT\u003e**\n-   `em.createNamedQuery(\"name\", Type.class)` → uses @NamedQuery\n-   `em.createNativeQuery(sql)` → raw SQL\n-   `q.getResultList()` — List (empty if 0)\n-   `q.getSingleResult()` — expect exactly 1 (NoResult/NonUniqueResult exceptions)\n-   `q.executeUpdate()` — INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE; returns count\n"}]},{"id":"4911-topic-mapping-persistent-objects-annotations","title":"Mapping Persistent Objects (Annotations)","pillar":"tech","priority":"high","chapter":"Ch 10","tags":["jpa","tech"],"blocks":[{"kind":"h3","html":"Required on every entity","text":"Required on every entity"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@Entity\u003c/code\u003e — marks class\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@Id\u003c/code\u003e — primary key field or property\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePublic/protected no-arg constructor\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eClass should be top-level, non-final\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   `@Entity` — marks class\n-   `@Id` — primary key field or property\n-   Public/protected no-arg constructor\n-   Class should be top-level, non-final"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Common annotations","text":"Common annotations"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eAnnotation\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePurpose\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eDefault\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@Table(name=&quot;X&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOverride table name\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eclass name\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@Column(name=&quot;X&quot;, nullable=true, length=255)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOverride column name / constraints\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eproperty name, nullable, 255\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@Id\u003c/code\u003e + \u003ccode\u003e@GeneratedValue\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePrimary key + auto-generation\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAUTO\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@Temporal(TemporalType.DATE)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ejava.util.Date → DATE/TIME/TIMESTAMP\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003erequired for Date\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@Enumerated(EnumType.STRING)\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eEnum → string (vs ORDINAL = int)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eORDINAL\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@Transient\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNOT persisted\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@Lob\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBLOB (byte[]) / CLOB (String)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@Version\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOptimistic locking — auto-increment on UPDATE\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@Embedded / @Embeddable\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eValue object (same table)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e—\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Composite keys — two ways (high-priority flag)","text":"Composite keys — two ways (high-priority flag)"},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"// Option 1: @IdClass — external PK class, multiple @Id fields\npublic class EmployeePK implements Serializable {\n    public Long empId;\n    public String dept;\n    // equals, hashCode, default ctor required\n}\n\n@Entity @IdClass(EmployeePK.class)\npublic class Employee {\n    @Id @Column(name=\"EMP_ID\")   private Long empId;\n    @Id @Column(name=\"DEPT\")     private String dept;\n}\n\n// Option 2: @EmbeddedId — @Embeddable PK class, single field\n@Embeddable\npublic class ProjectKey implements Serializable {\n    private Long projectId;\n    private int version;\n    // equals, hashCode, default ctor required\n}\n\n@Entity\npublic class Project {\n    @EmbeddedId private ProjectKey id;\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eKey: you need to recognize which is which by name\u003c/strong\u003e, not memorize full syntax. @EmbeddedId is &quot;more OOP&quot; — one field encapsulates PK.","text":"**Key: you need to recognize which is which by name**, not memorize full syntax. @EmbeddedId is \"more OOP\" — one field encapsulates PK."}]},{"id":"4911-topic-rup-four-phases-milestones","title":"RUP Four Phases & Milestones","pillar":"process","priority":"high","chapter":"","tags":["process"],"blocks":[{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePhase\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eMilestone\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eFocus\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eEffort\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eInception\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eLCO (Life-Cycle Objectives)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eVision, business case, scope, feasibility\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~10%\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eElaboration\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eLCA (Life-Cycle Architecture)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eArchitecture baselined, ~80% requirements, major risks mitigated\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~30%\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eConstruction\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eIOC (Initial Operating Capability)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBuild, integrate, test\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~50%\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTransition\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePR (Product Release)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDeploy, UAT, training, handoff\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e~10%\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Iteration = mini-waterfall","text":"Iteration = mini-waterfall"},{"kind":"p","html":"Each iteration includes all workflows (req → analysis → design → impl → test). Number of iterations varies per phase: Inception 1-2, Elaboration 2-3, Construction 3-5, Transition 1-2.","text":"Each iteration includes all workflows (req → analysis → design → impl → test). Number of iterations varies per phase: Inception 1-2, Elaboration 2-3, Construction 3-5, Transition 1-2."},{"kind":"h3","html":"&quot;Hump chart&quot; — workflow distribution","text":"\"Hump chart\" — workflow distribution"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRequirements hump: peaks in Inception/Elaboration\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAnalysis &amp; Design hump: peaks in Elaboration\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eImplementation hump: peaks in Construction\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTest hump: peaks in Construction, continues through Transition\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   Requirements hump: peaks in Inception/Elaboration\n-   Analysis & Design hump: peaks in Elaboration\n-   Implementation hump: peaks in Construction\n-   Test hump: peaks in Construction, continues through Transition\n"}]},{"id":"4911-topic-six-software-best-practices","title":"Six Software Best Practices","pillar":"process","priority":"high","chapter":"","tags":["process"],"blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDevelop Iteratively\u003c/strong\u003e — mitigates risk via continuous feedback; avoids late surprises\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eManage Requirements\u003c/strong\u003e — dynamic + traceable; every requirement → design → test\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUse Component-Based Architectures\u003c/strong\u003e — addresses brittle architecture, enables reuse\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eModel Visually (UML)\u003c/strong\u003e — use-case, class, sequence, deployment diagrams; reduces ambiguity\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eVerify Quality\u003c/strong\u003e — continuous testing; unit/integration/system/acceptance\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eControl Changes\u003c/strong\u003e — CM + version control; prevent chaos from ad-hoc edits\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e","text":"1.  **Develop Iteratively** — mitigates risk via continuous feedback; avoids late surprises\n2.  **Manage Requirements** — dynamic + traceable; every requirement → design → test\n3.  **Use Component-Based Architectures** — addresses brittle architecture, enables reuse\n4.  **Model Visually (UML)** — use-case, class, sequence, deployment diagrams; reduces ambiguity\n5.  **Verify Quality** — continuous testing; unit/integration/system/acceptance\n6.  **Control Changes** — CM + version control; prevent chaos from ad-hoc edits"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Root-cause mapping","text":"Root-cause mapping"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eRoot Cause\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eAddressed By\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eInsufficient requirements\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eManage Requirements\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eAmbiguous communication\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eModel Visually; Manage Requirements\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eBrittle architectures\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eComponent-Based Architectures\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOverwhelming complexity\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eComponent-Based; Model Visually\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUndetected inconsistencies\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eModel Visually; Verify Quality\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePoor testing\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eVerify Quality\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eWaterfall delays\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDevelop Iteratively\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eUncontrolled change\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eControl Changes\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Waterfall vs Iterative risk curve","text":"Waterfall vs Iterative risk curve"},{"kind":"p","html":"Waterfall: high risk sustained until late → problems surface near end → expensive fix. Iterative: risk reduced continuously → problems surface early → course-correct cheaply.","text":"Waterfall: high risk sustained until late → problems surface near end → expensive fix. Iterative: risk reduced continuously → problems surface early → course-correct cheaply."}]},{"id":"4911-topic-testing","title":"Testing","pillar":"process","priority":"med","chapter":"","tags":["testing","process"],"blocks":[{"kind":"h3","html":"Test levels","text":"Test levels"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUnit\u003c/strong\u003e — individual components in isolation (white-box)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIntegration\u003c/strong\u003e — component interactions\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSystem\u003c/strong\u003e — end-to-end, full behavior (black-box)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAcceptance\u003c/strong\u003e — user validation against requirements (black-box — Quiz 4 Q9)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **Unit** — individual components in isolation (white-box)\n-   **Integration** — component interactions\n-   **System** — end-to-end, full behavior (black-box)\n-   **Acceptance** — user validation against requirements (black-box — Quiz 4 Q9)"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Test types (Quiz 4 tested)","text":"Test types (Quiz 4 tested)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePerformance\u003c/strong\u003e — response time + processing time (Quiz 4 Q6)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLoad\u003c/strong\u003e — concurrent users / throughput\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eVolume\u003c/strong\u003e — large data\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eConfiguration\u003c/strong\u003e — different environments / hardware / OS\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **Performance** — response time + processing time (Quiz 4 Q6)\n-   **Load** — concurrent users / throughput\n-   **Volume** — large data\n-   **Configuration** — different environments / hardware / OS"},{"kind":"h3","html":"White-box vs Black-box","text":"White-box vs Black-box"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWhite-box: knows internal code (unit tests)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eBlack-box: tests I/O behavior only (system, acceptance)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   White-box: knows internal code (unit tests)\n-   Black-box: tests I/O behavior only (system, acceptance)\n"}]},{"id":"4911-topic-three-session-bean-types-high-priority","title":"Three Session Bean Types (HIGH PRIORITY)","pillar":"tech","priority":"high","chapter":"Ch 5-7","tags":["session-beans","tech"],"blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Three distinct session bean flavors, each with different statefulness + concurrency semantics.","text":"Three distinct session bean flavors, each with different statefulness + concurrency semantics."},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eType\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eAnnotation\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eState\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eLifecycle\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eConcurrency\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eStateless\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@Stateless\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo client state\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eDoesNotExist → PooledMethodReady\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eContainer serializes; pooled instances\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eStateful\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@Stateful\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003ePer-client conversational\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e+ Passive (via @PrePassivate / @PostActivate)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eOne thread per instance per client\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSingleton\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003ccode\u003e@Singleton\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eApp-wide shared\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSame as SLSB (no passive)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e@Lock(READ/WRITE)\u003c/strong\u003e or BEAN-managed\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Stateful lifecycle callbacks","text":"Stateful lifecycle callbacks"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e@PostConstruct\u003c/strong\u003e — after DI, before any business method\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e@PrePassivate\u003c/strong\u003e — before container serializes to disk (inactive client)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e@PostActivate\u003c/strong\u003e — after deserialization when client returns\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e@PreDestroy\u003c/strong\u003e — before removal\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e@Remove\u003c/strong\u003e — marks a method whose return ends the conversation\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **@PostConstruct** — after DI, before any business method\n-   **@PrePassivate** — before container serializes to disk (inactive client)\n-   **@PostActivate** — after deserialization when client returns\n-   **@PreDestroy** — before removal\n-   **@Remove** — marks a method whose return ends the conversation"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Singleton concurrency (high-priority flag)","text":"Singleton concurrency (high-priority flag)"},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"@Singleton\n@Startup\n@ConcurrencyManagement(ConcurrencyManagementType.CONTAINER)\n@Lock(LockType.READ)  // class-level default\npublic class Cache {\n    @Lock(LockType.WRITE)                  // exclusive\n    @AccessTimeout(value=5, unit=SECONDS)  // wait cap\n    public void refresh() { ... }\n\n    public Data get() { ... }              // READ: concurrent\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eREAD\u003c/strong\u003e = many readers, no writers concurrently. \u003cstrong\u003eWRITE\u003c/strong\u003e = exclusive (blocks all reads + writes). @AccessTimeout throws ConcurrentAccessTimeoutException if wait exceeded.","text":"**READ** = many readers, no writers concurrently. **WRITE** = exclusive (blocks all reads + writes). @AccessTimeout throws ConcurrentAccessTimeoutException if wait exceeded."},{"kind":"h3","html":"@DependsOn","text":"@DependsOn"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003ccode\u003e@DependsOn(&quot;ConfigSingleton&quot;)\u003c/code\u003e ensures another singleton&#39;s @PostConstruct runs first. Critical for init order.","text":"`@DependsOn(\"ConfigSingleton\")` ensures another singleton's @PostConstruct runs first. Critical for init order."}]},{"id":"4911-topic-understanding-preferences-mbti-quiz-4-heavy","title":"Understanding Preferences (MBTI) — Quiz 4 heavy","pillar":"process","priority":"high","chapter":"","tags":["mbti","process"],"blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Quiz 4 was \u003cstrong\u003esaturated with MBTI questions\u003c/strong\u003e — high probability on final.","text":"Quiz 4 was **saturated with MBTI questions** — high probability on final."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Four dimensions","text":"Four dimensions"},{"kind":"table","html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eDimension\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003ePoles\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eTraits\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eE / I (attitude to world)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eExtraversion / Introversion\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eE: face-to-face, think out loud. I: reflective, written comm.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eS / N (perception)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSensing / Intuition\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eS: details, facts, practical. N: patterns, new complex problems.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eT / F (judging function)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eThinking / Feeling\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eT: analytical, objective. F: fair, value-driven.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eJ / P (outer-world lifestyle)\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eJudging / Perceiving\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eJ: decide quickly, schedules. P: enjoy surprises, open.\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Functions vs attitudes","text":"Functions vs attitudes"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePerceiving functions\u003c/strong\u003e: Sensing + Intuition (gather info)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eJudging functions\u003c/strong\u003e: Thinking + Feeling (decide)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAttitudes\u003c/strong\u003e: Extraversion/Introversion (toward world); Judging/Perceiving (toward outer lifestyle)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **Perceiving functions**: Sensing + Intuition (gather info)\n-   **Judging functions**: Thinking + Feeling (decide)\n-   **Attitudes**: Extraversion/Introversion (toward world); Judging/Perceiving (toward outer lifestyle)"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Quiz 4 memorize table","text":"Quiz 4 memorize table"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eQ1: Perceiving → \u003cstrong\u003eenjoy surprises\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eQ2: Attitude toward world = \u003cstrong\u003eIntroversion\u003c/strong\u003e (or Extraversion)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eQ3: Feeling → \u003cstrong\u003eare fair\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eQ7: Judging → \u003cstrong\u003edecide quickly\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eQ11: Intuition → \u003cstrong\u003elike solving new complex problems\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eQ12: Judging function = \u003cstrong\u003eThinking\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eQ14: Perceiving function = \u003cstrong\u003eSensing\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eQ16: Extraversion → \u003cstrong\u003eprefer face-to-face communication\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   Q1: Perceiving → **enjoy surprises**\n-   Q2: Attitude toward world = **Introversion** (or Extraversion)\n-   Q3: Feeling → **are fair**\n-   Q7: Judging → **decide quickly**\n-   Q11: Intuition → **like solving new complex problems**\n-   Q12: Judging function = **Thinking**\n-   Q14: Perceiving function = **Sensing**\n-   Q16: Extraversion → **prefer face-to-face communication**\n"}]},{"id":"4911-topic-use-case-driven-development","title":"Use-Case Driven Development","pillar":"process","priority":"high","chapter":"","tags":["use-cases","process"],"blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Use cases are the \u003cstrong\u003eprimary artifact\u003c/strong\u003e — they drive the entire process.","text":"Use cases are the **primary artifact** — they drive the entire process."},{"kind":"h3","html":"What UCs drive","text":"What UCs drive"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRequirements\u003c/strong\u003e — UCs capture functional requirements\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAnalysis\u003c/strong\u003e — each UC decomposed into analysis classes (BCE)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDesign\u003c/strong\u003e — design model refines analysis; use-case realizations in sequence diagrams\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eImplementation\u003c/strong\u003e — UCs → components; guides build order\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTest\u003c/strong\u003e — each UC → test cases (main flow + alternates)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIteration planning\u003c/strong\u003e — prioritized UCs picked per iteration\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **Requirements** — UCs capture functional requirements\n-   **Analysis** — each UC decomposed into analysis classes (BCE)\n-   **Design** — design model refines analysis; use-case realizations in sequence diagrams\n-   **Implementation** — UCs → components; guides build order\n-   **Test** — each UC → test cases (main flow + alternates)\n-   **Iteration planning** — prioritized UCs picked per iteration"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Use-case structure","text":"Use-case structure"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eActor\u003c/strong\u003e — external entity (user, system, hardware)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMain flow\u003c/strong\u003e — happy path to goal\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAlternate flows\u003c/strong\u003e — exceptions, variations\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePreconditions / postconditions\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExtension points\u003c/strong\u003e — for include/extend relationships\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **Actor** — external entity (user, system, hardware)\n-   **Main flow** — happy path to goal\n-   **Alternate flows** — exceptions, variations\n-   **Preconditions / postconditions**\n-   **Extension points** — for include/extend relationships"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Use-case realization","text":"Use-case realization"},{"kind":"p","html":"How a UC is implemented by objects. In \u003cstrong\u003eAnalysis\u003c/strong\u003e: class + collaboration diagrams of analysis classes. In \u003cstrong\u003eDesign\u003c/strong\u003e: sequence diagrams of design classes. Each UC has one realization per model.","text":"How a UC is implemented by objects. In **Analysis**: class + collaboration diagrams of analysis classes. In **Design**: sequence diagrams of design classes. Each UC has one realization per model."}]},{"id":"4911-topic-4-1-architecture-view-not-on-final","title":"4+1 Architecture View (NOT on final)","pillar":"process","priority":"low","chapter":"","tags":["architecture","process"],"blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cstrong\u003eBruce: appeared on midterm, NOT on final.\u003c/strong\u003e Keep light.","text":"**Bruce: appeared on midterm, NOT on final.** Keep light."},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLogical\u003c/strong\u003e — structure (classes, BCE)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eProcess\u003c/strong\u003e — concurrency, threading\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eImplementation\u003c/strong\u003e — code modules, components\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDeployment\u003c/strong\u003e — hardware, network\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUse-Case\u003c/strong\u003e — the &quot;+1&quot;, integrates the other four\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **Logical** — structure (classes, BCE)\n-   **Process** — concurrency, threading\n-   **Implementation** — code modules, components\n-   **Deployment** — hardware, network\n-   **Use-Case** — the \"+1\", integrates the other four"},{"kind":"p","html":"Baselined at end of Elaboration. Captured in Software Architecture Document (SAD).","text":"Baselined at end of Elaboration. Captured in Software Architecture Document (SAD)."}]},{"id":"4911-topic-classic-mistakes-disaster-recovery","title":"Classic Mistakes + Disaster Recovery","pillar":"process","priority":"low","chapter":"","tags":["process"],"blocks":[{"kind":"h3","html":"Four categories (Steve McConnell)","text":"Four categories (Steve McConnell)"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePeople\u003c/strong\u003e: heroics, motivation issues, insufficient training, friction\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eProcess\u003c/strong\u003e: optimistic schedules, no risk mgmt, shortchanged QA, silver-bullet thinking\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eProduct\u003c/strong\u003e: requirements gold-plating, feature creep, over-engineering\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTechnology\u003c/strong\u003e: silver-bullet syndrome, switching tools mid-project, inadequate legacy management\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **People**: heroics, motivation issues, insufficient training, friction\n-   **Process**: optimistic schedules, no risk mgmt, shortchanged QA, silver-bullet thinking\n-   **Product**: requirements gold-plating, feature creep, over-engineering\n-   **Technology**: silver-bullet syndrome, switching tools mid-project, inadequate legacy management"},{"kind":"h3","html":"Disaster Recovery (LOW priority)","text":"Disaster Recovery (LOW priority)"},{"kind":"p","html":"Backup + DR planning, business continuity, RTO (Recovery Time Objective), RPO (Recovery Point Objective). Off-site backups. DR tests.","text":"Backup + DR planning, business continuity, RTO (Recovery Time Objective), RPO (Recovery Point Objective). Off-site backups. DR tests."}]},{"id":"4911-topic-message-driven-beans-low-priority","title":"Message-Driven Beans (LOW priority)","pillar":"tech","priority":"low","chapter":"Ch 8","tags":["mdb","tech"],"blocks":[{"kind":"p","html":"Async JMS consumers. Bruce: &quot;low question count, skip if tight on time.&quot; Know the basics.","text":"Async JMS consumers. Bruce: \"low question count, skip if tight on time.\" Know the basics."},{"kind":"h3","html":"Two JMS models","text":"Two JMS models"},{"kind":"p","html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePoint-to-Point (Queue)\u003c/strong\u003e — one message, one consumer. Guaranteed delivery.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePublish-Subscribe (Topic)\u003c/strong\u003e — one message, many subscribers. Non-durable loses messages if offline.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","text":"-   **Point-to-Point (Queue)** — one message, one consumer. Guaranteed delivery.\n-   **Publish-Subscribe (Topic)** — one message, many subscribers. Non-durable loses messages if offline."},{"kind":"code","lang":"java","code":"@MessageDriven(activationConfig = {\n    @ActivationConfigProperty(propertyName=\"destinationType\",\n                              propertyValue=\"javax.jms.Queue\"),\n    @ActivationConfigProperty(propertyName=\"destination\",\n                              propertyValue=\"jms/OrderQueue\"),\n    @ActivationConfigProperty(propertyName=\"acknowledgeMode\",\n                              propertyValue=\"Auto-acknowledge\")\n})\npublic class OrderProcessorMDB implements MessageListener {\n    @Override\n    public void onMessage(Message m) {\n        TextMessage tm = (TextMessage) m;\n        // process\n    }\n}"},{"kind":"p","html":"Lifecycle = SLSB (DoesNotExist → Method-Ready Pool, no passivation). Container pools multiple instances for concurrency.","text":"Lifecycle = SLSB (DoesNotExist → Method-Ready Pool, no passivation). Container pools multiple instances for concurrency."}]}],"cheatSheet":{"title":"COMP 4911 — exam-eve cheat sheet","blocks":[{"heading":"Session beans — 3 types","body_md":"-   **@Stateless**: pooled, no client state, method-ready pool\n-   **@Stateful**: per-client state, @Remove ends, @PrePassivate / @PostActivate\n-   **@Singleton**: one instance, @Lock(READ/WRITE), @Startup, @DependsOn, @AccessTimeout\n\n**Lifecycle callbacks**: @PostConstruct, @PreDestroy (all). +@PrePassivate / @PostActivate (SFSB).","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e@Stateless\u003c/strong\u003e: pooled, no client state, method-ready pool\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e@Stateful\u003c/strong\u003e: per-client state, @Remove ends, @PrePassivate / @PostActivate\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e@Singleton\u003c/strong\u003e: one instance, @Lock(READ/WRITE), @Startup, @DependsOn, @AccessTimeout\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLifecycle callbacks\u003c/strong\u003e: @PostConstruct, @PreDestroy (all). +@PrePassivate / @PostActivate (SFSB).\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"EntityManager core","body_md":"-   **persist(e)**: New → Managed (INSERT queued)\n-   **merge(e)**: Detached → Managed COPY (return new ref)\n-   **remove(e)**: Managed → Removed\n-   **find / getReference**: SELECT or proxy\n-   **flush()**: push pending SQL; TX stays open\n-   **refresh / detach / clear / contains**\n\nPC: **Transaction-scoped** (default) or **Extended** (SFSB only).","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003epersist(e)\u003c/strong\u003e: New → Managed (INSERT queued)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003emerge(e)\u003c/strong\u003e: Detached → Managed COPY (return new ref)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eremove(e)\u003c/strong\u003e: Managed → Removed\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003efind / getReference\u003c/strong\u003e: SELECT or proxy\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eflush()\u003c/strong\u003e: push pending SQL; TX stays open\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003erefresh / detach / clear / contains\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003ePC: \u003cstrong\u003eTransaction-scoped\u003c/strong\u003e (default) or \u003cstrong\u003eExtended\u003c/strong\u003e (SFSB only).\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"JPA mapping","body_md":"-   @Entity (required), @Table (optional; default = class name)\n-   @Id + @GeneratedValue (AUTO/IDENTITY/SEQUENCE/TABLE)\n-   @Column(name=\"\", nullable=T/F, length=n, unique=T/F)\n-   @Temporal(DATE/TIME/TIMESTAMP) — for java.util.Date\n-   @Enumerated(STRING) — safer than ORDINAL\n-   @Transient — excluded from DB\n-   @Version — optimistic lock\n-   @Embeddable/@Embedded — value object, same table\n-   Composite PK: @IdClass OR @EmbeddedId","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e@Entity (required), @Table (optional; default = class name)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e@Id + @GeneratedValue (AUTO/IDENTITY/SEQUENCE/TABLE)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e@Column(name=&quot;&quot;, nullable=T/F, length=n, unique=T/F)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e@Temporal(DATE/TIME/TIMESTAMP) — for java.util.Date\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e@Enumerated(STRING) — safer than ORDINAL\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e@Transient — excluded from DB\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e@Version — optimistic lock\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e@Embeddable/@Embedded — value object, same table\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eComposite PK: @IdClass OR @EmbeddedId\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"7 Relationships","body_md":"-   1:1 uni → @OneToOne + @JoinColumn\n-   1:1 bi → inverse: @OneToOne(mappedBy=\"owner\")\n-   1:N uni → @OneToMany + @JoinColumn OR @JoinTable\n-   N:1 uni → @ManyToOne + @JoinColumn\n-   1:N bi → **MANY side owns** (@ManyToOne); ONE side: @OneToMany(mappedBy=\"…\")\n-   M:N uni → @ManyToMany + @JoinTable\n-   M:N bi → owner @JoinTable; inverse @ManyToMany(mappedBy=\"…\")\n\nCascade: ALL/PERSIST/MERGE/REMOVE/REFRESH/DETACH · default = none\n\nFetch: \\*ToOne = EAGER; \\*ToMany = LAZY","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e1:1 uni → @OneToOne + @JoinColumn\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e1:1 bi → inverse: @OneToOne(mappedBy=&quot;owner&quot;)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e1:N uni → @OneToMany + @JoinColumn OR @JoinTable\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eN:1 uni → @ManyToOne + @JoinColumn\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e1:N bi → \u003cstrong\u003eMANY side owns\u003c/strong\u003e (@ManyToOne); ONE side: @OneToMany(mappedBy=&quot;…&quot;)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eM:N uni → @ManyToMany + @JoinTable\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eM:N bi → owner @JoinTable; inverse @ManyToMany(mappedBy=&quot;…&quot;)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCascade: ALL/PERSIST/MERGE/REMOVE/REFRESH/DETACH · default = none\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eFetch: *ToOne = EAGER; *ToMany = LAZY\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"Inheritance — 3 strategies","body_md":"-   **SINGLE\\_TABLE** (default) — one table + @DiscriminatorColumn + @DiscriminatorValue\n-   **JOINED** — table per class, FK joins\n-   **TABLE\\_PER\\_CLASS** — full table per concrete subclass\n\nUse @Inheritance(strategy=…). @MappedSuperclass for abstract non-entity bases.","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSINGLE_TABLE\u003c/strong\u003e (default) — one table + @DiscriminatorColumn + @DiscriminatorValue\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eJOINED\u003c/strong\u003e — table per class, FK joins\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTABLE_PER_CLASS\u003c/strong\u003e — full table per concrete subclass\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eUse @Inheritance(strategy=…). @MappedSuperclass for abstract non-entity bases.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"JPQL skeleton","body_md":"```sql\nSELECT e FROM Employee e\nWHERE e.salary \u003e :min\nORDER BY e.name\n```\n\n-   JOIN / LEFT JOIN / **JOIN FETCH** (N+1 fix)\n-   COUNT, AVG, SUM, MIN, MAX\n-   GROUP BY ... HAVING\n-   SELECT new com.x.Dto(f1, f2) FROM …\n-   :named / ?positional params\n-   q.setFirstResult(n).setMaxResults(m)\n-   q.getResultList() / getSingleResult() / executeUpdate()","body_html":"\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-sql\"\u003eSELECT e FROM Employee e\nWHERE e.salary &gt; :min\nORDER BY e.name\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eJOIN / LEFT JOIN / \u003cstrong\u003eJOIN FETCH\u003c/strong\u003e (N+1 fix)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eCOUNT, AVG, SUM, MIN, MAX\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eGROUP BY ... HAVING\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eSELECT new com.x.Dto(f1, f2) FROM …\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e:named / ?positional params\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eq.setFirstResult(n).setMaxResults(m)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eq.getResultList() / getSingleResult() / executeUpdate()\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Transaction attributes","body_md":"| Attr | Has TX | No TX |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| REQUIRED | Join | Create new |\n| REQUIRES\\_NEW | Suspend + new | Create new |\n| SUPPORTS | Join | No TX |\n| NOT\\_SUPPORTED | Suspend + no TX | No TX |\n| MANDATORY | Join | Exception |\n| NEVER | Exception | No TX |\n\n**Default: REQUIRED**. System exception → auto-rollback. Application exception → NOT unless @ApplicationException(rollback=true).","body_html":"\u003ctable\u003e\n\u003cthead\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eAttr\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eHas TX\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003cth\u003eNo TX\u003c/th\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/thead\u003e\n\u003ctbody\u003e\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eREQUIRED\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eJoin\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCreate new\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eREQUIRES_NEW\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSuspend + new\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eCreate new\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSUPPORTS\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eJoin\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo TX\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNOT_SUPPORTED\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eSuspend + no TX\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo TX\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eMANDATORY\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eJoin\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eException\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003ctr\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNEVER\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eException\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003ctd\u003eNo TX\u003c/td\u003e\n\u003c/tr\u003e\n\u003c/tbody\u003e\u003c/table\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDefault: REQUIRED\u003c/strong\u003e. System exception → auto-rollback. Application exception → NOT unless @ApplicationException(rollback=true).\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"ACID","body_md":"-   **Atomic**: all-or-nothing\n-   **Consistent**: integrity preserved\n-   **Isolated**: no interference\n-   **Durable**: persists after crash","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAtomic\u003c/strong\u003e: all-or-nothing\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eConsistent\u003c/strong\u003e: integrity preserved\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIsolated\u003c/strong\u003e: no interference\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDurable\u003c/strong\u003e: persists after crash\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Security annotations","body_md":"-   @DeclareRoles({\"A\",\"B\"}) — class level\n-   @RolesAllowed({\"A\"}) — method/class\n-   @PermitAll / @DenyAll\n-   @RunAs(\"X\") — elevate for downstream\n-   ctx.isCallerInRole(\"X\") / getCallerPrincipal()","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e@DeclareRoles({&quot;A&quot;,&quot;B&quot;}) — class level\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e@RolesAllowed({&quot;A&quot;}) — method/class\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e@PermitAll / @DenyAll\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e@RunAs(&quot;X&quot;) — elevate for downstream\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ectx.isCallerInRole(&quot;X&quot;) / getCallerPrincipal()\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Entity callbacks","body_md":"On entity (no args, void): @PrePersist, @PostPersist, @PreUpdate, @PostUpdate, @PreRemove, @PostRemove, @PostLoad.\n\nExternal: @EntityListeners(X.class). Listener method takes Object (entity) param.\n\nRules: NO EntityManager calls, NO other entity access.","body_html":"\u003cp\u003eOn entity (no args, void): @PrePersist, @PostPersist, @PreUpdate, @PostUpdate, @PreRemove, @PostRemove, @PostLoad.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eExternal: @EntityListeners(X.class). Listener method takes Object (entity) param.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRules: NO EntityManager calls, NO other entity access.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"RUP Phases / Milestones","body_md":"-   **Inception** → **LCO** (vision, business case, ~10%)\n-   **Elaboration** → **LCA** (arch baseline, 80% req, ~30%)\n-   **Construction** → **IOC** (build + integrate, ~50%)\n-   **Transition** → **PR** (deploy, UAT, ~10%)","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eInception\u003c/strong\u003e → \u003cstrong\u003eLCO\u003c/strong\u003e (vision, business case, ~10%)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eElaboration\u003c/strong\u003e → \u003cstrong\u003eLCA\u003c/strong\u003e (arch baseline, 80% req, ~30%)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eConstruction\u003c/strong\u003e → \u003cstrong\u003eIOC\u003c/strong\u003e (build + integrate, ~50%)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTransition\u003c/strong\u003e → \u003cstrong\u003ePR\u003c/strong\u003e (deploy, UAT, ~10%)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"6 Best Practices","body_md":"1.  Develop iteratively\n2.  Manage requirements\n3.  Use component-based architectures\n4.  Model visually (UML)\n5.  Verify quality\n6.  Control changes","body_html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDevelop iteratively\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eManage requirements\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eUse component-based architectures\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eModel visually (UML)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eVerify quality\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eControl changes\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e"},{"heading":"9 RUP Workflows","body_md":"1.  Business Modeling\n2.  Requirements\n3.  Analysis & Design\n4.  Implementation\n5.  Test\n6.  Deployment\n7.  Config & Change Mgmt\n8.  Project Management\n9.  Environment","body_html":"\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eBusiness Modeling\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eRequirements\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAnalysis &amp; Design\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eImplementation\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTest\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eDeployment\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eConfig &amp; Change Mgmt\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eProject Management\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEnvironment\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e"},{"heading":"BCE Stereotypes","body_md":"-   **Boundary** — UI / external interface (one per actor-UC pair)\n-   **Control** — workflow orchestration (one per UC typically)\n-   **Entity** — persistent domain object\n\nSystem Analyst owns analysis model integrity.","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBoundary\u003c/strong\u003e — UI / external interface (one per actor-UC pair)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eControl\u003c/strong\u003e — workflow orchestration (one per UC typically)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEntity\u003c/strong\u003e — persistent domain object\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSystem Analyst owns analysis model integrity.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"EVMS Formulas","body_md":"-   BCWS = planned, BCWP = earned, ACWP = actual\n-   **CV = BCWP − ACWP** (+ = under budget)\n-   **SV = BCWP − BCWS** (+ = ahead)\n-   **CPI = BCWP / ACWP**, **SPI = BCWP / BCWS**\n-   **EAC = BAC / CPI**","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eBCWS = planned, BCWP = earned, ACWP = actual\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCV = BCWP − ACWP\u003c/strong\u003e (+ = under budget)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSV = BCWP − BCWS\u003c/strong\u003e (+ = ahead)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCPI = BCWP / ACWP\u003c/strong\u003e, \u003cstrong\u003eSPI = BCWP / BCWS\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eEAC = BAC / CPI\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"MBTI Quick Map","body_md":"-   **E/I**: attitude to world · Extravert = face-to-face\n-   **S/N**: perception · Intuition = new complex problems\n-   **T/F**: judging function · Feeling = fair\n-   **J/P**: outer lifestyle · Perceiving = enjoy surprises; Judging = decide quickly\n-   Perceiving functions = S + N · Judging functions = T + F","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eE/I\u003c/strong\u003e: attitude to world · Extravert = face-to-face\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eS/N\u003c/strong\u003e: perception · Intuition = new complex problems\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eT/F\u003c/strong\u003e: judging function · Feeling = fair\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eJ/P\u003c/strong\u003e: outer lifestyle · Perceiving = enjoy surprises; Judging = decide quickly\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ePerceiving functions = S + N · Judging functions = T + F\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Testing","body_md":"-   **Unit** / Integration / System / Acceptance (black-box)\n-   **Performance** = response + processing time\n-   **Load** = concurrent users · **Volume** = data size\n-   **Configuration** = different envs","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUnit\u003c/strong\u003e / Integration / System / Acceptance (black-box)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePerformance\u003c/strong\u003e = response + processing time\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLoad\u003c/strong\u003e = concurrent users · \u003cstrong\u003eVolume\u003c/strong\u003e = data size\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eConfiguration\u003c/strong\u003e = different envs\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"MDB (minimal)","body_md":"```java\n@MessageDriven(activationConfig = {\n  @ACP(propertyName=\"destinationType\",\n       propertyValue=\"javax.jms.Queue\")\n})\nclass X implements MessageListener {\n  public void onMessage(Message m){…}\n}\n```\n\nQueue = 1:1 (point-to-point); Topic = 1:many (pub-sub). Lifecycle same as SLSB.","body_html":"\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-java\"\u003e@MessageDriven(activationConfig = {\n  @ACP(propertyName=&quot;destinationType&quot;,\n       propertyValue=&quot;javax.jms.Queue&quot;)\n})\nclass X implements MessageListener {\n  public void onMessage(Message m){…}\n}\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eQueue = 1:1 (point-to-point); Topic = 1:many (pub-sub). Lifecycle same as SLSB.\u003c/p\u003e"},{"heading":"Exam-day checklist","body_md":"-   Annotate class first (@Entity), THEN members\n-   Never skip @Id\n-   MCQ: watch fake annotations (@Identity, @PrimaryKey, @InheritanceStrategy — don't exist)\n-   T/F: \"required\" vs \"optional\" — @Table is OPTIONAL\n-   Transaction attributes: memorize table rows\n-   JPQL: use DISTINCT to avoid duplicates in joins\n-   Essay: bullet outline first; partial credit is real\n-   Time budget: don't spend \u003e30 min on essays","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eAnnotate class first (@Entity), THEN members\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eNever skip @Id\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eMCQ: watch fake annotations (@Identity, @PrimaryKey, @InheritanceStrategy — don&#39;t exist)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eT/F: &quot;required&quot; vs &quot;optional&quot; — @Table is OPTIONAL\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTransaction attributes: memorize table rows\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eJPQL: use DISTINCT to avoid duplicates in joins\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eEssay: bullet outline first; partial credit is real\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTime budget: don&#39;t spend &gt;30 min on essays\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"},{"heading":"Bruce priority recap","body_md":"-   **HIGH**: 3 session beans; 7 relationships; JPQL; composite keys (2 ways); transaction attrs; ACID; MBTI; JMS queue vs topic; container concurrency locks\n-   **LOW**: 4+1 view (NOT on final), MDB details, auto-gen key specifics, Java EE Ch 18 patterns\n-   Quizzes 3+4 questions REAPPEAR on final — memorize answers","body_html":"\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHIGH\u003c/strong\u003e: 3 session beans; 7 relationships; JPQL; composite keys (2 ways); transaction attrs; ACID; MBTI; JMS queue vs topic; container concurrency locks\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLOW\u003c/strong\u003e: 4+1 view (NOT on final), MDB details, auto-gen key specifics, Java EE Ch 18 patterns\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eQuizzes 3+4 questions REAPPEAR on final — memorize answers\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e"}]}};
